00:05:44.720 --> 00:05:48.640
[Amit Varma]: Let's get straight to our reforms. What's your first reform, Shruti?

00:05:48.640 --> 00:05:55.280
[Guest 1]: This is no surprise. I think the biggest thing going on is the jobs crisis. It's very strongly

00:05:55.280 --> 00:05:59.960
[Guest 1]: linked to the economic downturn. And it's going to become more acute because of the

00:05:59.960 --> 00:06:04.400
[Guest 1]: slowdown that the economy is experiencing. So I think the very first thing that we need

00:06:04.400 --> 00:06:10.400
[Guest 1]: to do is address the fact that we have too many people entering the job market and not

00:06:10.400 --> 00:06:16.120
[Guest 1]: enough jobs to go around. And this seems to be true pretty much at every level. So just

00:06:16.120 --> 00:06:21.080
[Guest 1]: in broad terms, the country is incredibly young, right? 50% of the country is below

00:06:21.080 --> 00:06:29.120
[Guest 1]: 25 or thereabouts. And all these people are young, fresh out of school or college or whatever

00:06:29.120 --> 00:06:34.440
[Guest 1]: their skill level is, they're all looking for jobs. The numbers were about 12 to 13

00:06:34.440 --> 00:06:41.240
[Guest 1]: million people looking for jobs, plus another 6 million odd attempting to leave agriculture.

00:06:41.240 --> 00:06:46.440
[Guest 1]: And you know, so it was estimated about 20 million jobs a year. Now, because we failed

00:06:46.440 --> 00:06:52.600
[Guest 1]: to create 20 million jobs in the last five or six years, there's a further backlog, right?

00:06:52.600 --> 00:06:56.600
[Guest 1]: Because just because they didn't get a job the first year, they might be underemployed

00:06:56.600 --> 00:07:01.920
[Guest 1]: or sort of looking for employment. But those people are also sort of looking for a job.

00:07:01.920 --> 00:07:05.760
[Guest 1]: So the numbers, we don't have clear numbers on how many people are looking for a job each

00:07:05.760 --> 00:07:11.720
[Guest 1]: year, but it's about 20 million plus is a conservative estimate entering the workforce

00:07:11.720 --> 00:07:18.440
[Guest 1]: every year. And we are creating nowhere close to those number of jobs, right? And a big

00:07:18.440 --> 00:07:26.920
[Guest 1]: part of this is because the regulatory system doesn't allow easy hiring and easy firing.

00:07:26.920 --> 00:07:31.340
[Guest 1]: So the easier it is to fire someone, the easier it is to hire someone, right? So that's the

00:07:31.340 --> 00:07:39.160
[Guest 1]: biggest problem caused by the Indian sort of wage regulatory structure. Added to this

00:07:39.160 --> 00:07:45.160
[Guest 1]: is other things like you have inspection systems. So they really clamp down on industries, mostly

00:07:45.160 --> 00:07:50.520
[Guest 1]: manufacturing, where if you don't follow the labor laws, there's a host of labor inspectors

00:07:50.520 --> 00:07:56.680
[Guest 1]: who are just sort of, you know, capturing the rents coming out of this regulatory system.

00:07:56.680 --> 00:08:01.560
[Guest 1]: So they're incredibly corrupt. They make it very difficult for small firms to function.

00:08:01.560 --> 00:08:06.460
[Guest 1]: In response, the government decided to pass quite recently, maybe a couple of weeks ago,

00:08:06.460 --> 00:08:14.520
[Guest 1]: the wage code for 2019. All that the code does, to my knowledge, is compiles four previous

00:08:14.520 --> 00:08:19.440
[Guest 1]: acts, the Payment of Wages Act, the Minimum Wages Act, the Payment of Bonus Act, and Equal

00:08:19.440 --> 00:08:25.560
[Guest 1]: Renumeration Act, right? So they've just sort of done what they do best. They've given it

00:08:25.560 --> 00:08:31.320
[Guest 1]: a new name. They haven't made any real reform in making it cheaper. They've actually made

00:08:31.320 --> 00:08:36.880
[Guest 1]: it harder. They've brought in about 500 million people in India under the ambit of the code

00:08:36.880 --> 00:08:42.920
[Guest 1]: bill. And it comes with a penalty, including domestic work. And there's a penalty for not

00:08:42.920 --> 00:08:46.720
[Guest 1]: paying minimum wage, which is well above market wage. Like the minimum wage seems to have

00:08:46.720 --> 00:08:52.000
[Guest 1]: no relevance in reality to what's actually going on in the market. And there is a huge

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:59.000
[Guest 1]: penalty, both fines and criminal penalty, for not paying minimum wage. And there is

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:03.080
[Guest 1]: no enforcement mechanism. I don't know if that's good or bad. That's probably good.

00:09:03.080 --> 00:09:07.360
[Guest 1]: Because that way more people can be hired. But it also because of pernicious enforcement

00:09:07.360 --> 00:09:12.760
[Guest 1]: and arbitrary enforcement, you know, it would be harder for manufacturing units hoping to

00:09:12.760 --> 00:09:18.720
[Guest 1]: hire more people below minimum wage or something to actually go and do it. So this is the mess

00:09:18.720 --> 00:09:26.160
[Guest 1]: we're in. So what this probably requires is sort of scrapping the existing labor laws,

00:09:26.160 --> 00:09:33.200
[Guest 1]: and just really simplifying it, right? And the next is getting rid of the labor inspection

00:09:33.200 --> 00:09:39.480
[Guest 1]: system. Whatever is a problem should be solved contractually, like any other contract, right?

00:09:39.480 --> 00:09:43.760
[Guest 1]: This labor inspection system, which is sort of like the government holding a danda above

00:09:43.760 --> 00:09:51.320
[Guest 1]: every employer's head, that is really what's causing the jobs crisis problem. So this,

00:09:51.320 --> 00:09:55.960
[Guest 1]: I mean, we can talk about this a little bit more, it's very hard to do this reform, because

00:09:55.960 --> 00:10:02.240
[Guest 1]: of the unions. And there is obviously winners and losers in every reform, the unions will

00:10:02.240 --> 00:10:07.200
[Guest 1]: lose and a very vast number of people in the informal economy and those who are unemployed

00:10:07.200 --> 00:10:12.880
[Guest 1]: will gain. But the unions are well organized. And the people in the economy who are unemployed

00:10:12.880 --> 00:10:17.600
[Guest 1]: and those who in the informal economy are not organized. And that makes it very difficult

00:10:17.600 --> 00:10:20.360
[Guest 1]: to break this stronghold.

00:10:20.360 --> 00:10:23.680
[Amit Varma]: And also, is there a central law, state laws, that kind of thing?

00:10:23.680 --> 00:10:27.040
[Guest 1]: So there are state amendments. So there are a host of central laws, you know, like the

00:10:27.040 --> 00:10:33.000
[Guest 1]: Industrial Disputes Act, and so on. And each state can amend those. So some of the amendments

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:37.320
[Guest 3]: are better than some of us, like some states do better than us.

00:10:37.320 --> 00:10:41.320
[Guest 3]: Basically, there are around 44 central government laws. And there are around 200 state government

00:10:41.320 --> 00:10:47.760
[Guest 3]: laws. So basically, you know, a few years back, Amit Mitra, who now is the finance minister

00:10:47.760 --> 00:10:54.040
[Guest 3]: of West Bengal, said that, at any point of time, you might be breaking some labor law

00:10:54.040 --> 00:10:57.960
[Guest 3]: without even realizing it, because there's so many of them out there.

00:10:57.960 --> 00:11:03.840
[Guest 2]: So Shruti, I think that's an excellent point. But one question that I had is, and this is

00:11:03.840 --> 00:11:08.480
[Guest 2]: just because I'm not very well aware of this particular field, which is that, even I hear

00:11:08.480 --> 00:11:13.000
[Guest 2]: that even in the formal sector today, there's a lot of contractualization of labor that's

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:17.440
[Guest 2]: going on. And that actually took me by surprise, because I was thinking that contractualization

00:11:17.440 --> 00:11:21.080
[Guest 2]: happens more in the informal sector. But I keep hearing for the last five years, this

00:11:21.080 --> 00:11:26.000
[Guest 2]: has taken up massively in the formal sector. And I'm guessing this is obviously not optimal,

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:29.960
[Guest 2]: because you're essentially working around the laws. And this also breeds insecurity,

00:11:29.960 --> 00:11:34.560
[Guest 2]: because these workers are not getting pension payments and other kinds of benefits. So would

00:11:34.560 --> 00:11:39.600
[Guest 2]: you have any thoughts on this? And if I may also add, and this is a broader point is,

00:11:39.600 --> 00:11:44.480
[Guest 2]: I don't completely think that the jobs crisis is because of labor laws, because our labor

00:11:44.480 --> 00:11:49.480
[Guest 2]: laws have been rigid and have been complicated and have been many and scattered for a very

00:11:49.480 --> 00:11:54.320
[Guest 2]: long period of time. And the jobs crisis, essentially speaking, has been brewing over

00:11:54.320 --> 00:11:59.600
[Guest 2]: the last few years. And it has actually broken out of the thing and everybody's talking about

00:11:59.600 --> 00:12:04.800
[Guest 2]: it over the last few years. And that perhaps also has a lot to do, and as you rightly mentioned,

00:12:04.800 --> 00:12:09.560
[Guest 2]: with the economic slowdown, which is basically, there's a manufacturing sector crisis that

00:12:09.560 --> 00:12:14.080
[Guest 2]: has been also brewing for a long time, there is a credit market crisis that's happening

00:12:14.080 --> 00:12:18.800
[Guest 2]: for quite some time. And as a result, there is a demand slowdown that's happening, which

00:12:18.800 --> 00:12:23.360
[Guest 2]: is perhaps leading to a situation where, because companies are not investing, they don't feel

00:12:23.360 --> 00:12:27.960
[Guest 2]: the need to hire more workers. And because they are not hiring more workers, they're

00:12:27.960 --> 00:12:32.960
[Guest 2]: not producing enough output. And that is having a vicious cycle effect. And a related point

00:12:32.960 --> 00:12:38.680
[Guest 2]: being that not enough workers have the skills required. So there is a skilling gap and there

00:12:38.680 --> 00:12:43.240
[Guest 2]: is a so I'm guessing what I'm trying to say is there are many other factors which have

00:12:43.240 --> 00:12:47.840
[Guest 2]: probably aggravated the current jobs crisis. And of course, it is perhaps built on the

00:12:47.840 --> 00:12:50.240
[Guest 1]: base of a rigid labor law.

00:12:50.240 --> 00:12:53.600
[Guest 1]: So I think I would just add one more thing. I mean, I agree with you, we've always had

00:12:53.600 --> 00:12:59.040
[Guest 1]: bad labor laws. But what has made the effect worse and caused the glut is the demography,

00:12:59.040 --> 00:13:05.320
[Guest 1]: right? So and that is just something, it happened by chance, right? You don't control, you can

00:13:05.320 --> 00:13:11.520
[Guest 1]: control the regulatory system, it's much harder to control how the demographic dividend moves,

00:13:11.520 --> 00:13:16.440
[Guest 1]: right? And countries that have tried to control it, like China are in a total mess because

00:13:16.440 --> 00:13:21.360
[Guest 1]: of it. So one part of the glut is, we've always had terrible laws, but we never had so many

00:13:21.360 --> 00:13:27.160
[Guest 1]: people who were young and entering the workforce. So this is a bad combination of both. It's

00:13:27.160 --> 00:13:32.160
[Guest 1]: definitely, you know, we've had a jobs crisis for the last seven years. The economic slowdown

00:13:32.160 --> 00:13:37.040
[Guest 1]: is only maybe post demonetization, or maybe even last 18 months, you know, not immediately

00:13:37.040 --> 00:13:41.000
[Guest 1]: post demonetization, but I wouldn't agree, but we can debate that later. Yeah. So the

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:45.240
[Guest 1]: last, you know, 12 to 18 months, you could start hearing warning bells and people started

00:13:45.240 --> 00:13:50.080
[Guest 1]: saying, you know, things are not good, something's going on. And you know, you start getting

00:13:50.080 --> 00:13:56.000
[Guest 1]: the different warning bells from different sectors, saying, okay, the GDP numbers don't

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:02.040
[Guest 1]: quite add up to what's going on with cement, right? Today, the news last week is, it doesn't

00:14:02.040 --> 00:14:06.760
[Guest 1]: quite add up with what's going on with auto sales, right, or biscuit sales. So different

00:14:06.760 --> 00:14:12.800
[Guest 1]: sectors have sort of sent the SOS signal at different points. But we've had a demand slowdown

00:14:12.800 --> 00:14:17.080
[Guest 1]: for a while, right? And the demand slowdown definitely has an effect, you know, when people

00:14:17.080 --> 00:14:21.880
[Guest 1]: don't, and it's not just the slowdown, it's the expectation, right? When people form an

00:14:21.880 --> 00:14:25.720
[Guest 1]: expectation that demand is going to slow down further, they're even more nervous to hire

00:14:25.720 --> 00:14:30.160
[Guest 1]: employees. And that's a very large part of this contractualization that you're talking

00:14:30.160 --> 00:14:36.360
[Guest 1]: about, right? So one part of switching from long term labor contracts to this kind of,

00:14:36.360 --> 00:14:40.480
[Guest 1]: so you know, there are three versions of it. One is the very elite version, that is the

00:14:40.480 --> 00:14:46.600
[Guest 1]: Amit and Vivek version, right? They want to work for themselves, they would rather work

00:14:46.600 --> 00:14:51.880
[Guest 1]: on certain terms with different firms rather than have a single employer, and sort of clock

00:14:51.880 --> 00:14:57.200
[Guest 1]: in. So that's a very first world sort of and that those numbers are very small. The second

00:14:57.200 --> 00:15:04.960
[Guest 1]: group is where firms are trying to reduce the cost of labor, highly skilled labor to

00:15:04.960 --> 00:15:10.680
[Guest 1]: avoid paying pensions and provident funds and all the other employee benefits, right?

00:15:10.680 --> 00:15:15.100
[Guest 1]: So that you can see when there is economic distress, that's probably the first part that

00:15:15.100 --> 00:15:18.280
[Guest 1]: gets cut, because you don't want to lose the skilled labor, which is already scarce in

00:15:18.280 --> 00:15:23.000
[Guest 1]: India. And at the same time, there is some cost cutting that goes on. And then the third

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:29.960
[Guest 1]: part is this kind of contractualization caused by uncertainty. We don't know if things are

00:15:29.960 --> 00:15:33.440
[Guest 1]: going to get worse, right? We just laid off six people, we don't know if we need to lay

00:15:33.440 --> 00:15:39.760
[Guest 1]: off 10 more people. So let's just sort of, you know, rework because it is hard, you know,

00:15:39.760 --> 00:15:45.400
[Guest 1]: we think of firing workers as sort of stroke of a pen thing, right? But when you're inside

00:15:45.400 --> 00:15:50.720
[Guest 1]: working within a firm, these are real people. It's difficult to fire and burn bridges, and

00:15:50.720 --> 00:15:56.320
[Guest 1]: then it's hard to hire them back when things are going well. So these sorts of arrangements

00:15:56.320 --> 00:16:00.600
[Guest 1]: are a product of we really want to hold on to skilled labor, and yet, we want to deal

00:16:00.600 --> 00:16:06.760
[Guest 1]: with the uncertainty. So I think broadly, you're right, it's not just a labor law issue.

00:16:06.760 --> 00:16:12.480
[Guest 1]: But that really, you know, that's the scaffolding that stifles everything else, you know, nothing

00:16:12.480 --> 00:16:14.760
[Guest 1]: can expand past that.

00:16:14.760 --> 00:16:20.960
[Guest 3]: So I mean, talking about contract workers. So you look at a company like Maruti, and

00:16:20.960 --> 00:16:25.400
[Guest 3]: I mean, from what I remember, half of their workers are contract workers, and half of

00:16:25.400 --> 00:16:31.040
[Guest 3]: the workers are employees. So on the same, you know, floor, assembly floor, you might

00:16:31.040 --> 00:16:34.920
[Guest 3]: have a situation where there are two people doing exactly the same thing. But one guy

00:16:34.920 --> 00:16:39.760
[Guest 3]: because he's employed, might end up making probably twice or, you know, two and a half

00:16:39.760 --> 00:16:44.720
[Guest 3]: times the guy who's on contract. So that's, and if you remember, there was a lot of violence

00:16:44.720 --> 00:16:51.120
[Guest 3]: in the Gurgaon belt, a few years back in an HR manager was burnt by the Maruti by not

00:16:51.120 --> 00:16:57.280
[Guest 3]: not at Maruti, this was at one of these auto ancillaries. So that's one point. The second

00:16:57.280 --> 00:17:04.240
[Guest 3]: point about, you know, I find this term demographic dividend very, very funny. A dividend, I know,

00:17:04.240 --> 00:17:10.880
[Guest 3]: we are assuming that there is a dividend already, it may not be a dividend, it might be a disaster

00:17:10.880 --> 00:17:15.680
[Guest 3]: as well, which is what it is turning out to be. The third point is, I mean, demographic

00:17:15.680 --> 00:17:20.800
[Guest 3]: dividend at a very simple level is that our parents basically produced way too many kids,

00:17:20.800 --> 00:17:27.200
[Guest 3]: right? On 15th August, I think the Prime Minister when he made his Independence Day speech talked

00:17:27.200 --> 00:17:32.300
[Guest 3]: about population and the need to control it. And you know, this is a huge misconception

00:17:32.300 --> 00:17:37.960
[Guest 3]: that people have, that India's population continues to grow, which is not really true.

00:17:37.960 --> 00:17:42.000
[Amit Varma]: This is one of my reforms. If it's not one of your reforms, stop right now. No, what

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:49.280
[Guest 3]: I'm trying to say is that, you know, the replacement rate is 2.1, whereas India's fertility rate,

00:17:49.280 --> 00:17:55.920
[Guest 3]: you know, which is the average number of children a woman has is 2.3. So once you take the infant

00:17:55.920 --> 00:17:59.960
[Guest 3]: mortality rate in India's case, which is anyway very high into account, so we are more or

00:17:59.960 --> 00:18:03.440
[Guest 3]: less at the replacement rate. And many states in India, I mean, if you look at states like

00:18:03.440 --> 00:18:11.800
[Guest 3]: Kerala, West Bengal, Tamil Nadu, are now not producing, you know, kids at the replacement

00:18:11.800 --> 00:18:16.840
[Guest 3]: rate. So their population over a period of time will start to contract. Now, it's states

00:18:16.840 --> 00:18:22.520
[Guest 3]: like Bihar, UP, Madhya Pradesh, Rajasthan, you know, the original Bimaru states, where

00:18:22.520 --> 00:18:28.280
[Guest 3]: the rates continue to be high. Now, as the medical facilities improve, and as more women

00:18:28.280 --> 00:18:31.360
[Guest 3]: get educated, I mean, this is bound to come down.

00:18:31.360 --> 00:18:33.200
[Amit Varma]: Let's move on to your first reform.

00:18:33.200 --> 00:18:40.320
[Guest 3]: Okay, so I just wanted to sort of, before I get into the reform, I wanted to sort of

00:18:40.320 --> 00:18:45.200
[Guest 3]: make a long, long disclaimer. So you know, what happens is when you and I, I mean, you

00:18:45.200 --> 00:18:49.920
[Guest 3]: know, given that we are so active on the social media, one of the things that sort of gets

00:18:49.920 --> 00:18:57.200
[Guest 3]: thrown off thrown at us all the time is, you know, problem, problem, solution. Now, the

00:18:57.200 --> 00:19:01.800
[Guest 3]: first thing is, you know, how do you come up with a solution without identifying the

00:19:01.800 --> 00:19:07.480
[Guest 3]: problem? I mean, that's as basic as it gets. But having said that, you know, this entire

00:19:07.480 --> 00:19:13.720
[Guest 3]: Indian tendency to sort of, you know, solution, but I think comes from the fact that when

00:19:13.720 --> 00:19:19.000
[Guest 3]: we, you know, write our exams, when we grow up, a lot of the, in fact, most of the questions

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:24.320
[Guest 3]: have a right answer or a wrong answer. Okay. And that's primarily because of our focus

00:19:24.320 --> 00:19:30.040
[Guest 3]: on science and maths and so on. And we look down upon subjects like history and geography

00:19:30.040 --> 00:19:36.520
[Guest 3]: where. So, you know, so because of that, what happens is, this solution thing is very, very

00:19:36.520 --> 00:19:41.680
[Guest 3]: strong, and which is what we're doing here today. Now, one of the things that I realized

00:19:41.680 --> 00:19:48.880
[Guest 3]: while writing my, you know, book, last book, India's Big Government was that over the years,

00:19:48.880 --> 00:19:53.960
[Guest 3]: the government of India has constituted lots of committees on lots of issues. And all those

00:19:53.960 --> 00:20:00.160
[Guest 3]: committees have come up with recommendations and solutions. Or another, you know, that

00:20:00.160 --> 00:20:05.960
[Guest 3]: you have so many economists and experts working for the government. They also write regularly

00:20:05.960 --> 00:20:13.120
[Guest 3]: in publications, I mean, which the government sort of brings out. Now, what has happened

00:20:13.120 --> 00:20:17.800
[Guest 3]: is that, you know, if you to give you a very, very simple example, now look at the banking

00:20:17.800 --> 00:20:23.160
[Guest 3]: crisis currently, if you were to sort of go back to 1991, there was a Narasimhan committee,

00:20:23.160 --> 00:20:26.560
[Guest 3]: the first Narasimhan committee, as they call it, I mean, all the solutions are there in

00:20:26.560 --> 00:20:31.440
[Guest 3]: that report. And if you look at, you know, various social and economic problems that

00:20:31.440 --> 00:20:36.640
[Guest 3]: we've had, and, and the committees that were constituted to tackle them, those reports

00:20:36.640 --> 00:20:41.720
[Guest 3]: have all those solutions already. Okay, so it's not like the government does not know

00:20:41.720 --> 00:20:48.040
[Guest 3]: what is to be done. All they need to do is if you have a problem, just pick out the last

00:20:48.040 --> 00:20:52.080
[Guest 3]: report and go ahead and implement it. But obviously, you know, these solutions have

00:20:52.080 --> 00:20:56.640
[Guest 3]: not been implemented. I mean, even when a committee's solutions, recommendations are

00:20:56.640 --> 00:21:01.640
[Guest 3]: taken on, they're diluted to a large extent, and then they are pushed through. So the long

00:21:01.640 --> 00:21:05.480
[Guest 3]: and the short of it is that the government knows what is to be done. And this is not

00:21:05.480 --> 00:21:10.760
[Guest 3]: just the current government, or the central government, I mean, includes the state governments,

00:21:10.760 --> 00:21:13.960
[Guest 3]: the governments at the municipal level, but they don't do it.

00:21:13.960 --> 00:21:18.880
[Amit Varma]: I think if all governments are dissolved in water, you'll have a very interesting solution.

00:21:18.880 --> 00:21:29.880
[Guest 3]: Bad joke. So my point is, you know, it's, it's like, so I mean, since you were talking

00:21:29.880 --> 00:21:35.480
[Guest 3]: about the fact that, you know, to give references, so before I sort of, you know, early, you

00:21:35.480 --> 00:21:40.560
[Guest 3]: know, even though I'm an atheist, I like listening to bhajans, particularly by this gentleman

00:21:40.560 --> 00:21:44.800
[Guest 3]: called Hari Omsharan, because I sort of grew up, I mean, if you grew up anywhere in North

00:21:44.800 --> 00:21:51.680
[Guest 3]: or East India, you know, his voice was very, very, sort of, you know, I mean, you used

00:21:51.680 --> 00:21:55.400
[Guest 3]: to listen to it every morning, because that is all the temples would play. I mean, this

00:21:55.400 --> 00:22:01.640
[Guest 3]: is before, no, so this is before Gulshan Kumar and T-Series took over the game, and the bhajans

00:22:01.640 --> 00:22:05.000
[Guest 3]: basically became film tunes. So, yeah.

00:22:05.000 --> 00:22:07.080
[Guest 3]: And the film tunes also became jagrata tunes.

00:22:07.080 --> 00:22:12.240
[Guest 3]: Yeah, I mean, yeah, both of them. So, so, so basically, so this, this, the line from

00:22:12.240 --> 00:22:18.320
[Guest 3]: this bhajan is ki, man maila aur tan ko dhoye. So, the economic, you know, inference here

00:22:18.320 --> 00:22:24.240
[Guest 3]: is that, you know, you keep tackling the symptom without looking at the problem. So, in the

00:22:24.240 --> 00:22:25.240
[Guest 3]: current situation,

00:22:25.240 --> 00:22:28.720
[Amit Varma]: Or it could also mean, man maila aur tan ko dhoye, could also mean that you're really

00:22:28.720 --> 00:22:30.840
[Amit Varma]: a perv, but you're virtue signalling on Twitter.

00:22:30.840 --> 00:22:35.760
[Guest 3]: I don't know what that means. So, so, virtue signalling is like, I mean,

00:22:35.760 --> 00:22:44.040
[Guest 3]: So, look at the current situation, you know, you talk to a corporate, you talk to an economist,

00:22:44.040 --> 00:22:48.440
[Guest 3]: and everyone's like, interest rates should be cut, interest rates should be cut. I mean,

00:22:48.440 --> 00:22:52.440
[Guest 3]: what will happen, you know, if the home loan is not at, you know, let's say, 8%, and it's

00:22:52.440 --> 00:22:57.680
[Guest 3]: at seven and a half? I mean, how will that help in any way? So, this is like, you know,

00:22:57.680 --> 00:23:01.800
[Guest 3]: you're just looking at the symptom that people are probably not borrowing. So, just cut interest

00:23:01.800 --> 00:23:07.720
[Guest 3]: rates. But you are not looking at why is it that people are not borrowing. So, anyway,

00:23:07.720 --> 00:23:15.200
[Guest 3]: so that was the long disclaimer, ki kuch hona nahi hai, but still, since we are here, we

00:23:15.200 --> 00:23:20.600
[Guest 3]: need to do our jobs properly. So, the first thing I sort of wanted to talk about is, and

00:23:20.600 --> 00:23:24.880
[Guest 3]: this is something a little, it's not really an, you know, I wouldn't call it an economic

00:23:24.880 --> 00:23:30.880
[Guest 3]: reform, but it's more of a reform in education. Now, what has happened over the years, over

00:23:30.880 --> 00:23:36.120
[Guest 3]: the last 70 years is that even, you know, the government has essentially paid a lot

00:23:36.120 --> 00:23:41.600
[Guest 3]: of attention on higher education. But the long and the short of it is that our primary

00:23:41.600 --> 00:23:45.800
[Guest 3]: education system is basically pretty much screwed up. And it's been screwed up even

00:23:45.800 --> 00:23:50.000
[Guest 3]: more after the right to education was put in place, which we have discussed in an episode.

00:23:50.000 --> 00:23:54.400
[Guest 3]: We have, yeah. So, one of the key clauses in right to education, I mean, if you read

00:23:54.400 --> 00:23:59.840
[Guest 3]: the Bear Act, is that the teacher has to complete the syllabus. Okay. Now, because of this,

00:23:59.840 --> 00:24:06.040
[Guest 3]: what happens is that, you know, students who come to school at a young age and come from

00:24:06.040 --> 00:24:10.300
[Guest 3]: a very reading deficient background tend to lose out because the teacher is essentially

00:24:10.300 --> 00:24:14.640
[Guest 3]: interested in completing the syllabus. And because of that, he ends up, he or she ends

00:24:14.640 --> 00:24:18.800
[Guest 3]: up concentrating only on the best students in the class who are picking up stuff. That's

00:24:18.800 --> 00:24:21.960
[Guest 3]: the first part of the problem. The second part of the problem is that there are no exams

00:24:21.960 --> 00:24:26.240
[Guest 3]: till class eight. So, irrespective of whether you are learning or not, you keep getting

00:24:26.240 --> 00:24:31.960
[Guest 3]: promoted and you reach class eight. Now, what has happened is in 2018 and 2019, you know,

00:24:31.960 --> 00:24:38.320
[Guest 3]: the first batch of RTE students who started in, you know, lower KG or preparatory or whatever

00:24:38.320 --> 00:24:43.960
[Guest 3]: you call it, in 2010, have now reached a stage where they have to write exams and they have

00:24:43.960 --> 00:24:48.560
[Guest 3]: never written exams in their life. So, this is the new crisis which is brewing and the

00:24:48.560 --> 00:24:53.640
[Guest 3]: parents don't know, even those who sort of, you know, belong to the well-off categories

00:24:53.640 --> 00:24:59.520
[Guest 3]: as to what to do with this. I mean, if a student has never written exams. So, my thing is that

00:24:59.520 --> 00:25:04.120
[Guest 3]: this is a problem that needs to be tackled seriously. And it's not about throwing more

00:25:04.120 --> 00:25:09.560
[Guest 3]: money at, you know, as a lot of people keep saying, and that includes me, that the government

00:25:09.560 --> 00:25:13.600
[Guest 3]: doesn't spend enough money on education. But you have to look at the situation a little

00:25:13.600 --> 00:25:18.440
[Guest 3]: more creatively. So, one solution, because, you know, which is what we all love, is something

00:25:18.440 --> 00:25:25.960
[Guest 3]: that, you know, Abhijit Banerjee, who's a famous economist at MIT, he shared with me

00:25:25.960 --> 00:25:31.240
[Guest 3]: many years back, and he talked about how they had carried out a small experiment in Bihar,

00:25:31.240 --> 00:25:36.040
[Guest 3]: in schools in Bihar, where they had hired teachers who were given contract teachers

00:25:36.040 --> 00:25:41.680
[Guest 3]: who were trained for two weeks. And then these guys went and taught in all these schools.

00:25:41.680 --> 00:25:48.360
[Guest 3]: And they had a very clear motive, as in, they didn't have to complete the syllabus, what

00:25:48.360 --> 00:25:52.080
[Guest 3]: they had to do is they had to ensure that if a student couldn't read, he had to be taught

00:25:52.080 --> 00:25:57.480
[Guest 3]: to read. If he couldn't write, he had to be taught to write. And if he couldn't do basic

00:25:57.480 --> 00:26:03.360
[Guest 3]: maths, plus minus, he had to be taught that. And when they sort of went back and, you know,

00:26:03.360 --> 00:26:08.080
[Guest 3]: you do a study, and you have a control group, and you know, you do all that. And when they

00:26:08.080 --> 00:26:13.720
[Guest 3]: sort of measured it, they found that the method, at least in the experiment, really helped.

00:26:13.720 --> 00:26:19.120
[Guest 3]: So you have to look at the entire problem from a very, very lateral point of view.

00:26:19.120 --> 00:26:20.120
[Guest 1]: So,

00:26:20.120 --> 00:26:24.680
[Guest 1]: I would just add a couple more things to Vivek. He's absolutely right. The RT is a total mess.

00:26:24.680 --> 00:26:30.760
[Guest 1]: It has a schedule at the back. Okay. And one of the things that the act says is, you know,

00:26:30.760 --> 00:26:35.840
[Guest 1]: every school must have this list of things. And if you look at those things, all of them

00:26:35.840 --> 00:26:41.900
[Guest 1]: are inputs. You know, so clearly these people, so Alex Tabarrok, and I have written some

00:26:41.900 --> 00:26:49.440
[Guest 1]: work on what Lantridge calls isomorphic mimicry, right? So this is basically you go to Denmark

00:26:49.440 --> 00:26:53.480
[Guest 1]: or something, you know, you go to the United States, you look around and you're like, what

00:26:53.480 --> 00:26:59.160
[Guest 1]: does a good school look like? Oh, a good school has large, airy classrooms, chalo, large,

00:26:59.160 --> 00:27:05.720
[Guest 1]: airy classrooms, right? So a good school has such and such teacher to pupil ratio, right?

00:27:05.720 --> 00:27:11.080
[Guest 1]: A good school has bathroom facilities, a good school has a separate kitchen area, a good

00:27:11.080 --> 00:27:15.840
[Guest 1]: school has a playground, which is at least 40 meters by 20 meters. So they make a note

00:27:15.840 --> 00:27:20.080
[Guest 1]: of all this, right? So when the government asked them, and this is where I disagree a

00:27:20.080 --> 00:27:26.680
[Guest 1]: little bit with Vivek, I think there is some knowledge crisis also in the government. They,

00:27:26.680 --> 00:27:31.720
[Guest 1]: the things they know are not the right things to know, right? So they're like, we know what

00:27:31.720 --> 00:27:36.620
[Guest 1]: a good school looks like. This is what a good school looks like. And if you fundamentally

00:27:36.620 --> 00:27:42.520
[Guest 1]: think education should be mandated top down, then it's easier to mandate inputs than outcomes,

00:27:42.520 --> 00:27:49.360
[Guest 1]: right? Because outcomes mean you'll have to be tested. And then so it is not a coincidence

00:27:49.360 --> 00:27:54.640
[Guest 1]: that these kids are not tested until eighth standard, right? We like to think they just

00:27:54.640 --> 00:27:59.440
[Guest 1]: kind of forgot and said no child left behind. No child left behind is also an American and

00:27:59.440 --> 00:28:00.440
[Guest 1]: foreign import.

00:28:00.440 --> 00:28:02.680
[Guest 1]: There are exams there. It's not like there are no exams.

00:28:02.680 --> 00:28:07.800
[Guest 1]: There are exams. So the fact that there are, it's completely devoid of any outcomes, you

00:28:07.800 --> 00:28:14.200
[Guest 1]: know, you see that schedule, there's not one single outcome, right? Now, all these economists,

00:28:14.200 --> 00:28:19.080
[Guest 1]: including some of these, you know, very fine, eminent MIT economists, and so on.

00:28:19.080 --> 00:28:21.720
[Guest 3]: She doesn't like Banerjee and Duflo, which is what she's saying.

00:28:21.720 --> 00:28:25.840
[Guest 1]: No, that's not true. I actually very, they've written a lovely book called Poor Economics.

00:28:25.840 --> 00:28:31.200
[Guest 1]: I strongly recommend it. But one of the things that has come out of the, of the halls of

00:28:31.200 --> 00:28:37.920
[Guest 1]: MIT is this randomized control trial business, right? So these people now come and measure

00:28:37.920 --> 00:28:41.200
[Guest 1]: and what is measurable is inputs, right?

00:28:41.200 --> 00:28:46.920
[Guest 1]: So as Vivek pointed out, one of the things is the teacher needs to complete the syllabus.

00:28:46.920 --> 00:28:51.440
[Guest 1]: Another thing is that the teacher is a union employee, right? They get paid a lot of money,

00:28:51.440 --> 00:28:55.720
[Guest 1]: whether they show up or not. So what all these people found was all these schools are there,

00:28:55.720 --> 00:28:59.400
[Guest 1]: they have the correct size window, they have a bathroom, they have a kitchen, they have

00:28:59.400 --> 00:29:02.520
[Guest 1]: a playground, but the teachers don't show up.

00:29:02.520 --> 00:29:07.800
[Guest 1]: So all there are like RCTs, one after the other, which are trying to figure out how

00:29:07.800 --> 00:29:13.680
[Guest 1]: to reduce teacher absenteeism, right? And we've kind of forgotten the point. The point

00:29:13.680 --> 00:29:19.360
[Guest 1]: of the schooling was not that the teacher shows up, it was that the students learn.

00:29:19.360 --> 00:29:25.160
[Guest 1]: We assume that the teacher showing up is instrumental to the student learning, right? But that was

00:29:25.160 --> 00:29:30.960
[Guest 1]: not our end goal. So these people have really confused what the end goal is. They think

00:29:30.960 --> 00:29:37.360
[Guest 1]: end goal is delivery of inputs by the state. The end goal is actually that students need

00:29:37.360 --> 00:29:40.720
[Guest 1]: to know how to write their name by the time they're in second standard, and they need

00:29:40.720 --> 00:29:45.160
[Guest 1]: to know how to do arithmetic by fifth standard, and they need to be able to take an exam.

00:29:45.160 --> 00:29:50.800
[Guest 1]: So I think there is much more wrong with the RT and Vivek was actually being very, very

00:29:50.800 --> 00:29:55.000
[Guest 1]: generous and kind to the education bureaucrats.

00:29:55.000 --> 00:29:58.920
[Guest 2]: So I would completely agree with Shruti. First of all, I really like the point about isomorphic

00:29:58.920 --> 00:30:03.880
[Guest 2]: mimicry because I think that applies not just in education, but in many other areas of so-called

00:30:03.880 --> 00:30:08.200
[Guest 2]: public sector reforms that we just see somewhere, something very nice and shiny. And we think

00:30:08.200 --> 00:30:11.680
[Guest 2]: if we transplant that to India, it will work like a miracle. And we do exactly that. And

00:30:11.680 --> 00:30:16.200
[Guest 2]: we don't really, that's a hollow structure and we don't do anything inside. And I think

00:30:16.200 --> 00:30:19.960
[Guest 2]: this input and outcome thing that Shruti mentioned, I would just put a little bit more structure

00:30:19.960 --> 00:30:25.560
[Guest 2]: to it. So the way I look at it, it is basically input, output, outcome. So there are some

00:30:25.560 --> 00:30:30.440
[Guest 2]: inputs that you're putting in to reform any particular sector of the economy or the state,

00:30:30.440 --> 00:30:34.720
[Guest 2]: then you need to measure what is the output. Let's say in this particular example, how

00:30:34.720 --> 00:30:39.800
[Guest 2]: many students are graduating in a particular class, or how many boys versus girls. So these

00:30:39.800 --> 00:30:44.760
[Guest 2]: are the tangible outputs that you can measure. And it is very important for any reform to

00:30:44.760 --> 00:30:49.720
[Guest 2]: have this tangible output measure, not just looking at the input. And the final thing,

00:30:49.720 --> 00:30:53.920
[Guest 2]: which is very important is the outcome, that not only are you graduating a certain number

00:30:53.920 --> 00:30:58.400
[Guest 2]: of boys and girls, but what is it they're really learning. The learning is the outcome

00:30:58.400 --> 00:31:02.040
[Guest 2]: and the output is the students going from one class to the other or leaving the school

00:31:02.040 --> 00:31:06.280
[Guest 2]: or more students coming in. And the input would be the infrastructure, the teachers.

00:31:06.280 --> 00:31:11.560
[Guest 2]: Unless we design all our reforms in this kind of a structure, we'll just keep doing that

00:31:11.560 --> 00:31:15.160
[Guest 2]: isomorphic mimicry and we'll keep building the inputs, but then there'll be absolutely

00:31:15.160 --> 00:31:19.080
[Guest 2]: no evaluation of the output and the outcome, which is I think what ends up happening. And

00:31:19.080 --> 00:31:26.520
[Guest 2]: I have one more point to what Vivek's disclaimer was. I think it's absolutely fine to have

00:31:26.520 --> 00:31:32.240
[Guest 2]: committees and committee reports. And that's the way a lot of governments function. And

00:31:32.240 --> 00:31:37.360
[Guest 2]: I think the problem that happens in the implementation of the committee recommendations is a vast

00:31:37.360 --> 00:31:42.960
[Guest 2]: black box called political economy. I mean, economists will recommend whatever we want

00:31:42.960 --> 00:31:47.440
[Guest 2]: to recommend. And like in the banking example that you gave, right? I mean, when 70% of

00:31:47.440 --> 00:31:51.440
[Guest 2]: the banking sector is owned by the government, and the banks are regulated, it's not true

00:31:51.440 --> 00:31:58.360
[Guest 3]: anymore. It is. No, it's not. It is. No, it's not. As of March 2019, 63% of loans in India

00:31:58.360 --> 00:32:02.480
[Guest 3]: were given by public sector banks, and they had only 58% of the deposits. So even if I

00:32:02.480 --> 00:32:08.000
[Guest 3]: take 60%, the majority of the banking sector is still owned by the government. But that

00:32:08.000 --> 00:32:12.680
[Guest 3]: is changing. And in the next five years, you will have public sector banks. But till now,

00:32:12.680 --> 00:32:16.480
[Guest 2]: all the problems that have happened in the banking sector, look at the NPA, 90% of the

00:32:16.480 --> 00:32:20.320
[Guest 2]: NPAs are in the public sector banks, not in the private banks, right? And if these banks

00:32:20.320 --> 00:32:25.720
[Guest 2]: are owned by the government, and they're regulated by an agent of the government, it's like the

00:32:25.720 --> 00:32:29.720
[Guest 2]: agent is regulating the principle, it's never going to work no matter what committees are

00:32:29.720 --> 00:32:34.080
[Guest 2]: recommending. So I think committee recommendation is somewhere and the political economy of

00:32:34.080 --> 00:32:35.080
[Guest 3]: the state is somewhere else.

00:32:35.080 --> 00:32:38.880
[Guest 3]: So it's like, you know, we talk about what are the structural factors, you know, this

00:32:38.880 --> 00:32:43.680
[Guest 3]: is the new, you know, not a new jargon, but it's sort of come back.

00:32:43.680 --> 00:32:47.880
[Amit Varma]: It's new for you, you're learning. It's not new for me. There's something called a structural

00:32:47.880 --> 00:32:48.880
[Unknown]: slowdown.

00:32:48.880 --> 00:32:56.240
[Unknown]: We're recording this, by the way, on August 23rd.

00:32:56.240 --> 00:32:57.640
[Guest 3]: It is not a cyclical slowdown.

00:32:57.640 --> 00:33:02.440
[Guest 3]: I have to write a column on this for Dainik Jagran after I'm out of here. So whether it's

00:33:02.440 --> 00:33:04.480
[Guest 3]: a cyclical slowdown or a structural slowdown.

00:33:04.480 --> 00:33:05.720
[Guest 2]: What's the Hindi of structural slowdown?

00:33:05.720 --> 00:33:06.720
[Amit Varma]: That I'll figure out.

00:33:06.720 --> 00:33:07.720
[Amit Varma]: Okay, these are digressions.

00:33:07.720 --> 00:33:12.760
[Guest 3]: Google Translate. No, so what I was saying was, so the biggest structural problem are

00:33:12.760 --> 00:33:14.900
[Guest 3]: basically the politicians.

00:33:14.900 --> 00:33:16.720
[Guest 3]: So and what do you do about them?

00:33:16.720 --> 00:33:22.240
[Guest 3]: So which is where all these committee reports get confined to the dustbins of history and

00:33:22.240 --> 00:33:27.480
[Guest 3]: you know, then people like me dig it out to sort of read and make a living.

00:33:27.480 --> 00:33:32.120
[Guest 1]: You know, I agree with you, but I also disagree with you a little bit.

00:33:32.120 --> 00:33:39.080
[Guest 1]: We have this whole input, output, outcome business only in government, right?

00:33:39.080 --> 00:33:44.400
[Guest 1]: So if government is in the business of making bread, like it used to own Modern Bakery,

00:33:44.400 --> 00:33:45.400
[Guest 1]: not that long ago.

00:33:45.400 --> 00:33:47.240
[Guest 1]: In my living memory, it used to own Modern Bakery.

00:33:47.240 --> 00:33:49.360
[Guest 3]: Yeah, we've all grown up eating modern bread.

00:33:49.360 --> 00:33:50.360
[Guest 1]: It's disgusting.

00:33:50.360 --> 00:33:52.960
[Guest 1]: It's like one step above cardboard, right?

00:33:52.960 --> 00:33:56.120
[Guest 1]: So there is the input that goes into making bread.

00:33:56.120 --> 00:34:00.040
[Guest 1]: Then there is the output, how many slices of bread or how many kilos or how many loaves

00:34:00.040 --> 00:34:01.780
[Guest 1]: of bread, so on and so forth.

00:34:01.780 --> 00:34:05.160
[Guest 1]: And then there's the outcome, which is vomit, okay?

00:34:05.160 --> 00:34:10.640
[Guest 1]: So that's how we evaluate government made bread.

00:34:10.640 --> 00:34:15.300
[Guest 1]: How do we evaluate just bread, right?

00:34:15.300 --> 00:34:18.420
[Guest 1]: We go to the market, we pick the bread we like, right?

00:34:18.420 --> 00:34:19.700
[Guest 1]: You vote with your money.

00:34:19.700 --> 00:34:24.920
[Guest 1]: The more number of people think this is good quality bread at a particular price.

00:34:24.920 --> 00:34:32.600
[Guest 1]: So now when you're in the business of government controlling education, then we have to slice

00:34:32.600 --> 00:34:36.280
[Guest 1]: and dice and then that system can be gamed, right?

00:34:36.280 --> 00:34:39.120
[Guest 1]: Then we can make the outcome how many kids are graduating.

00:34:39.120 --> 00:34:41.360
[Guest 2]: So then the problem goes even more fundamental.

00:34:41.360 --> 00:34:42.360
[Guest 2]: Exactly.

00:34:42.360 --> 00:34:45.400
[Guest 1]: Is it the government's business to be in education?

00:34:45.400 --> 00:34:46.400
[Amit Varma]: Which is one of my reforms.

00:34:46.400 --> 00:34:48.560
[Amit Varma]: No, actually, that's not the appropriate question.

00:34:48.560 --> 00:34:53.120
[Guest 1]: I think the appropriate question is, is it the government's business to be in education

00:34:53.120 --> 00:34:54.920
[Guest 1]: to the exclusion of everyone else?

00:34:54.920 --> 00:34:56.400
[Amit Varma]: Okay, may I butt in here?

00:34:56.400 --> 00:34:57.400
[Guest 1]: Right.

00:34:57.400 --> 00:34:59.080
[Guest 1]: The government wants to eliminate competition.

00:34:59.080 --> 00:35:04.800
[Amit Varma]: I'll butt in here because this is one of my reforms and therefore I will ask you to wait

00:35:04.800 --> 00:35:08.280
[Amit Varma]: a little bit and we will change the order and I will get this reform over with.

00:35:08.280 --> 00:35:12.520
[Amit Varma]: So my reform basically is that we allow schools for profit.

00:35:12.520 --> 00:35:15.440
[Amit Varma]: Now I want to set a little bit of context here.

00:35:15.440 --> 00:35:20.240
[Amit Varma]: What really happened in the 50s and 60s was that we had a mindset that private enterprise

00:35:20.240 --> 00:35:21.240
[Amit Varma]: was bad.

00:35:21.240 --> 00:35:25.540
[Amit Varma]: Jawaharlal Nehru famously said to JRD Tata, do not speak to me of profit.

00:35:25.540 --> 00:35:27.720
[Amit Varma]: Profit is a dirty word, stop quote.

00:35:27.720 --> 00:35:31.240
[Amit Varma]: And as a result of that, there was a sense that there are some sectors of the economy

00:35:31.240 --> 00:35:34.360
[Amit Varma]: which are too important to leave to the private sector.

00:35:34.360 --> 00:35:35.760
[Amit Varma]: The government has to do them.

00:35:35.760 --> 00:35:38.440
[Amit Varma]: And one of them, of course, was education.

00:35:38.440 --> 00:35:40.840
[Amit Varma]: And there were a lot of sectors which were part of this.

00:35:40.840 --> 00:35:46.200
[Amit Varma]: And what really happened with liberalization is that some of the sectors in which the government

00:35:46.200 --> 00:35:50.640
[Amit Varma]: was controlling and there wasn't much private participation, were basically opened up.

00:35:50.640 --> 00:35:56.040
[Amit Varma]: For example, if you remember, back in the 80s, you know, you could only fly Air India

00:35:56.040 --> 00:35:59.040
[Amit Varma]: or Indian Airlines, they were prohibitively expensive.

00:35:59.040 --> 00:36:02.600
[Amit Varma]: If you wanted a telephone, you had a five year waiting list, all of that, telecom got

00:36:02.600 --> 00:36:04.680
[Amit Varma]: opened up, airlines got opened up.

00:36:04.680 --> 00:36:08.120
[Amit Varma]: And instantly, you know, we can see the difference all around us.

00:36:08.120 --> 00:36:11.040
[Amit Varma]: Today, a phone is accessible to anyone.

00:36:11.040 --> 00:36:14.020
[Amit Varma]: And far more people can afford to fly than was the case earlier.

00:36:14.020 --> 00:36:19.280
[Amit Varma]: The problem with education is that we haven't allowed schools for profit.

00:36:19.280 --> 00:36:25.700
[Amit Varma]: And what that does with not necessarily debarring them, but with a host of regulations like

00:36:25.700 --> 00:36:29.960
[Amit Varma]: your playground has to be this size and blah, blah, blah, and it just becomes almost impossible

00:36:29.960 --> 00:36:33.640
[Amit Varma]: to run a school for profit.

00:36:33.640 --> 00:36:37.800
[Amit Varma]: And a lot of private schools that exist do jugars with trusts and all of that.

00:36:37.800 --> 00:36:42.560
[Amit Varma]: And the result of that is that the amount of choice that is available for parents goes

00:36:42.560 --> 00:36:44.280
[Amit Varma]: down massively.

00:36:44.280 --> 00:36:47.920
[Amit Varma]: And what you see across the country is people have this impression that private schools

00:36:47.920 --> 00:36:50.000
[Amit Varma]: are just very expensive.

00:36:50.000 --> 00:36:51.000
[Amit Varma]: And they're only for the elites.

00:36:51.000 --> 00:36:52.280
[Amit Varma]: That's not at all true.

00:36:52.280 --> 00:36:57.560
[Amit Varma]: What you see across the country is you have budget private schools opening up in slums.

00:36:57.560 --> 00:37:00.920
[Amit Varma]: James Tully has written a book on this, I forget the name, and there have been studies

00:37:00.920 --> 00:37:03.220
[Amit Varma]: by the Center for Civil Society.

00:37:03.220 --> 00:37:08.480
[Amit Varma]: And we know from Delhi, Hyderabad, Chennai, that you have situations where schools open

00:37:08.480 --> 00:37:15.160
[Amit Varma]: up impromptu in the slums, and like, poor parents like domestic help and auto rickshaw

00:37:15.160 --> 00:37:20.400
[Amit Varma]: drivers and so on, prefer to pay 100 bucks or 200 bucks a month to send their kid to

00:37:20.400 --> 00:37:23.120
[Amit Varma]: that school rather than to a free government school.

00:37:23.120 --> 00:37:27.120
[Amit Varma]: Now, they're basically voting with their feet, which is as it should be, and which is how

00:37:27.120 --> 00:37:31.160
[Amit Varma]: people choose bread, for example, by voting with their wallets.

00:37:31.160 --> 00:37:35.720
[Amit Varma]: And I am often mischaracterized for saying that the government should get out of education,

00:37:35.720 --> 00:37:37.600
[Amit Varma]: what will happen there, which is not my case at all.

00:37:37.600 --> 00:37:41.520
[Amit Varma]: My case is simply that the government should do the same thing in education, which it did

00:37:41.520 --> 00:37:47.160
[Amit Varma]: in airlines and telecom, you allow private players to participate without any conditions.

00:37:47.160 --> 00:37:52.120
[Amit Varma]: Nobody wants to open a budget private school in a slum in a room only with no playground,

00:37:52.120 --> 00:37:57.000
[Amit Varma]: allow them to do so, don't harass them, let the market vote with their feet, see what

00:37:57.000 --> 00:38:02.360
[Amit Varma]: happens and get rid of this mentality that profit is a dirty word because the only way

00:38:02.360 --> 00:38:06.400
[Amit Varma]: anyone can profit is by fulfilling somebody else's need.

00:38:06.400 --> 00:38:08.360
[Amit Varma]: That is the only way to profit.

00:38:08.360 --> 00:38:11.720
[Amit Varma]: Profit is therefore the greatest form of philanthropy.

00:38:11.720 --> 00:38:17.200
[Amit Varma]: And I think this is like a fundamental mind shift that needs to happen, especially in

00:38:17.200 --> 00:38:20.800
[Amit Varma]: education, where to add a point and to connect it to the jobs crisis.

00:38:20.800 --> 00:38:26.160
[Amit Varma]: There is a massive mismatch today between the kind of workers coming out into the field

00:38:26.160 --> 00:38:28.040
[Amit Varma]: and the kind of skills that are needed.

00:38:28.040 --> 00:38:32.120
[Amit Varma]: People do PhDs and MPhils and they simply have no employable skills.

00:38:32.120 --> 00:38:37.560
[Amit Varma]: And where does such a demand supply mismatch happen, where there is no market at play?

00:38:37.560 --> 00:38:39.440
[Amit Varma]: Allow the freaking market.

00:38:39.440 --> 00:38:40.960
[Guest 1]: I would add one more thing.

00:38:40.960 --> 00:38:47.520
[Guest 1]: I think there is no greater damning evidence that a system has completely failed when parents

00:38:47.520 --> 00:38:54.200
[Guest 1]: from really poor families would spend close to half their income and spend four thousand

00:38:54.200 --> 00:38:59.280
[Guest 1]: or five thousand rupees to send their children to a for-profit tiny school where you're sort

00:38:59.280 --> 00:39:04.000
[Guest 1]: of, you know, stacked like sardines rather than go to the government school, which is

00:39:04.000 --> 00:39:05.640
[Guest 1]: for free and which is nearby.

00:39:05.640 --> 00:39:06.640
[Guest 1]: Right.

00:39:06.640 --> 00:39:14.240
[Guest 1]: And one very large part of not allowing for-profit schools is the optics will be terrible because

00:39:14.240 --> 00:39:18.400
[Guest 1]: right now they can show the nice building with the airy windows and no teachers and

00:39:18.400 --> 00:39:23.920
[Guest 1]: no students and then compare it to these terribly crowded, you know, they actually look quite

00:39:23.920 --> 00:39:24.920
[Guest 1]: bad.

00:39:24.920 --> 00:39:25.920
[Guest 1]: Right.

00:39:25.920 --> 00:39:29.320
[Guest 1]: I went to maths tuition in 10th standard or 11th standard in one of these rooms where

00:39:29.320 --> 00:39:32.760
[Guest 1]: it was like a capacity for 30 people and 90 people were stacked.

00:39:32.760 --> 00:39:36.280
[Guest 1]: But the quality of the maths being taught to us was fantastic.

00:39:36.280 --> 00:39:38.160
[Guest 1]: It doesn't look good.

00:39:38.160 --> 00:39:42.940
[Guest 1]: So they produce these documents in court and say, look at these people commercializing.

00:39:42.940 --> 00:39:45.160
[Guest 1]: These children don't have room to breathe.

00:39:45.160 --> 00:39:46.640
[Guest 1]: There is no window in the room.

00:39:46.640 --> 00:39:48.720
[Guest 1]: They don't get bathroom breaks.

00:39:48.720 --> 00:39:49.720
[Guest 1]: Right.

00:39:49.720 --> 00:39:55.240
[Guest 1]: So if you really genuinely allowed for-profit schools, those schools would be able to invest.

00:39:55.240 --> 00:39:59.140
[Guest 1]: See, right now, the schools are under tremendous uncertainty.

00:39:59.140 --> 00:40:03.440
[Guest 1]: You know, in Sangam Vihar in Delhi, they shut down like five, six hundred schools like this

00:40:03.440 --> 00:40:04.440
[Guest 1]: every year.

00:40:04.440 --> 00:40:07.840
[Guest 1]: They have this little raid, they take their, you know, billboards down and then one year

00:40:07.840 --> 00:40:08.840
[Guest 2]: later they back up.

00:40:08.840 --> 00:40:10.120
[Guest 2]: So I have a question here.

00:40:10.120 --> 00:40:13.880
[Guest 2]: Is that other than the government causing obstacles like this, right, like going to

00:40:13.880 --> 00:40:16.520
[Guest 2]: the court and taking them down, etc.

00:40:16.520 --> 00:40:21.600
[Guest 2]: Legally speaking or from a regulatory perspective or institution wise, is there any bottleneck

00:40:21.600 --> 00:40:24.880
[Guest 2]: or obstacle for the private sector to set up primary education?

00:40:24.880 --> 00:40:27.160
[Guest 1]: So the licensing requirement.

00:40:27.160 --> 00:40:29.800
[Guest 1]: So first of all, this is state and municipal, right?

00:40:29.800 --> 00:40:35.840
[Guest 1]: The licensing requirements to set up any school is just incredibly high.

00:40:35.840 --> 00:40:40.520
[Guest 1]: So even the best, you know, posh convent schools are breaking half a dozen rules at any given

00:40:40.520 --> 00:40:45.680
[Guest 1]: point in time, because to open a new school, I think the number that I last read was 34

00:40:45.680 --> 00:40:46.680
[Guest 1]: or 44.

00:40:46.680 --> 00:40:48.720
[Guest 1]: Like, you just need a ridiculous number of licenses.

00:40:48.720 --> 00:40:50.640
[Guest 1]: That's one kind of bottleneck.

00:40:50.640 --> 00:40:54.920
[Guest 1]: The other kind of bottleneck is, you know, a school is supposed to be a structure that

00:40:54.920 --> 00:41:00.480
[Guest 1]: lasts for a really long time, right, which means when you go to these old countries,

00:41:00.480 --> 00:41:05.120
[Guest 1]: you know, these European countries and you see the school was set up in 1500 or 1400,

00:41:05.120 --> 00:41:08.000
[Guest 1]: they set it up as if it was supposed to exist forever.

00:41:08.000 --> 00:41:11.920
[Guest 1]: Now if you're constantly under regulatory threat that someone's going to come and shut

00:41:11.920 --> 00:41:15.680
[Guest 1]: down your shutter, you're not going to invest in windows, right?

00:41:15.680 --> 00:41:21.120
[Guest 1]: You invest in the bare bones, which is benches, markers, the teacher and the students showing

00:41:21.120 --> 00:41:22.120
[Guest 1]: up and that's it.

00:41:22.120 --> 00:41:23.880
[Guest 1]: You don't invest in anything else.

00:41:23.880 --> 00:41:27.360
[Guest 1]: So private schools also look terrible.

00:41:27.360 --> 00:41:31.680
[Guest 1]: Even the budget private schools look terrible, even though there's so much money in education

00:41:31.680 --> 00:41:35.880
[Guest 1]: and people would like to invest, because it's so difficult to invest in education and get

00:41:35.880 --> 00:41:36.880
[Guest 2]: a return on it.

00:41:36.880 --> 00:41:40.900
[Guest 2]: So essentially this reform, what I'm trying to understand is what are the tangible things

00:41:40.900 --> 00:41:42.880
[Guest 2]: required to make this reform work.

00:41:42.880 --> 00:41:47.640
[Amit Varma]: And this would be amending a lot of laws and require regulatory licensing requirements.

00:41:47.640 --> 00:41:51.880
[Amit Varma]: I've actually had a great episode on this with Amit Chandra, who actually works in this

00:41:51.880 --> 00:41:52.880
[Amit Varma]: specific field.

00:41:52.880 --> 00:41:53.880
[Amit Varma]: It's an over one hour episode.

00:41:53.880 --> 00:41:54.880
[Amit Varma]: That's really good.

00:41:54.880 --> 00:41:57.680
[Amit Varma]: I recommend listeners check that out.

00:41:57.680 --> 00:42:03.640
[Amit Varma]: And also, I would just add that the larger point here is of agency and choice.

00:42:03.640 --> 00:42:07.000
[Amit Varma]: Parents are in the best position to make a decision about where the kids should go to

00:42:07.000 --> 00:42:08.000
[Amit Varma]: school.

00:42:08.000 --> 00:42:09.000
[Amit Varma]: You are robbing them of choice.

00:42:09.000 --> 00:42:11.320
[Amit Varma]: No one is saying shut down the government schools, keep them going, but you're robbing

00:42:11.320 --> 00:42:15.000
[Amit Varma]: them of choice by not allowing private providers.

00:42:15.000 --> 00:42:18.280
[Amit Varma]: Imagine if the same thing happened to bread, there would be so much outrage.

00:42:18.280 --> 00:42:21.440
[Amit Varma]: It happens in education, which is so much more important than bread and there is no

00:42:21.440 --> 00:42:23.680
[Amit Varma]: outrage and Vivek.

00:42:23.680 --> 00:42:24.680
[Guest 3]: Couple of points.

00:42:24.680 --> 00:42:29.040
[Guest 3]: So one is that, you know, because of all this, you know, we have an employment crisis.

00:42:29.040 --> 00:42:31.040
[Guest 3]: We also have an employability crisis.

00:42:31.040 --> 00:42:37.400
[Guest 3]: So even when companies put out, you know, posts for jobs, they don't get the right candidates.

00:42:37.400 --> 00:42:40.960
[Guest 3]: The second point I would like to make, and you know, this is education for profit.

00:42:40.960 --> 00:42:46.880
[Guest 3]: I mean, look at the fact that a lot of private equity money is now going into tutorials.

00:42:46.880 --> 00:42:51.640
[Guest 3]: I mean, if education for profit was allowed, and I mean, tutorial is nothing just, you

00:42:51.640 --> 00:42:56.080
[Guest 3]: know, you're beating the system by you're starting a school, but you call it a tutorial.

00:42:56.080 --> 00:42:57.600
[Amit Varma]: You're filling a gap in the system.

00:42:57.600 --> 00:42:59.760
[Guest 3]: The question is, why is that gap there?

00:42:59.760 --> 00:43:04.520
[Guest 3]: So the gaps there and someone's filling in that gap and he's getting private equity money.

00:43:04.520 --> 00:43:09.960
[Guest 3]: Now that private equity money could easily go to an a real education entrepreneur who's

00:43:09.960 --> 00:43:13.300
[Guest 3]: setting up real schools and so on and so forth.

00:43:13.300 --> 00:43:17.720
[Guest 3]: So I mean, why should all the private equity money go to Swiggy and you know,

00:43:17.720 --> 00:43:24.680
[Amit Varma]: I think we're spending so much time per reform that we, you know, maybe we should leave jobs

00:43:24.680 --> 00:43:26.440
[Amit Varma]: and education behind us.

00:43:26.440 --> 00:43:27.920
[Guest 2]: Thank you so much.

00:43:27.920 --> 00:43:32.040
[Guest 2]: So actually, yeah, I will not talk about jobs and education, but I'll talk about something

00:43:32.040 --> 00:43:34.300
[Guest 2]: that is related to government spending.

00:43:34.300 --> 00:43:38.760
[Guest 2]: So taking the cues from what Amit said about, you know, government should let the private

00:43:38.760 --> 00:43:40.600
[Guest 2]: sector come in and all of that.

00:43:40.600 --> 00:43:47.120
[Guest 2]: So my reform is basically about fiscal discipline, which I think is an extremely important thing

00:43:47.120 --> 00:43:48.860
[Guest 2]: for the government to follow.

00:43:48.860 --> 00:43:53.840
[Guest 2]: So whenever a government spends money, there are, let's say, three ways for the government

00:43:53.840 --> 00:43:54.840
[Guest 2]: to finance that expenditure.

00:43:54.840 --> 00:43:58.960
[Guest 2]: You can either tax the current generation, which is in a way the most fair way to do

00:43:58.960 --> 00:44:02.800
[Guest 2]: because the current generation is also benefiting from the goodies that the government is giving.

00:44:02.800 --> 00:44:06.960
[Guest 2]: Or you tax the future generation, which is unfair because the future generation is not

00:44:06.960 --> 00:44:09.140
[Guest 2]: benefiting from the government spending.

00:44:09.140 --> 00:44:11.040
[Guest 2]: The second way would be to borrow.

00:44:11.040 --> 00:44:13.880
[Guest 2]: And at some point, you will have to repay what you have borrowed.

00:44:13.880 --> 00:44:17.240
[Guest 2]: And the third is to basically print money and inflate your way out of it, which is a

00:44:17.240 --> 00:44:18.580
[Guest 2]: big burden on the poor.

00:44:18.580 --> 00:44:22.800
[Guest 2]: So either which way, whenever the government ends up spending, the burden falls on the

00:44:22.800 --> 00:44:26.540
[Guest 2]: taxpayer either today or tomorrow, one way or the other.

00:44:26.540 --> 00:44:30.040
[Guest 2]: And what the government typically ends up doing is, and this is not just the Indian

00:44:30.040 --> 00:44:34.480
[Guest 2]: government, this is governments in general have a temptation to spend 100 rupees today

00:44:34.480 --> 00:44:36.840
[Guest 2]: and tax only 90 rupees.

00:44:36.840 --> 00:44:40.120
[Guest 2]: This makes us feel very good because we are getting goodies worth of rupees 100, but we

00:44:40.120 --> 00:44:41.840
[Guest 2]: are only bearing the burden of 90.

00:44:41.840 --> 00:44:45.520
[Guest 2]: But what ends up happening is that 10 rupees gets pushed out to the next generation.

00:44:45.520 --> 00:44:48.960
[Guest 2]: So we make our children pay more for what we are enjoying today.

00:44:48.960 --> 00:44:52.640
[Guest 2]: And this is basically the classic way that what is called fiscal deficit, right, keeps

00:44:52.640 --> 00:44:54.440
[Guest 2]: on increasing and increasing.

00:44:54.440 --> 00:44:57.840
[Guest 2]: And that keeps on adding to the debt burden of the government.

00:44:57.840 --> 00:44:59.960
[Guest 2]: And that's a very serious problem.

00:44:59.960 --> 00:45:04.960
[Guest 2]: Because if governments give in to this temptation of spending and pushing the taxing in the

00:45:04.960 --> 00:45:07.040
[Guest 2]: future generation, then this can go on forever.

00:45:07.040 --> 00:45:10.480
[Guest 2]: And generation after generation keeps paying for this.

00:45:10.480 --> 00:45:14.640
[Guest 2]: And we have recently seen in Europe, for example, what happens when there is a sovereign debt

00:45:14.640 --> 00:45:18.440
[Guest 2]: crisis when governments default on their debt and so on so forth.

00:45:18.440 --> 00:45:23.640
[Guest 2]: Now coming to India, there is now given that we have Aadhaar and we have Jan Dhan accounts

00:45:23.640 --> 00:45:28.360
[Guest 2]: and whatnot, there is not only a temptation for the government to spend, but there is

00:45:28.360 --> 00:45:32.200
[Guest 2]: also a very easy way for the government to spend because all you have to do is essentially

00:45:32.200 --> 00:45:36.200
[Guest 2]: just keep giving your transfers and direct benefits or what have you made to these bank

00:45:36.200 --> 00:45:37.200
[Guest 2]: accounts.

00:45:37.200 --> 00:45:42.640
[Guest 2]: And what we have also seen is that the government has practically no interest to listen to whatever

00:45:42.640 --> 00:45:48.080
[Guest 2]: our Fiscal Responsibility Budget Management Act, a long thing, FRBM Act stipulated because

00:45:48.080 --> 00:45:51.600
[Guest 2]: that has become a farce and there is no real consequence for the government to violate

00:45:51.600 --> 00:45:52.600
[Guest 2]: it.

00:45:52.600 --> 00:45:56.200
[Guest 2]: And every year when the budget is presented, we spend a lot of time writing and discussing

00:45:56.200 --> 00:46:00.760
[Guest 2]: what is the actual fiscal deficit, what has been pushed out of the budget, so on so forth.

00:46:00.760 --> 00:46:06.160
[Guest 2]: So fiscal discipline, I think, is a big crisis in India and has been so for a while.

00:46:06.160 --> 00:46:11.960
[Guest 2]: So one reform that I can think of is, and it's a bit of a draconian thing, but I think

00:46:11.960 --> 00:46:16.400
[Guest 2]: that's what is needed, is something what Germany did.

00:46:16.400 --> 00:46:21.360
[Guest 2]: In the peak of the 2008 financial crisis, when the temptation of the government to give

00:46:21.360 --> 00:46:26.440
[Guest 2]: a fiscal stimulus was very high, and when Germany was in the acute shock of the financial

00:46:26.440 --> 00:46:31.480
[Guest 2]: crisis, the German debt to GDP had reached 80 percent and they were only supposed to

00:46:31.480 --> 00:46:34.980
[Guest 2]: be at 60 percent according to the Maastricht Treaty.

00:46:34.980 --> 00:46:39.880
[Guest 2]: So what the German constitution, what the German government did, which I think is remarkable,

00:46:39.880 --> 00:46:43.800
[Guest 2]: they were decent enough to say that at the time when the temptation of the government

00:46:43.800 --> 00:46:48.640
[Guest 2]: to run a high fiscal deficit is so big, we are going to tie the hands of the government.

00:46:48.640 --> 00:46:55.120
[Guest 2]: And so they enshrined in the German constitutional law something called a debt break, which stipulated

00:46:55.120 --> 00:47:02.600
[Guest 2]: that by 2016, the overall structural deficit of the government will be at a tight maximum

00:47:02.600 --> 00:47:04.640
[Guest 2]: of 0.35 percent of GDP.

00:47:04.640 --> 00:47:09.160
[Guest 2]: Now, imagine you're starting at a point where the debt to GDP ratio is 83 percent.

00:47:09.160 --> 00:47:13.000
[Guest 2]: And technically, you're saying that in the next four or five years, you bring down the

00:47:13.000 --> 00:47:17.400
[Guest 2]: structural deficit to 0.35 percent of GDP, which means your debt gradually goes down

00:47:17.400 --> 00:47:22.160
[Guest 2]: to 60 percent from 83 percent at a time when Germany is in the throes of the financial

00:47:22.160 --> 00:47:23.160
[Guest 2]: crisis.

00:47:23.160 --> 00:47:29.840
[Guest 2]: And all the states of Germany will bring down the deficit to zero by 2020.

00:47:29.840 --> 00:47:35.240
[Guest 2]: So this was a really, really tight fiscal discipline rule where Germany imposed a balanced

00:47:35.240 --> 00:47:37.440
[Guest 2]: budget on itself.

00:47:37.440 --> 00:47:44.080
[Guest 2]: And the consequence of that was that over the next seven years, from 2012 to now, Germany

00:47:44.080 --> 00:47:47.680
[Guest 2]: has run a budget surplus in each of the years.

00:47:47.680 --> 00:47:53.240
[Guest 2]: And last year, the German budget surplus was as high as 1.7 percent of GDP.

00:47:53.240 --> 00:47:58.040
[Guest 2]: And now the debt to GDP is actually at 60 percent, it's projected to be 50 percent.

00:47:58.040 --> 00:48:02.040
[Guest 2]: So it's a remarkable thing that they have done, and it's not that the German government

00:48:02.040 --> 00:48:03.040
[Guest 2]: is not spending.

00:48:03.040 --> 00:48:07.320
[Guest 2]: What they have done is you are essentially financing your expenses just from your revenue

00:48:07.320 --> 00:48:11.840
[Guest 2]: and you're shrinking your public debt, which is exactly what John Maynard Keynes would

00:48:11.840 --> 00:48:16.680
[Guest 2]: recommend, which is exactly what any fiscal sound principle would recommend, that you

00:48:16.680 --> 00:48:19.960
[Guest 2]: spend during bad times and you save during good times.

00:48:19.960 --> 00:48:24.640
[Guest 2]: And basically, if you save during good times, what it does is when the next bad time comes,

00:48:24.640 --> 00:48:26.880
[Guest 2]: you have the credibility and the space to borrow.

00:48:26.880 --> 00:48:32.040
[Guest 2]: Otherwise, if you keep borrowing and spending, you are just in that perpetual fiscal deficit

00:48:32.040 --> 00:48:35.280
[Guest 2]: mode where there is no credibility and nobody will want to lend you money if there is a

00:48:35.280 --> 00:48:36.940
[Guest 2]: war, if there is a deep recession.

00:48:36.940 --> 00:48:42.160
[Guest 2]: The only exception the German debt break constitutional amendment has is natural disasters and deep

00:48:42.160 --> 00:48:43.160
[Guest 2]: recession.

00:48:43.160 --> 00:48:45.080
[Guest 2]: Other than that, you have to stick to this rule.

00:48:45.080 --> 00:48:48.780
[Guest 2]: And I think that is something it's high time we introduce in India.

00:48:48.780 --> 00:48:53.360
[Guest 2]: And since constitutional amendment is not very difficult these days, we should enshrine

00:48:53.360 --> 00:48:57.580
[Guest 2]: that in the constitution and make a meaningful change to say we are going to tie down the

00:48:57.580 --> 00:49:02.560
[Guest 2]: hands of our government and that will force the government to prioritize its expenses.

00:49:02.560 --> 00:49:07.200
[Guest 2]: Instead of announcing 65 different schemes, which nobody is monitoring, you prioritize

00:49:07.200 --> 00:49:11.600
[Guest 2]: that, OK, if these are the five schemes which are important, I'm going to do this and then

00:49:11.600 --> 00:49:14.240
[Guest 2]: gradually shrink the size of the government.

00:49:14.240 --> 00:49:18.160
[Guest 2]: And as you said, let the private sector, let the market give them a chance and let them

00:49:18.160 --> 00:49:19.160
[Guest 2]: work.

00:49:19.160 --> 00:49:23.320
[Guest 2]: Otherwise, we'll end up in a situation where the government is so intrusive in our lives

00:49:23.320 --> 00:49:26.480
[Guest 2]: that it just keeps becoming a fatter and fatter cat.

00:49:26.480 --> 00:49:28.080
[Guest 2]: And who's financing it?

00:49:28.080 --> 00:49:29.080
[Guest 3]: We.

00:49:29.080 --> 00:49:34.600
[Guest 3]: So, I mean, clearly, she doesn't believe in the modern monetary theory and which is a

00:49:34.600 --> 00:49:35.600
[Guest 3]: huge thing these days.

00:49:35.600 --> 00:49:41.680
[Guest 3]: I mean, when the moment you talk about fiscal deficit on the social media, people will jump

00:49:41.680 --> 00:49:44.720
[Guest 3]: on you, citing this new area of economics.

00:49:44.720 --> 00:49:50.240
[Guest 2]: Because everyone on social media is a trained economist, especially when I usually don't

00:49:50.240 --> 00:49:53.000
[Guest 3]: believe in things which are huge things.

00:49:53.000 --> 00:49:57.600
[Guest 3]: And the second point, you know, in Germany's case, they were lucky to have had the hyperinflation

00:49:57.600 --> 00:50:02.140
[Guest 3]: of 1923, because all that economic thinking goes back to that.

00:50:02.140 --> 00:50:03.640
[Guest 3]: And then they tend to do the right things.

00:50:03.640 --> 00:50:07.040
[Guest 3]: I mean, every other nation is not as lucky.

00:50:07.040 --> 00:50:10.120
[Guest 3]: The third point I wanted to make is and I mean, this is something, you know, we've had

00:50:10.120 --> 00:50:16.080
[Guest 3]: long conversations on is the fact that the fiscal deficit of the central government,

00:50:16.080 --> 00:50:20.600
[Guest 3]: you know, when we say is 3.4 or 3.3% of the GDP, I mean, that's one big sham.

00:50:20.600 --> 00:50:25.560
[Guest 3]: I mean, if you look at the total public sector borrowing requirement, as you know, the total

00:50:25.560 --> 00:50:30.120
[Guest 3]: borrowing of the government is termed as it comes to clearly, you know, it comes to 8.5%,

00:50:30.120 --> 00:50:39.040
[Guest 3]: 9% of the GDP in an era where our financial savings have come down dramatically.

00:50:39.040 --> 00:50:43.160
[Guest 3]: So I mean, one is that, you know, fiscal deficit is not represented correctly.

00:50:43.160 --> 00:50:47.600
[Guest 3]: And the other point, the more important point is that this is why interest rates are not

00:50:47.600 --> 00:50:48.600
[Guest 3]: going to come down.

00:50:48.600 --> 00:50:51.440
[Guest 3]: I mean, you can keep cutting the repo rate till kingdom come.

00:50:51.440 --> 00:50:55.080
[Guest 3]: But the banks ultimately have to compete with the government.

00:50:55.080 --> 00:50:58.200
[Guest 3]: So unless the government sort of cuts its expenditure, the interest rates are not going

00:50:58.200 --> 00:50:59.200
[Guest 2]: to come down.

00:50:59.200 --> 00:51:03.840
[Guest 2]: And one point to add to what Vivek said is, ironically enough, our government expenditure

00:51:03.840 --> 00:51:08.280
[Guest 2]: is ballooned at a time when apparently our economy has been booming, you know, it doesn't

00:51:08.280 --> 00:51:15.200
[Guest 2]: make any sense that if the GDP growth is showing that we are growing at 7.5, 8.2% in a quarter,

00:51:15.200 --> 00:51:19.920
[Guest 2]: that is the time when your government expenditure fiscal deficit is not able to stick to their

00:51:19.920 --> 00:51:23.120
[Guest 2]: FRBM target and you're going to 3.4, 3.5% of GDP.

00:51:23.120 --> 00:51:25.080
[Guest 2]: It doesn't make any economic sense whatsoever.

00:51:25.080 --> 00:51:29.360
[Guest 2]: Yeah, if you explain to me, fine, we are in a deep recession, you need to give some real

00:51:29.360 --> 00:51:32.980
[Guest 2]: good stimulus to infrastructure projects to yank the economy out of it.

00:51:32.980 --> 00:51:35.200
[Guest 2]: And you're going to cut expenses on the schemes.

00:51:35.200 --> 00:51:36.200
[Guest 2]: That's a different thing.

00:51:36.200 --> 00:51:40.160
[Guest 2]: But we are doing schemes, we are doing apparently some infrastructure, we are doing everything,

00:51:40.160 --> 00:51:43.680
[Guest 2]: because the government is doing all the spending, because all the other demand sources in the

00:51:43.680 --> 00:51:44.680
[Guest 2]: economy have gone to sleep.

00:51:44.680 --> 00:51:49.480
[Guest 2]: So we have no investment, no exports, no consumption, nobody's buying toothpaste or biscuits or

00:51:49.480 --> 00:51:50.480
[Guest 2]: cars.

00:51:50.480 --> 00:51:53.800
[Guest 2]: But the government is the big giant elephant in the room who's spending, because the government

00:51:53.800 --> 00:51:57.080
[Guest 2]: has access to some real secret source of money hidden away somewhere.

00:51:57.080 --> 00:51:59.280
[Guest 2]: Of course, that's not true, because we are all paying for that.

00:51:59.280 --> 00:52:01.720
[Guest 3]: You've got some really nice statues.

00:52:01.720 --> 00:52:07.360
[Guest 3]: So which is why the next point here is that when businesses now ask for a fiscal stimulus,

00:52:07.360 --> 00:52:11.440
[Guest 3]: the point is, if you look at data over the last two years, the fiscal stimulus is already

00:52:11.440 --> 00:52:12.440
[Guest 3]: there in the system.

00:52:12.440 --> 00:52:17.080
[Guest 3]: And it's a huge one, because if you look at government, just the government expenditure,

00:52:17.080 --> 00:52:21.600
[Guest 3]: it grew by 19% in 17-18 and 13% in 18-19.

00:52:21.600 --> 00:52:27.040
[Guest 3]: And it's the biggest growth in the last 10 years, I mean, if you leave out the part around

00:52:27.040 --> 00:52:29.040
[Guest 3]: the financial crisis.

00:52:29.040 --> 00:52:32.560
[Guest 2]: So it's the nature of the fiscal stimulus, Vivek.

00:52:32.560 --> 00:52:39.760
[Guest 2]: So for example, if I give you the analogy, so in 1999-2002, we had another economic slowdown.

00:52:39.760 --> 00:52:42.920
[Guest 2]: We had a very big economic stagnation, we had a slowdown.

00:52:42.920 --> 00:52:46.160
[Guest 2]: And that was also the time when the government had given a fiscal stimulus.

00:52:46.160 --> 00:52:50.240
[Guest 2]: But that stimulus was in the form of, let's say, an NHEI investment, a golden quadrilateral,

00:52:50.240 --> 00:52:52.320
[Guest 2]: like proper infrastructure investment.

00:52:52.320 --> 00:52:57.200
[Guest 2]: Now a fiscal stimulus takes the form of building toilets and houses and gases and I don't know

00:52:57.200 --> 00:52:58.200
[Guest 2]: what, right.

00:52:58.200 --> 00:53:00.760
[Guest 2]: So there is also a nature of fiscal stimulus that is needed.

00:53:00.760 --> 00:53:04.360
[Guest 2]: But I think, yeah, the overarching thing is whatever the government does, there needs

00:53:04.360 --> 00:53:07.240
[Guest 2]: to be a rule that ties down the hand of the government.

00:53:07.240 --> 00:53:10.600
[Guest 2]: And a rule that has real consequences, like if you're enshrined in the Constitution, it's

00:53:10.600 --> 00:53:13.680
[Guest 2]: a real consequence of the change that you really have to amend it again.

00:53:13.680 --> 00:53:18.760
[Guest 2]: And all off balance sheet fine, if you're a BHAL, if an FCI, if an NHEI, too bad, you

00:53:18.760 --> 00:53:22.240
[Guest 2]: also get clubbed into that because you have just been party to this whole thing as well.

00:53:22.240 --> 00:53:31.280
[Guest 3]: So the, I mean, sorry to butt in again, now, NHEI, not NHEI, sorry, FCI, in 2019-20, will

00:53:31.280 --> 00:53:37.520
[Guest 3]: end up borrowing around 1,90,000 crore from the National Small Savings Fund.

00:53:37.520 --> 00:53:40.840
[Guest 3]: I mean, this is, we're getting into very, very dangerous territory now, because this

00:53:40.840 --> 00:53:47.280
[Guest 3]: is, you know, the money that we invest in our public provident fund and all the post

00:53:47.280 --> 00:53:49.640
[Guest 3]: office income schemes.

00:53:49.640 --> 00:53:52.720
[Guest 1]: So you know, I'll tell you what I agree on.

00:53:52.720 --> 00:53:58.360
[Guest 1]: So I completely agree with you that, you know, our fiscal discipline, I mean, we don't have

00:53:58.360 --> 00:54:00.080
[Guest 1]: any fiscal discipline.

00:54:00.080 --> 00:54:03.220
[Guest 1]: And there are parts of the fiscal discipline, which is depending on the kind of spending

00:54:03.220 --> 00:54:06.360
[Guest 1]: can be better or worse, we've lost the plot there also.

00:54:06.360 --> 00:54:10.780
[Guest 1]: There's a great book on what you were talking about the whole, you know, taxing versus debt.

00:54:10.780 --> 00:54:16.320
[Guest 1]: So this whole nonsense of Ricardian equivalence, James Buchanan and Richard Wagner have a book

00:54:16.320 --> 00:54:22.560
[Guest 1]: called Democracy in Deficit, which talks about the inherent problems of democratic politics,

00:54:22.560 --> 00:54:28.480
[Guest 1]: which push it towards debt as opposed to taxation, basically, because when you're taxing people,

00:54:28.480 --> 00:54:30.720
[Guest 1]: they also tend to be your voters.

00:54:30.720 --> 00:54:35.480
[Guest 1]: And when you raise money through debt, those voters are either not yet voting or not yet

00:54:35.480 --> 00:54:36.600
[Guest 1]: born.

00:54:36.600 --> 00:54:41.960
[Guest 1]: So it is much easier to reduce taxes and increase debt, because those people are not yet voting,

00:54:41.960 --> 00:54:42.960
[Guest 1]: right.

00:54:42.960 --> 00:54:44.560
[Guest 1]: So we shift the problem to the next generation.

00:54:44.560 --> 00:54:50.600
[Guest 1]: And because any government is sort of, you know, has no limit in that sense, right, so

00:54:50.600 --> 00:54:52.400
[Guest 1]: it's going to be immortal.

00:54:52.400 --> 00:54:56.240
[Guest 1]: You can keep sort of rolling it on to the next generation and the next generation, the

00:54:56.240 --> 00:55:01.360
[Guest 1]: music only stops when you have these demographic problems or crises or something like that.

00:55:01.360 --> 00:55:04.240
[Guest 1]: So it's a lovely book that I recommend for everyone.

00:55:04.240 --> 00:55:09.720
[Guest 1]: Now, coming to Germany versus India, you know, Germany could have done this even without

00:55:09.720 --> 00:55:13.360
[Guest 1]: the constitutional constraint, because it's Germany.

00:55:13.360 --> 00:55:19.440
[Guest 1]: One, they have excellent legislative discipline, right, they have very good separation of powers.

00:55:19.440 --> 00:55:24.520
[Guest 1]: They have a very tight feedback mechanism between the voters and taxpayers, who are

00:55:24.520 --> 00:55:29.640
[Guest 1]: fairly rich individuals, like the tax base is really big, and the government, right.

00:55:29.640 --> 00:55:34.960
[Guest 1]: So all these three things included means that people do get upset in Germany, like regular

00:55:34.960 --> 00:55:39.960
[Guest 1]: folks get upset if you're going too much into debt, because they know what the consequences

00:55:39.960 --> 00:55:40.960
[Guest 1]: of that are.

00:55:40.960 --> 00:55:43.160
[Guest 1]: Now, that's not the case in India.

00:55:43.160 --> 00:55:46.600
[Guest 1]: So the temptation in India is let's constitutionalize it.

00:55:46.600 --> 00:55:52.740
[Guest 1]: Now I have studied all our 103 or whatever the number of constitutional amendments are.

00:55:52.740 --> 00:55:57.160
[Guest 1]: What we like to do is to push things to the constitutional stage, but it's ridiculously

00:55:57.160 --> 00:56:05.060
[Guest 1]: easy to amend our constitution, right, a little bit harder than passing law, passing legislation.

00:56:05.060 --> 00:56:06.560
[Guest 1]: It's really no constraint.

00:56:06.560 --> 00:56:08.800
[Guest 1]: We change the constitution.

00:56:08.800 --> 00:56:13.320
[Guest 1]: I keep buying new copies of the constitution in the last 15 years, because it keeps changing.

00:56:13.320 --> 00:56:15.600
[Amit Varma]: As the joke goes, it's a periodical, not a book.

00:56:15.600 --> 00:56:16.600
[Guest 1]: Yeah.

00:56:16.600 --> 00:56:18.000
[Guest 1]: So this is a problem.

00:56:18.000 --> 00:56:24.360
[Guest 1]: So now if you put this in to the constitution, like certain parts of the constitution, which

00:56:24.360 --> 00:56:29.680
[Guest 1]: are just, you know, there's one of these provisions of reservations, which Ambedkar had initially

00:56:29.680 --> 00:56:33.320
[Guest 1]: intended would eclipse after the first 10 years, you know, after 10 years, we won't

00:56:33.320 --> 00:56:34.320
[Guest 1]: need reservation.

00:56:34.320 --> 00:56:37.560
[Guest 1]: That was the world Ambedkar had imagined for India.

00:56:37.560 --> 00:56:39.800
[Guest 1]: Every 10 years, it's extended.

00:56:39.800 --> 00:56:41.400
[Guest 1]: It's a constitutional amendment.

00:56:41.400 --> 00:56:44.560
[Guest 1]: It is so procedural now, they just show up.

00:56:44.560 --> 00:56:47.080
[Guest 1]: You know what the quorum requirement, you know, how many people need to say yes, they

00:56:47.080 --> 00:56:48.680
[Guest 1]: just amend and move on.

00:56:48.680 --> 00:56:54.200
[Guest 1]: I have a feeling that any kind of fiscal responsibility in the constitution will just become one of

00:56:54.200 --> 00:56:58.440
[Guest 1]: those things, while they can still feel good about the fact that they constitutionalized

00:56:58.440 --> 00:56:59.440
[Guest 1]: it.

00:56:59.440 --> 00:57:01.480
[Guest 1]: So in some senses, it's, I think, even more dangerous.

00:57:01.480 --> 00:57:05.800
[Guest 1]: I think what is really important long run, right, I mean, since we're really looking

00:57:05.800 --> 00:57:11.760
[Guest 1]: for reform and not band-aid, long run, what is really important is, one, we need to really

00:57:11.760 --> 00:57:16.720
[Guest 1]: expand our tax base, right, our tax base is just not big enough.

00:57:16.720 --> 00:57:21.000
[Guest 1]: So our government both spends too much and too little, depending on which area of the

00:57:21.000 --> 00:57:22.960
[Guest 1]: economy that you're talking about.

00:57:22.960 --> 00:57:29.400
[Guest 1]: So and the larger the tax base, the more people will be upset if you increase taxes.

00:57:29.400 --> 00:57:33.360
[Guest 1]: So that also acts as some kind of fiscal check or fiscal constraints, because the moment

00:57:33.360 --> 00:57:37.120
[Guest 1]: you become a taxpayer, suddenly you start worrying about government spending and, you

00:57:37.120 --> 00:57:39.640
[Guest 1]: know, fiscal responsibility and so on.

00:57:39.640 --> 00:57:41.680
[Guest 1]: So that's, you know, one thing.

00:57:41.680 --> 00:57:45.320
[Guest 1]: The second goes back to our education problem, which is, you know, I mean, forget fiscal

00:57:45.320 --> 00:57:48.920
[Guest 1]: responsibility, we can't count in class 10.

00:57:48.920 --> 00:57:55.080
[Guest 1]: So the idea that we are going to have an electorate in 20 years from today, or even three years

00:57:55.080 --> 00:57:59.520
[Guest 1]: from today, who actually understand these things, you know, I mean, they don't need

00:57:59.520 --> 00:58:04.280
[Guest 1]: to understand it at the sophistication you have as an economics professor who does this

00:58:04.280 --> 00:58:05.280
[Guest 1]: for a living.

00:58:05.280 --> 00:58:09.560
[Guest 1]: But to just understand the basics of, oh, this is the arithmetic, right?

00:58:09.560 --> 00:58:13.520
[Guest 1]: And the government can't defy the rules of basic arithmetic the same way we can't.

00:58:13.520 --> 00:58:14.520
[Guest 1]: Right?

00:58:14.520 --> 00:58:16.400
[Guest 1]: So where does this gap coming from?

00:58:16.400 --> 00:58:19.980
[Guest 1]: That is just completely missing in these other people voting for them.

00:58:19.980 --> 00:58:25.360
[Guest 1]: So in some sense, I mean, what, what is your fail safe when the constitutional constraint

00:58:25.360 --> 00:58:26.360
[Guest 1]: fails?

00:58:26.360 --> 00:58:27.360
[Guest 1]: It's the people.

00:58:27.360 --> 00:58:28.360
[Guest 1]: Right?

00:58:28.360 --> 00:58:32.320
[Guest 1]: So maybe that fail safe is just missing, we've broken the constitutional fail safe.

00:58:32.320 --> 00:58:33.560
[Guest 2]: So we're screwed.

00:58:33.560 --> 00:58:35.760
[Guest 2]: So let me just respond to Shruti very quickly.

00:58:35.760 --> 00:58:40.680
[Guest 2]: So the first point about the fact that, yeah, of course, it's very easy politically to spend

00:58:40.680 --> 00:58:43.840
[Guest 2]: and of course, unpopular to tax, which is the case everywhere.

00:58:43.840 --> 00:58:46.520
[Guest 2]: But it's also and since we're talking of dream reforms here, right?

00:58:46.520 --> 00:58:52.320
[Guest 2]: It is imperative for the government to people also vote on the basis of what kind of public

00:58:52.320 --> 00:58:55.520
[Guest 2]: goods they have access to, whether they have a road next to their house through which they

00:58:55.520 --> 00:58:58.800
[Guest 2]: can go to the school, whether they have a school that they can they can learn to after

00:58:58.800 --> 00:59:01.800
[Guest 2]: the school, do they actually have a job, do they have the train connection.

00:59:01.800 --> 00:59:06.440
[Guest 2]: So people also vote on the basis of the public goods that they have access to, and not just

00:59:06.440 --> 00:59:08.680
[Guest 2]: on the basis of whether they are taxing more or less, right.

00:59:08.680 --> 00:59:13.520
[Guest 2]: And so if and given a fact in a situation where there are people who are accessing the

00:59:13.520 --> 00:59:16.800
[Guest 2]: public goods, and that's critical to them and not really the ones who are paying taxes,

00:59:16.800 --> 00:59:17.800
[Guest 2]: right.

00:59:17.800 --> 00:59:22.160
[Guest 2]: So if the government believes in this, that, okay, we have to basically win election on

00:59:22.160 --> 00:59:26.920
[Guest 2]: the basis of the public goods that we are providing, and not on the basis of this fiscal

00:59:26.920 --> 00:59:30.120
[Guest 2]: jugglery that we are doing, then it's not impossible.

00:59:30.120 --> 00:59:35.080
[Guest 2]: And it's not required that the all the people of the country don't need to understand that

00:59:35.080 --> 00:59:36.880
[Guest 2]: what the complicated fiscal math is.

00:59:36.880 --> 00:59:41.400
[Guest 2]: And this is something that is strongly believe in, we are not running the government in Twitter,

00:59:41.400 --> 00:59:46.960
[Guest 2]: we do not and should not continuously care about what all the people of the country want,

00:59:46.960 --> 00:59:49.680
[Guest 2]: you know, I mean, all the people of the country will want something that may not be good for

00:59:49.680 --> 00:59:53.200
[Guest 2]: the country, because they may not be aware of what is really good for the country.

00:59:53.200 --> 00:59:54.640
[Guest 2]: And that's perfectly fine.

00:59:54.640 --> 00:59:58.800
[Guest 2]: But if we tell them that we are giving you the services and the goods that you need,

00:59:58.800 --> 01:00:03.480
[Guest 2]: and we are not taxing you, that is a very, it's a nice dream world to have.

01:00:03.480 --> 01:00:07.960
[Guest 2]: And as I said, you don't literacy and education, of course, it is very important, but because

01:00:07.960 --> 01:00:13.200
[Guest 2]: we don't have it does not mean that we will reach a situation that as and when the population

01:00:13.200 --> 01:00:18.960
[Guest 2]: is literate, like Germany, only then we can aspire to have a debt GDP ratio, which is

01:00:18.960 --> 01:00:19.960
[Guest 2]: 60%.

01:00:19.960 --> 01:00:22.040
[Guest 2]: I don't think these two are should be connected.

01:00:22.040 --> 01:00:26.760
[Guest 2]: And, and the the last point I want to make is, yes, I agree that Indian Constitution

01:00:26.760 --> 01:00:29.000
[Guest 2]: is the most amended one in the world.

01:00:29.000 --> 01:00:30.800
[Guest 2]: And it is very easy to amend it.

01:00:30.800 --> 01:00:35.000
[Guest 2]: But my point is that what I the German debt break, I was using as an example, that something

01:00:35.000 --> 01:00:39.480
[Guest 2]: which is that tight something which is that enshrined in the law of the land, because

01:00:39.480 --> 01:00:43.720
[Guest 2]: clearly, there's some kind of a willingness because we did pass the FRBM Act.

01:00:43.720 --> 01:00:46.000
[Guest 2]: And we do keep mentioning FRBM every year.

01:00:46.000 --> 01:00:51.040
[Guest 2]: So there is some awareness, vague consciousness that okay, we need to be on the fiscal path.

01:00:51.040 --> 01:00:55.880
[Guest 2]: But there is nothing which is of consequence, because in any country, it is difficult to

01:00:55.880 --> 01:00:58.480
[Guest 2]: tie the hands of the government, because who will tie the hands of the government, the

01:00:58.480 --> 01:00:59.960
[Guest 2]: government itself.

01:00:59.960 --> 01:01:03.600
[Guest 2]: So it is very difficult, it is very tricky to tie the hands of the government, because

01:01:03.600 --> 01:01:05.520
[Guest 2]: the government itself will have to do it.

01:01:05.520 --> 01:01:10.240
[Guest 2]: Now, the reason I said constitutional amendment is because even if it is easy, but it's still

01:01:10.240 --> 01:01:14.980
[Guest 2]: relatively harder than just violating an FRBM Act without any consequence.

01:01:14.980 --> 01:01:20.000
[Guest 2]: But my point is to dream and think of some kind of a structure which will really tie

01:01:20.000 --> 01:01:24.360
[Guest 2]: the hands of the government so tight, that to violate it, there will be some consequence.

01:01:24.360 --> 01:01:27.400
[Guest 2]: Of course, you can argue that a government can do anything and there's no consequence,

01:01:27.400 --> 01:01:29.040
[Guest 2]: of course, with that caveat.

01:01:29.040 --> 01:01:32.920
[Guest 2]: Because otherwise, as you said, we will end up in a situation where the government will

01:01:32.920 --> 01:01:35.920
[Guest 2]: keep conning us for generation after generation.

01:01:35.920 --> 01:01:40.520
[Guest 2]: And we will never be able to move out of this state that the economy is in.

01:01:40.520 --> 01:01:44.480
[Guest 1]: I would say, you know, the German example is pertinent, because you have to understand

01:01:44.480 --> 01:01:47.000
[Guest 1]: where the causation of the constraint comes from.

01:01:47.000 --> 01:01:48.680
[Guest 1]: It comes from the people.

01:01:48.680 --> 01:01:50.680
[Guest 1]: It doesn't come from the constitution.

01:01:50.680 --> 01:01:56.320
[Guest 1]: The constitution is the manifestation of what the people of Germany really care about, which

01:01:56.320 --> 01:02:00.040
[Guest 1]: is, you know, tight fiscal discipline.

01:02:00.040 --> 01:02:06.400
[Guest 1]: As long as in majoritarian politics, where the majority gets to amend the constitution

01:02:06.400 --> 01:02:13.080
[Guest 1]: and do it over and over again, if the people genuinely don't care about this, and since

01:02:13.080 --> 01:02:17.840
[Guest 1]: we're talking about the dream reform, right, like, if we genuinely don't have people who

01:02:17.840 --> 01:02:20.880
[Guest 1]: care about fiscal discipline, you're not going to get it.

01:02:20.880 --> 01:02:24.560
[Guest 2]: So I don't agree that people don't care about fiscal discipline, for example, people don't

01:02:24.560 --> 01:02:25.560
[Guest 2]: think about fiscal discipline.

01:02:25.560 --> 01:02:29.240
[Guest 2]: Every time there is a budget, there are enough people, people are writing and thinking and

01:02:29.240 --> 01:02:30.240
[Guest 1]: discussing.

01:02:30.240 --> 01:02:31.240
[Guest 1]: Those are not the people I'm talking about.

01:02:31.240 --> 01:02:32.240
[Guest 2]: No, but that's what I'm saying.

01:02:32.240 --> 01:02:36.720
[Guest 2]: I think if we keep thinking that all the people of the country will have to care about a reform

01:02:36.720 --> 01:02:37.960
[Amit Varma]: for that reform to happen.

01:02:37.960 --> 01:02:41.480
[Guest 1]: I think Rajeshwari's point is that elite shaped the discourse.

01:02:41.480 --> 01:02:46.360
[Guest 1]: I know the point, but that's why we have so much of the elite signaling, we passed FRBM

01:02:46.360 --> 01:02:50.280
[Guest 1]: because we wanted to pretend to the rest of the world, we are open for business, right?

01:02:50.280 --> 01:02:55.120
[Guest 2]: So Oh, India, we also passed FRBM because we did realize that having a fiscally profligate

01:02:55.120 --> 01:02:56.480
[Guest 2]: government is not good for the economy.

01:02:56.480 --> 01:02:57.480
[Unknown]: I understand.

01:02:57.480 --> 01:03:02.280
[Guest 1]: But I'm saying, it's the means to other ends, which is, you know, we want more private investment

01:03:02.280 --> 01:03:03.800
[Amit Varma]: in FDI and so on.

01:03:03.800 --> 01:03:07.920
[Amit Varma]: Part of the dream and dream reform, which she is mentioning, and I share the dream is

01:03:07.920 --> 01:03:11.680
[Amit Varma]: that we have a constitution, which is which actually means something and as you and I

01:03:11.680 --> 01:03:13.720
[Amit Varma]: would agree, it doesn't mean anything, it doesn't mean anything.

01:03:13.720 --> 01:03:17.200
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, the whole purpose of a constitution in the kind of republic that

01:03:17.200 --> 01:03:22.120
[Amit Varma]: we dream of is a constitution that is a restraint on government and which ties the hands of

01:03:22.120 --> 01:03:23.120
[Amit Varma]: government as she correctly said.

01:03:23.120 --> 01:03:24.120
[Guest 1]: It hasn't tied the hands of government.

01:03:24.120 --> 01:03:25.120
[Unknown]: At all.

01:03:25.120 --> 01:03:26.120
[Amit Varma]: Sure.

01:03:26.120 --> 01:03:27.120
[Unknown]: But what is happening in Kashmir?

01:03:27.120 --> 01:03:28.120
[Unknown]: Since we are dreaming.

01:03:28.120 --> 01:03:32.320
[Unknown]: We passed a constitutional amendment by voice vote with the president signing this deal.

01:03:32.320 --> 01:03:42.360
[Amit Varma]: If you're going to talk about reforms, which are feasible in the current setup of the government,

01:03:42.360 --> 01:03:44.640
[Guest 2]: then there is nothing called a dream reform.

01:03:44.640 --> 01:03:51.440
[Guest 3]: So because we are dreaming, let's let's have Vivek take the middle path.

01:03:51.440 --> 01:03:56.040
[Guest 3]: So see, one of the biggest problems in reforms in India, I mean, has been the fact that it's

01:03:56.040 --> 01:03:58.240
[Guest 3]: always been reformed by stealth.

01:03:58.240 --> 01:04:03.640
[Guest 3]: No politician has ever bothered to sit and explain to the electorate, you know, this

01:04:03.640 --> 01:04:04.860
[Guest 3]: is why we're doing this.

01:04:04.860 --> 01:04:07.200
[Guest 3]: This is why let's say we introduce a tax.

01:04:07.200 --> 01:04:10.760
[Guest 3]: So this is the reason we are introducing this tax or anything for that matter.

01:04:10.760 --> 01:04:13.560
[Guest 3]: I mean, let's say the government decides to shut down Air India.

01:04:13.560 --> 01:04:14.560
[Guest 3]: Okay.

01:04:14.560 --> 01:04:17.360
[Guest 3]: So somebody is going to explain it to the people never happens.

01:04:17.360 --> 01:04:22.000
[Guest 3]: The only time I've seen, you know, a little bit of it happening was when Narendra Modi

01:04:22.000 --> 01:04:24.360
[Guest 3]: tried to push in the Land Acquisition Act.

01:04:24.360 --> 01:04:26.440
[Guest 3]: He did one episode on Man Ki Baat.

01:04:26.440 --> 01:04:32.840
[Guest 3]: Uske baad, what happened was, you know, Rahul Gandhi made that sootboot ki sarkar jaib and

01:04:32.840 --> 01:04:33.840
[Guest 3]: we were done.

01:04:33.840 --> 01:04:35.280
[Guest 3]: We went back to where we were.

01:04:35.280 --> 01:04:40.480
[Guest 3]: So unless politicians take a lead here and start explaining things to people, and which

01:04:40.480 --> 01:04:45.920
[Guest 3]: is very easy these days, you know, I mean, look at the kind of all, you know, fake news,

01:04:45.920 --> 01:04:50.840
[Guest 3]: which keeps going around in the, you know, on the social media.

01:04:50.840 --> 01:04:55.040
[Guest 3]: I mean, there are multiple ways of reaching people these days, which are not there.

01:04:55.040 --> 01:04:57.160
[Guest 1]: So it has to start from the top.

01:04:57.160 --> 01:04:58.160
[Guest 1]: I mean, otherwise, it's not.

01:04:58.160 --> 01:05:03.800
[Guest 1]: I have one of my reforms caters to this point, but from the bottom, we'll come to it a little

01:05:03.800 --> 01:05:04.800
[Amit Varma]: later.

01:05:04.800 --> 01:05:09.880
[Amit Varma]: But I would add there that we can't rely on politicians, but we can rely on incentives,

01:05:09.880 --> 01:05:15.400
[Amit Varma]: which gives me the slightly dismal hope that it is only a massive crisis, which absolutely

01:05:15.400 --> 01:05:18.760
[Amit Varma]: forces change, which will help us in any way.

01:05:18.760 --> 01:05:25.160
[Guest 3]: Yes, but see, again, you know, the point there is that, you know, if the economy keeps getting

01:05:25.160 --> 01:05:29.320
[Amit Varma]: reformed, only when there is a crisis, exactly, I agree with you, we'll never reach anywhere.

01:05:29.320 --> 01:05:31.160
[Amit Varma]: No, no, no, we have to stop this doom and gloom.

01:05:31.160 --> 01:05:34.920
[Amit Varma]: We need to take a break and come back sunshiny and cheerful.

