[Amit Varma]: I have with me Shruti Rajgopalan, Vivek Kaul, Rajeshwari Sengupta, in the order that we

01:07:54.400 --> 01:07:56.320
[Amit Varma]: will go through our next reforms.

01:07:56.320 --> 01:08:00.120
[Amit Varma]: Reform number four, Shruti's reform number two, coming up now.

01:08:00.120 --> 01:08:06.100
[Guest 1]: Yeah, so my next big reform actually coincides well with the point that Rajeshwari made about

01:08:06.100 --> 01:08:07.100
[Guest 1]: fiscal discipline.

01:08:07.100 --> 01:08:10.120
[Guest 1]: Though that's not the only goal of this reform.

01:08:10.120 --> 01:08:15.320
[Guest 1]: So I wish India to be more fiscally federal, right?

01:08:15.320 --> 01:08:19.320
[Guest 1]: So India, I mean, India's federal structure is very centripetal.

01:08:19.320 --> 01:08:24.620
[Guest 1]: So I don't know, we are all different generations here, but my generation read civics books

01:08:24.620 --> 01:08:29.060
[Guest 1]: that said India is a federal country with a unitary bias.

01:08:29.060 --> 01:08:31.480
[Guest 1]: Is that what yours also read?

01:08:31.480 --> 01:08:32.480
[Amit Varma]: Something like that?

01:08:32.480 --> 01:08:33.480
[Amit Varma]: I have to hold to remember civics.

01:08:33.480 --> 01:08:37.760
[Guest 1]: And no, I remember the sentence because I went around asking everyone what the hell

01:08:37.760 --> 01:08:39.040
[Guest 1]: this means.

01:08:39.040 --> 01:08:40.280
[Guest 1]: And now I figured out what it means.

01:08:40.280 --> 01:08:42.440
[Guest 1]: It means India is not federal.

01:08:42.440 --> 01:08:47.560
[Guest 1]: And so, you know, one of the core reasons is there is an administrative federalism,

01:08:47.560 --> 01:08:49.040
[Guest 1]: but there is no fiscal federalism.

01:08:49.040 --> 01:08:53.880
[Guest 1]: And what I mean by that is our taxes and spending are highly centralized, right?

01:08:53.880 --> 01:08:58.880
[Guest 1]: Now less and less so in the last 25 years or so, we have this fine establishment called

01:08:58.880 --> 01:09:02.640
[Guest 1]: the Finance Commission, where all our taxes, you know, think of it as sort of, you know,

01:09:02.640 --> 01:09:06.880
[Guest 1]: you collect all the taxes in one basket, and then the finance, it would go to the Finance

01:09:06.880 --> 01:09:12.760
[Guest 1]: Commission, not physically, but the idea of it, and they would make a split between how

01:09:12.760 --> 01:09:15.560
[Guest 1]: much the center gets and how much the state gets.

01:09:15.560 --> 01:09:17.920
[Guest 1]: And there are a whole number of ways to figure this out.

01:09:17.920 --> 01:09:21.160
[Guest 1]: One was, you know, union government was really under central planning.

01:09:21.160 --> 01:09:22.320
[Guest 1]: That's one part.

01:09:22.320 --> 01:09:27.720
[Guest 1]: The other part was, you know, depending on how poor the state is, or how much development

01:09:27.720 --> 01:09:31.660
[Guest 1]: it needs, or how much infrastructure needs to be built, get more money or less money.

01:09:31.660 --> 01:09:33.200
[Guest 1]: This is a giant rent-seeking exercise.

01:09:33.200 --> 01:09:38.240
[Guest 1]: There have been papers written on how, you know, this kind of fiscal control was used

01:09:38.240 --> 01:09:40.280
[Guest 1]: to punish opposition governments.

01:09:40.280 --> 01:09:44.680
[Guest 1]: So if you're the same party in the state forming government as the center, you could, you know,

01:09:44.680 --> 01:09:49.680
[Guest 1]: tend to get more money, then I think Stuti Khemani at the World Bank has written on this.

01:09:49.680 --> 01:09:53.640
[Guest 1]: And you know, if you're an opposition party forming a government in a state, they deny

01:09:53.640 --> 01:09:56.360
[Guest 1]: you the budget, and that's how they hold up.

01:09:56.360 --> 01:10:02.040
[Guest 1]: So one of the big, there are three reasons I want to see more fiscal federalism.

01:10:02.040 --> 01:10:06.280
[Guest 1]: The first is, we want more public goods.

01:10:06.280 --> 01:10:10.680
[Guest 1]: And what we mean by more public goods, most of the time, is we want the garbage outside

01:10:10.680 --> 01:10:12.280
[Guest 1]: our house to be picked up.

01:10:12.280 --> 01:10:16.140
[Guest 1]: We want better roads, we, you know, we all managed to get here on time.

01:10:16.140 --> 01:10:22.520
[Guest 1]: But I got here on time because I sort of accounted for 25-30 minute delay, which turned out to

01:10:22.520 --> 01:10:26.480
[Guest 1]: be true, because it's pouring in Bombay, and you know, every road is dug up, and it's a

01:10:26.480 --> 01:10:27.560
[Guest 1]: total mess.

01:10:27.560 --> 01:10:32.480
[Guest 1]: We would like to have better public infrastructure, right, we'd like airports to be better, trains

01:10:32.480 --> 01:10:34.480
[Guest 1]: to be better.

01:10:34.480 --> 01:10:38.000
[Guest 1]: We would like public schooling to be better, which is, you know, one function is the reforms

01:10:38.000 --> 01:10:40.180
[Guest 1]: we talked about, the other is expenditure.

01:10:40.180 --> 01:10:45.360
[Guest 1]: So we would like to see a lot of spending at the local municipal level.

01:10:45.360 --> 01:10:48.000
[Guest 1]: And our municipal governments have no money.

01:10:48.000 --> 01:10:49.000
[Guest 3]: And the reason for that...

01:10:49.000 --> 01:10:50.000
[Guest 3]: Except for BMC.

01:10:50.000 --> 01:10:51.000
[Guest 3]: Except for BMC.

01:10:51.000 --> 01:10:56.640
[Guest 1]: Yeah, which is a very rich, because they're building the metro, which is a very rich municipal

01:10:56.640 --> 01:10:57.640
[Guest 1]: corporation.

01:10:57.640 --> 01:11:04.000
[Guest 1]: But overall, the centre devolves money to the states, and then the state has the option

01:11:04.000 --> 01:11:05.200
[Guest 1]: of devolving money.

01:11:05.200 --> 01:11:09.040
[Guest 1]: So you know, like, there's a central finance commission, every state has its own finance

01:11:09.040 --> 01:11:12.800
[Guest 1]: commission post the 73rd and 74th amendment.

01:11:12.800 --> 01:11:16.160
[Guest 1]: And depending on whether you're talking about the rural or the urban areas, the state is

01:11:16.160 --> 01:11:19.380
[Guest 1]: supposed to devolve finances to local government.

01:11:19.380 --> 01:11:21.200
[Guest 1]: That is not a condition.

01:11:21.200 --> 01:11:22.200
[Guest 1]: It's not mandatory.

01:11:22.200 --> 01:11:23.200
[Guest 1]: Right?

01:11:23.200 --> 01:11:24.200
[Guest 1]: It's a choice.

01:11:24.200 --> 01:11:28.480
[Guest 1]: So what ends up happening is, the states are spending a lot of money.

01:11:28.480 --> 01:11:31.000
[Guest 1]: And the union governments are spending a lot of money.

01:11:31.000 --> 01:11:34.040
[Guest 1]: But they're spending it on all useless things, as Rajeshwari pointed out, right?

01:11:34.040 --> 01:11:36.480
[Guest 1]: They're not spending it on the things we care about.

01:11:36.480 --> 01:11:41.840
[Guest 1]: So you can have government spending, which causes both stimulus, also builds infrastructure

01:11:41.840 --> 01:11:45.160
[Guest 1]: and also delivers public goods to the people who need it the most.

01:11:45.160 --> 01:11:46.360
[Guest 1]: But the money never goes there.

01:11:46.360 --> 01:11:51.480
[Guest 1]: The money goes to satisfy special interests with these freebies that are highly targeted

01:11:51.480 --> 01:11:55.920
[Guest 1]: to capture one vote bank or another, or you know, for uptakes like this whole toilet building

01:11:55.920 --> 01:11:59.800
[Guest 1]: thing with just you know, I mean, then I've talked about it just drives us crazy.

01:11:59.800 --> 01:12:05.800
[Guest 1]: So one huge, you know, this is one reform, which can sort of kill a lot of birds with

01:12:05.800 --> 01:12:07.320
[Guest 1]: one stone.

01:12:07.320 --> 01:12:10.660
[Guest 1]: One part of it is municipal governments will be more empowered.

01:12:10.660 --> 01:12:14.720
[Guest 1]: So I get this idea from all the condo associations that I see, you know, they collect this common

01:12:14.720 --> 01:12:19.700
[Guest 1]: charges of fees that you see in Bombay and Delhi, and actually spend that money, right?

01:12:19.700 --> 01:12:24.440
[Guest 1]: And when you go to these condo association meetings, people are really up in arms about

01:12:24.440 --> 01:12:29.720
[Guest 1]: an increased charge or you know, you took money to build a you know, water filtration

01:12:29.720 --> 01:12:31.840
[Guest 1]: plant and then never got built and there's all this.

01:12:31.840 --> 01:12:37.440
[Guest 1]: So there's a lot of local politics, which can be tied to fiscal feedback.

01:12:37.440 --> 01:12:39.360
[Guest 1]: And that's an opportunity we're missing right now.

01:12:39.360 --> 01:12:40.360
[Guest 1]: Right?

01:12:40.360 --> 01:12:42.300
[Guest 1]: So the municipal corporator, no one knows his name.

01:12:42.300 --> 01:12:43.860
[Guest 1]: That's one problem.

01:12:43.860 --> 01:12:45.640
[Guest 1]: So this will solve that problem.

01:12:45.640 --> 01:12:50.520
[Guest 1]: The second problem it will solve is, it will divide the functions of different levels of

01:12:50.520 --> 01:12:52.160
[Guest 1]: government much better.

01:12:52.160 --> 01:12:53.200
[Guest 1]: Right?

01:12:53.200 --> 01:12:59.280
[Guest 1]: So the union government is supposed to maintain law and order at the highest level, right?

01:12:59.280 --> 01:13:05.000
[Guest 1]: Interstate highways, interstate river water, right, foreign trade, of course, safety and

01:13:05.000 --> 01:13:06.800
[Guest 1]: security of the country, right?

01:13:06.800 --> 01:13:11.520
[Guest 1]: That's all that kind of expenditure, or you know, large externalities, like pollution

01:13:11.520 --> 01:13:12.520
[Guest 1]: across states.

01:13:12.520 --> 01:13:15.640
[Guest 1]: That's really the job of the union government.

01:13:15.640 --> 01:13:20.760
[Guest 1]: Everything within the state, which is your, you know, local highway, all your public parks,

01:13:20.760 --> 01:13:23.760
[Guest 1]: you know, which are going beyond municipal boundaries.

01:13:23.760 --> 01:13:27.440
[Guest 1]: That's the job of the state government and then, you know, lower level further municipal

01:13:27.440 --> 01:13:28.440
[Guest 1]: government.

01:13:28.440 --> 01:13:31.440
[Guest 1]: And we just don't have that clean demarcation.

01:13:31.440 --> 01:13:36.040
[Guest 1]: But the moment you make a demarcation with money, the demarcation and goods will be a

01:13:36.040 --> 01:13:40.440
[Guest 1]: little bit more, it won't be automatic, it won't happen overnight, but it will happen

01:13:40.440 --> 01:13:41.440
[Guest 1]: over a period of time.

01:13:41.440 --> 01:13:42.440
[Guest 1]: Right?

01:13:42.440 --> 01:13:46.840
[Guest 1]: And if you look at the state spending in a place like Maharashtra, disproportionate amount

01:13:46.840 --> 01:13:50.880
[Guest 1]: goes to rural and farmers freebies, right?

01:13:50.880 --> 01:13:55.140
[Guest 1]: Even though Maharashtra has been urbanizing at a very rapid pace, right?

01:13:55.140 --> 01:14:00.120
[Guest 1]: And that doesn't get reflected and the spending is at the state level.

01:14:00.120 --> 01:14:06.320
[Guest 1]: And Mumbai citizens are underrepresented in votes and overrepresented in revenue giving,

01:14:06.320 --> 01:14:07.320
[Guest 1]: but not in expenditure.

01:14:07.320 --> 01:14:10.680
[Amit Varma]: In fact, you and I had an episode on this on urban governance where we spoke about the

01:14:10.680 --> 01:14:13.000
[Guest 1]: mismatch between power and accountability.

01:14:13.000 --> 01:14:14.000
[Guest 1]: Exactly.

01:14:14.000 --> 01:14:15.000
[Guest 1]: So that's the second part, right?

01:14:15.000 --> 01:14:16.480
[Guest 1]: So first is we actually get public goods.

01:14:16.480 --> 01:14:20.920
[Guest 1]: The second solution is it actually demarcates what each level of government is supposed

01:14:20.920 --> 01:14:21.920
[Guest 1]: to do and can do.

01:14:21.920 --> 01:14:26.920
[Guest 1]: And the third part is tying the hands of government, which is what Rajeshwari was talking about.

01:14:26.920 --> 01:14:31.360
[Guest 1]: I think this is a bottom up way of tying the hands of government, right?

01:14:31.360 --> 01:14:38.080
[Guest 1]: You allot different fiscal resources and therefore different levels of fiscal accountability.

01:14:38.080 --> 01:14:41.520
[Guest 1]: I would like to live in a world where the maximum spending is done by the municipal

01:14:41.520 --> 01:14:46.080
[Guest 1]: government because that has the tightest feedback level, right, at that level.

01:14:46.080 --> 01:14:49.780
[Guest 1]: And also that's where we use the public resources the most.

01:14:49.780 --> 01:14:54.080
[Guest 1]: You want a public library, you want a public park, you want poor children in your area

01:14:54.080 --> 01:14:59.640
[Guest 1]: to have, you know, certain things despite their income level, which is, you know, access

01:14:59.640 --> 01:15:02.160
[Guest 1]: to schools and access to water and access to vaccination.

01:15:02.160 --> 01:15:04.100
[Guest 1]: So that's what I would like to see.

01:15:04.100 --> 01:15:05.100
[Guest 1]: So that's the second part.

01:15:05.100 --> 01:15:09.120
[Guest 1]: Now, the fiscal responsibility, because of the tight feedback, you automatically, you

01:15:09.120 --> 01:15:12.320
[Guest 1]: know, you first of all create a check between government.

01:15:12.320 --> 01:15:16.000
[Guest 1]: So there's a horizontal separation of powers, but there's also a vertical separation of

01:15:16.000 --> 01:15:17.120
[Guest 1]: powers, right?

01:15:17.120 --> 01:15:21.080
[Guest 1]: So this way, municipal government, state government and union government have to fight over the

01:15:21.080 --> 01:15:27.360
[Guest 1]: size of the pie and how they split it, which is a really good check for each other.

01:15:27.360 --> 01:15:33.280
[Guest 1]: And the second is, this is a bottom up way of really tying the hands of the union government,

01:15:33.280 --> 01:15:37.200
[Guest 1]: which is what is doing a bulk of the sharing of the spending.

01:15:37.200 --> 01:15:40.640
[Guest 1]: And that's why it is so mistargeted, right?

01:15:40.640 --> 01:15:44.340
[Guest 1]: So you absolutely right, you know, both Rajeshwari and Vivek have said, we've been in some kind

01:15:44.340 --> 01:15:46.400
[Guest 1]: of stimulus mode for the last two years.

01:15:46.400 --> 01:15:51.600
[Guest 1]: It's just it's not working like a stimulus, because it's all nonsense that we're spending

01:15:51.600 --> 01:15:52.600
[Guest 1]: on.

01:15:52.600 --> 01:15:57.320
[Guest 1]: So you can also stimulate the economy, you can, you have different livers to pull, you

01:15:57.320 --> 01:16:01.680
[Guest 1]: have more sophisticated livers to pull, though I don't believe in that kind of like hydraulic

01:16:01.680 --> 01:16:02.680
[Guest 1]: Keynesianism.

01:16:02.680 --> 01:16:06.680
[Guest 1]: But even if you were of that school, you have more sophisticated livers to pull when you

01:16:06.680 --> 01:16:09.600
[Guest 1]: can split fiscal levels.

01:16:09.600 --> 01:16:13.360
[Amit Varma]: And what also strikes me is that this would then change incentives.

01:16:13.360 --> 01:16:18.860
[Amit Varma]: Because the point is, if you know, local neighborhoods are so empowered and are doing so much spending,

01:16:18.860 --> 01:16:23.000
[Amit Varma]: people can vote with their feet and go to where the governance is the best, which improves

01:16:23.000 --> 01:16:24.000
[Guest 1]: everybody's incentives.

01:16:24.000 --> 01:16:27.880
[Guest 1]: Yeah, and voting with your feet is naturally much easier when the geographical distances

01:16:27.880 --> 01:16:29.080
[Guest 1]: are small, right?

01:16:29.080 --> 01:16:32.240
[Guest 1]: You can go from Khar to Juhu and Juhu to Andheri much more easily.

01:16:32.240 --> 01:16:34.480
[Guest 1]: Then you can go from Maharashtra to Gujarat, right?

01:16:34.480 --> 01:16:38.280
[Guest 1]: Or from India to Pakistan, which is what people keep telling me I should be doing, right?

01:16:38.280 --> 01:16:44.800
[Guest 1]: So this is one kind of voting with your feet, which is made lower cost, because voting with

01:16:44.800 --> 01:16:48.320
[Guest 1]: your feet comes with a constraint, you have to uproot your whole life.

01:16:48.320 --> 01:16:51.320
[Guest 1]: So that's one part that makes the feedback mechanism tighter.

01:16:51.320 --> 01:16:55.920
[Guest 1]: The second part that makes the feedback mechanism tighter is your voters are your taxpayers.

01:16:55.920 --> 01:16:59.560
[Guest 1]: So there is much, you know, even though first of all, all of us are not voting for Modi

01:16:59.560 --> 01:17:03.160
[Guest 1]: ji, right, it's a representative system.

01:17:03.160 --> 01:17:07.760
[Guest 1]: The second is, all of us are not paying taxes, right?

01:17:07.760 --> 01:17:11.160
[Guest 1]: So there is this really big problem of everyone who voted for Modi ji and everyone who is

01:17:11.160 --> 01:17:13.040
[Guest 1]: paying taxes to Modi ji.

01:17:13.040 --> 01:17:16.680
[Guest 1]: And I say Modi ji because he's the one really, you know, in control, right?

01:17:16.680 --> 01:17:18.440
[Guest 1]: That's not a slip of the tongue.

01:17:18.440 --> 01:17:21.240
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, please don't ask Shruti to go to Pakistan, people.

01:17:21.240 --> 01:17:23.960
[Guest 1]: No, you can ask me, I would love to visit.

01:17:23.960 --> 01:17:24.960
[Guest 1]: She'll go via Dubai.

01:17:24.960 --> 01:17:26.960
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, when people ask me to go to Pakistan

01:17:26.960 --> 01:17:29.520
[Guest 1]: Or via United States, which is where I live.

01:17:29.520 --> 01:17:32.840
[Amit Varma]: When people ask me to go to Pakistan, I say, been there, done that, I mean, which is true.

01:17:32.840 --> 01:17:33.840
[Guest 1]: I haven't been there.

01:17:33.840 --> 01:17:34.840
[Guest 1]: I'd love to go.

01:17:34.840 --> 01:17:35.840
[Guest 1]: I have no problem.

01:17:35.840 --> 01:17:39.920
[Guest 1]: I just have a problem with people ordering me on what my travel plans should be.

01:17:39.920 --> 01:17:41.680
[Guest 2]: That is what I'm most offended by.

01:17:41.680 --> 01:17:45.520
[Guest 2]: So essentially, you're talking of a more decentralization kind of thing.

01:17:45.520 --> 01:17:49.960
[Guest 1]: No, I'm actually not talking about decentralization, I'm talking about genuine fiscal federalism.

01:17:49.960 --> 01:17:52.520
[Guest 1]: What we have right now is decentralization.

01:17:52.520 --> 01:17:55.960
[Guest 1]: And I'll tell you what I think the difference is.

01:17:55.960 --> 01:18:00.320
[Guest 1]: Decentralization is that the head decides what the hand will get, right?

01:18:00.320 --> 01:18:04.640
[Guest 1]: I am the center, you are my sub-center and I'm going to

01:18:04.640 --> 01:18:08.880
[Guest 1]: Federalism requires that they own separate power centers, right?

01:18:08.880 --> 01:18:13.400
[Guest 1]: What we have in India is a very large degree of decentralization without federalism, which

01:18:13.400 --> 01:18:17.160
[Guest 1]: is, you know, I don't want to just pull Kashmir into everything, but a very large part of

01:18:17.160 --> 01:18:22.080
[Guest 1]: the uproar that came from Tamil Nadu and the other states, actually very little uproar,

01:18:22.080 --> 01:18:26.080
[Guest 1]: according to me, but you know, one part of the uproar was that, you know, we're all states

01:18:26.080 --> 01:18:29.280
[Guest 1]: until we are union territories when we are, right?

01:18:29.280 --> 01:18:34.600
[Guest 1]: Which is really true because we are all really agents of the union government, which is not

01:18:34.600 --> 01:18:35.600
[Guest 1]: true.

01:18:35.600 --> 01:18:38.640
[Guest 1]: We're not the central government of India, we're a union of states, right?

01:18:38.640 --> 01:18:39.640
[Guest 1]: So we're never

01:18:39.640 --> 01:18:43.320
[Guest 1]: If you look at the constitution, the central government is called the union government,

01:18:43.320 --> 01:18:44.320
[Guest 1]: right?

01:18:44.320 --> 01:18:49.160
[Guest 1]: It's the union of states, but it never set it up as such because you can't just administratively

01:18:49.160 --> 01:18:52.800
[Guest 1]: make a union and not give them any revenue raising capacity.

01:18:52.800 --> 01:18:56.240
[Guest 1]: That's what makes a federal government, a federal government.

01:18:56.240 --> 01:19:01.800
[Guest 1]: So right now we are centripetal because we have three lists, but we have enough loopholes

01:19:01.800 --> 01:19:06.200
[Guest 1]: in the constitution that the center can usurp any of the three lists completely, right?

01:19:06.200 --> 01:19:07.560
[Guest 1]: And there's enough vagueness there.

01:19:07.560 --> 01:19:08.640
[Guest 1]: So that's one.

01:19:08.640 --> 01:19:13.120
[Guest 1]: That is not the case in genuinely federal countries like Switzerland or United States

01:19:13.120 --> 01:19:14.120
[Guest 1]: and so on.

01:19:14.120 --> 01:19:16.680
[Guest 1]: The second part of it is, of course, the fiscal map.

01:19:16.680 --> 01:19:23.760
[Guest 1]: The third part of it is, all the ancillary services we provide are highly centripetal,

01:19:23.760 --> 01:19:24.760
[Guest 1]: right?

01:19:24.760 --> 01:19:29.000
[Guest 1]: The union Supreme Court, which is the only Supreme Court we have, that determines what

01:19:29.000 --> 01:19:31.960
[Guest 1]: every high court will do, right?

01:19:31.960 --> 01:19:33.160
[Guest 1]: Every state high court.

01:19:33.160 --> 01:19:36.720
[Guest 1]: So now this comes down in culture.

01:19:36.720 --> 01:19:40.880
[Guest 1]: You know, there is a system by which, you know, your planning commission at the center,

01:19:40.880 --> 01:19:42.800
[Guest 2]: every state planning commission is like

01:19:42.800 --> 01:19:45.640
[Guest 2]: Actually, this has very interesting implications for financing.

01:19:45.640 --> 01:19:46.640
[Guest 2]: For financing.

01:19:46.640 --> 01:19:51.000
[Guest 2]: For example, instead of a finance commission distributing across different states, etc.

01:19:51.000 --> 01:19:54.400
[Guest 2]: Something that I have thought about for quite some time is a very small thing like a municipal

01:19:54.400 --> 01:19:55.400
[Guest 2]: bond.

01:19:55.400 --> 01:19:56.400
[Guest 2]: Yeah.

01:19:56.400 --> 01:19:59.720
[Guest 2]: You know, I mean, it's like in Bombay or other municipalities, instead of waiting for some

01:19:59.720 --> 01:20:02.400
[Guest 2]: funding to come, why can't we just issue municipal bonds?

01:20:02.400 --> 01:20:03.400
[Guest 2]: Or tax it.

01:20:03.400 --> 01:20:04.400
[Guest 2]: Exactly.

01:20:04.400 --> 01:20:05.400
[Guest 1]: Or tax it.

01:20:05.400 --> 01:20:08.440
[Guest 1]: People of Bombay are paying enough tax and are happy to spend it on resources instead

01:20:08.440 --> 01:20:09.680
[Guest 2]: of, you know, going through potholes.

01:20:09.680 --> 01:20:13.000
[Guest 2]: So since we are dreaming, I'll just, Vivek, just give me two minutes.

01:20:13.000 --> 01:20:16.120
[Guest 2]: I'll just take off on a little bit of another tangent, but related.

01:20:16.120 --> 01:20:20.640
[Guest 2]: Since we are dreaming is how about now we all know that the cities of India are really

01:20:20.640 --> 01:20:21.640
[Guest 2]: struggling, right?

01:20:21.640 --> 01:20:22.640
[Guest 2]: There's a water crisis.

01:20:22.640 --> 01:20:26.800
[Guest 2]: There's an infrastructure crisis in Bombay, in Madras, in Calcutta, wherever, right?

01:20:26.800 --> 01:20:31.220
[Guest 2]: So how about converting the top 10 cities of India into states?

01:20:31.220 --> 01:20:33.480
[Guest 2]: And just hear me out a little bit on this.

01:20:33.480 --> 01:20:37.840
[Guest 2]: The model that I have in mind is like a New York or a London, which have their own directly

01:20:37.840 --> 01:20:38.840
[Guest 2]: elected mayors.

01:20:38.840 --> 01:20:44.080
[Guest 2]: And the mayors are like the CEOs of the New York government and the London City Council.

01:20:44.080 --> 01:20:48.000
[Guest 2]: And they're basically responsible for running the institution, the economic development,

01:20:48.000 --> 01:20:50.000
[Guest 2]: the infrastructure, everything in the cities.

01:20:50.000 --> 01:20:55.000
[Guest 2]: What is happening in our cities is, as Shruti pointed out, is, for example, in Bombay, right?

01:20:55.000 --> 01:20:57.600
[Guest 2]: Bombay is generating a lot of tax revenue, so to speak.

01:20:57.600 --> 01:21:01.200
[Guest 2]: But how much of that is something that's really coming to the Bombay for Bombay's own development?

01:21:01.200 --> 01:21:05.000
[Guest 2]: Now, I come from Calcutta, which was once called the Paris of India, East India, no

01:21:05.000 --> 01:21:06.680
[Guest 2]: longer the case.

01:21:06.680 --> 01:21:09.800
[Guest 2]: Calcutta is held hostage by a lot of politics of the hinterland.

01:21:09.800 --> 01:21:13.400
[Guest 2]: The chief minister of Calcutta or chief minister of Bengal has to bother a lot about what's

01:21:13.400 --> 01:21:17.640
[Guest 2]: happening in the rural state, because West Bengal is essentially a rural state.

01:21:17.640 --> 01:21:20.680
[Guest 2]: What's happening in the hinterland politics of the districts and villages.

01:21:20.680 --> 01:21:23.480
[Guest 2]: And much less attention gets actually paid to what the city needs.

01:21:23.480 --> 01:21:28.400
[Guest 2]: And as a result, the city is really struggling today in terms of jobs, infrastructure, institutions,

01:21:28.400 --> 01:21:29.400
[Guest 2]: everything.

01:21:29.400 --> 01:21:33.560
[Guest 2]: So instead of that, since we have a familiar machinery of the state, why not convert the

01:21:33.560 --> 01:21:38.040
[Guest 2]: top 10 cities into states so that they get the autonomy, they get autonomy of financing,

01:21:38.040 --> 01:21:41.680
[Guest 2]: they get autonomy of economic development of those regions.

01:21:41.680 --> 01:21:45.840
[Guest 2]: But then you can have real good development pockets, instead of saying that there are

01:21:45.840 --> 01:21:48.320
[Guest 2]: only two big cities in India, which is Bombay and Delhi.

01:21:48.320 --> 01:21:50.000
[Guest 1]: So this is just a thought that came up.

01:21:50.000 --> 01:21:55.960
[Guest 1]: Yeah, I would say, you know, I mean, the conversion of the administrative structure from a city

01:21:55.960 --> 01:21:58.760
[Guest 1]: to a state or a state to a city with a mayor, that's easy enough.

01:21:58.760 --> 01:21:59.760
[Guest 2]: We have mayors already.

01:21:59.760 --> 01:22:04.080
[Guest 2]: See, mayor problem is in Indian political structure, the mayor will always be kept subservient

01:22:04.080 --> 01:22:05.080
[Guest 2]: to the chief minister.

01:22:05.080 --> 01:22:09.400
[Guest 2]: So the mayor will never be able to do things autonomously because the chief minister in

01:22:09.400 --> 01:22:11.520
[Guest 2]: the political hierarchy will be the more powerful one.

01:22:11.520 --> 01:22:12.520
[Unknown]: But I think it's not a political hierarchy.

01:22:12.520 --> 01:22:15.600
[Guest 1]: Instead, let's just convert them into states and make them each an autonomous unit.

01:22:15.600 --> 01:22:16.600
[Guest 1]: No, I disagree.

01:22:16.600 --> 01:22:20.760
[Guest 1]: I don't think the problem is because of the mayor is lower than the chief minister.

01:22:20.760 --> 01:22:23.440
[Guest 1]: I think the mayor is lower than the chief minister because he doesn't control his own

01:22:23.440 --> 01:22:24.440
[Guest 1]: budget.

01:22:24.440 --> 01:22:25.440
[Guest 2]: So my point is, why even have this?

01:22:25.440 --> 01:22:26.440
[Unknown]: He's a mayor, mayor.

01:22:26.440 --> 01:22:27.440
[Amit Varma]: He's a mayor, mayor.

01:22:27.440 --> 01:22:28.440
[Unknown]: Yeah.

01:22:28.440 --> 01:22:29.440
[Unknown]: So by the way, relatively okay joke.

01:22:29.440 --> 01:22:33.040
[Unknown]: You know, we like to compare New York and London.

01:22:33.040 --> 01:22:34.040
[Guest 2]: I'm not comparing.

01:22:34.040 --> 01:22:35.040
[Guest 2]: I'm not comparing.

01:22:35.040 --> 01:22:36.040
[Guest 2]: I'm saying that.

01:22:36.040 --> 01:22:39.560
[Guest 1]: But they're different in the sense that in New York, the mayor doesn't control his own

01:22:39.560 --> 01:22:40.560
[Guest 1]: budget.

01:22:40.560 --> 01:22:41.560
[Guest 1]: He controls his own company.

01:22:41.560 --> 01:22:42.560
[Guest 1]: Right.

01:22:42.560 --> 01:22:43.560
[Guest 1]: Right.

01:22:43.560 --> 01:22:44.560
[Unknown]: London, it is set by the council of London.

01:22:44.560 --> 01:22:48.480
[Guest 2]: So I'm saying is instead of going into the complication of mayor, why, how about dreaming

01:22:48.480 --> 01:22:53.280
[Guest 2]: that we convert the top 10 cities into states and have their own autonomous political financial

01:22:53.280 --> 01:22:54.280
[Guest 1]: unit?

01:22:54.280 --> 01:22:55.280
[Guest 1]: Yeah.

01:22:55.280 --> 01:22:56.280
[Guest 1]: I'm saying you're still beholden to the center.

01:22:56.280 --> 01:22:57.280
[Guest 1]: It's another kind of decentralization.

01:22:57.280 --> 01:23:00.280
[Amit Varma]: I think she's saying in addition to what you are saying.

