[Guest 3]: I understand that.

01:26:07.520 --> 01:26:10.000
[Guest 3]: But now I think we should also have a disclaimer.

01:26:10.000 --> 01:26:18.240
[Guest 3]: I mean, while we should dream, but dreaming with disclaimers is always a better idea.

01:26:18.240 --> 01:26:24.560
[Guest 3]: Otherwise you get into a dream sequence, you know, which is not dreaming with disclaimers.

01:26:24.560 --> 01:26:25.560
[Amit Varma]: It's very Indian thing.

01:26:25.560 --> 01:26:26.560
[Amit Varma]: So horrendous.

01:26:26.560 --> 01:26:33.480
[Guest 3]: Now it is time for your second dream reform is over, kindly give us something.

01:26:33.480 --> 01:26:39.160
[Guest 3]: So I think, you know, I mean, the second thing I want to talk about was basically tax reforms.

01:26:39.160 --> 01:26:43.120
[Guest 3]: And, you know, because we've talked about increasing the tax base.

01:26:43.120 --> 01:26:48.860
[Guest 3]: So people talk about the fact that, you know, India doesn't pay enough tax because enough

01:26:48.860 --> 01:26:51.560
[Guest 3]: Indians don't make enough money, which is true at many levels.

01:26:51.560 --> 01:26:58.480
[Guest 3]: But what is also true is that our tax filing system is so bloody complicated, that it drives

01:26:58.480 --> 01:27:00.760
[Guest 3]: away people from being honest.

01:27:00.760 --> 01:27:03.840
[Amit Varma]: What I should briefly point out at just this point is that you're talking really about

01:27:03.840 --> 01:27:08.320
[Guest 3]: income tax, because everybody basically pays income tax, and I'm talking about the goods

01:27:08.320 --> 01:27:09.320
[Guest 3]: and services tax.

01:27:09.320 --> 01:27:14.680
[Amit Varma]: Sure, but you're right that not everybody pays those, but everybody pays tax, every

01:27:14.680 --> 01:27:18.800
[Amit Varma]: Indian is a taxpayer, because anything you buy, you buy soap, you buy soap, you pay tax.

01:27:18.800 --> 01:27:19.800
[Guest 3]: Which is true.

01:27:19.800 --> 01:27:20.800
[Guest 3]: But what I'm trying to say is...

01:27:20.800 --> 01:27:23.520
[Amit Varma]: For our listeners, I wanted to clarify that you're speaking about this particular category

01:27:23.520 --> 01:27:27.080
[Guest 3]: when you said tax, lest this becomes a gotcha moment on Twitter.

01:27:27.080 --> 01:27:31.400
[Guest 3]: I mean, someone will, some smart alec will come, everybody pays tax.

01:27:31.400 --> 01:27:32.400
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, so...

01:27:32.400 --> 01:27:33.400
[Unknown]: They'll come anyway.

01:27:33.400 --> 01:27:41.000
[Guest 3]: So, what I was saying is, if you look at something as simple as our tax return forms, every year

01:27:41.000 --> 01:27:42.160
[Guest 3]: there are changes in it.

01:27:42.160 --> 01:27:43.160
[Guest 3]: Why?

01:27:43.160 --> 01:27:48.600
[Guest 3]: I mean, why can't a tax return form be a stable sort of thing, which this chartered accountant

01:27:48.600 --> 01:27:53.240
[Guest 3]: doesn't have to figure out every year, what has changed this year?

01:27:53.240 --> 01:27:59.360
[Guest 3]: Or take into account the fact that we have some six, seven, eight types of capital gains.

01:27:59.360 --> 01:28:05.280
[Guest 3]: So there is one capital gain for stocks and equity mutual funds, one for debt mutual funds,

01:28:05.280 --> 01:28:07.680
[Guest 3]: one for real estate, one for gold.

01:28:07.680 --> 01:28:08.680
[Guest 3]: Why?

01:28:08.680 --> 01:28:13.480
[Guest 3]: I mean, you know, you have to have one, you know, capital gain is capital gain, and you

01:28:13.480 --> 01:28:14.480
[Guest 3]: tax it like that.

01:28:14.480 --> 01:28:18.920
[Guest 3]: I mean, in some cases you have indexation, in some cases you have no indexation.

01:28:18.920 --> 01:28:23.560
[Guest 3]: So the point is that you have to have a stable tax system.

01:28:23.560 --> 01:28:29.360
[Guest 3]: Now, look at something like GST, you know, every time the GST council meets, there is

01:28:29.360 --> 01:28:30.360
[Guest 3]: some change.

01:28:30.360 --> 01:28:33.280
[Guest 3]: So there are changes which are happening at the central level, there are changes which

01:28:33.280 --> 01:28:38.080
[Guest 3]: are happening at the state level, which is why, you know, if you look at the annual return

01:28:38.080 --> 01:28:44.920
[Guest 3]: for 2017-18 of GST, only 20% of people have filed it till date.

01:28:44.920 --> 01:28:49.080
[Guest 3]: So I think you need to have a stable tax system.

01:28:49.080 --> 01:28:53.120
[Guest 3]: And in case of GST, what has happened is, they've obviously launched it without thinking

01:28:53.120 --> 01:28:54.120
[Guest 3]: it through.

01:28:54.120 --> 01:28:56.200
[Guest 3]: So they have to keep changing it.

01:28:56.200 --> 01:28:59.960
[Guest 3]: Now, you know, you can't keep changing it every week or every, you know, every time

01:28:59.960 --> 01:29:01.480
[Guest 3]: the GST council meets.

01:29:01.480 --> 01:29:06.920
[Guest 3]: So better thing to do right now would be to sit down and figure out what is wrong, and

01:29:06.920 --> 01:29:13.200
[Guest 3]: then make major changes at a single go, instead of meeting every time and tweaking this and

01:29:13.200 --> 01:29:16.860
[Guest 3]: tweaking that and making, you know, things difficult for everyone.

01:29:16.860 --> 01:29:23.200
[Guest 3]: So like, if you if you sort of, you know, pick up the what is called as the HSN book,

01:29:23.200 --> 01:29:28.920
[Guest 3]: which is, you know, the codes for the economic activity you carry out, if you are in the

01:29:28.920 --> 01:29:33.240
[Guest 3]: goods part, and then there is something for the services part as well.

01:29:33.240 --> 01:29:35.880
[Guest 3]: Now, it's a huge thick thing.

01:29:35.880 --> 01:29:36.880
[Guest 3]: I mean, why?

01:29:36.880 --> 01:29:37.880
[Guest 1]: It's about 16,000 entries.

01:29:37.880 --> 01:29:41.560
[Guest 3]: Why are you why are you complicating these things?

01:29:41.560 --> 01:29:47.160
[Guest 3]: I mean, you know, you can have, let's say two rates and just, you know, 12% for goods

01:29:47.160 --> 01:29:51.920
[Guest 3]: and 15% for services and get done, get along, you know, get on with it.

01:29:51.920 --> 01:29:57.040
[Guest 3]: But then, you know, you'll have the argument on the fact that how can, you know, something

01:29:57.040 --> 01:30:00.520
[Guest 3]: that everyone is using and Mercedes be taxed at the same rate.

01:30:00.520 --> 01:30:06.000
[Guest 3]: But boss, Mercedes, if it comes to 1 crore, then 15% tax will come to 15 lakhs.

01:30:06.000 --> 01:30:09.560
[Guest 3]: This is something that, you know, people don't get, but then they don't want, they're not

01:30:09.560 --> 01:30:16.000
[Guest 3]: happy with 15 lakhs, they want 43 lakhs, because they want to tax it at 42% or 43% or whatever.

01:30:16.000 --> 01:30:21.280
[Guest 3]: So as long so, you know, this is something that will sort of also help, I mean, along

01:30:21.280 --> 01:30:29.500
[Guest 3]: with being a structural reform, it will also have an immediate impact on economic activity.

01:30:29.500 --> 01:30:34.240
[Guest 2]: So I want to add to what Vivek said that I completely agree that simplifying tax administration

01:30:34.240 --> 01:30:36.720
[Guest 2]: is something that we have been discussing for a very long time.

01:30:36.720 --> 01:30:40.780
[Guest 2]: And it's one of those things that we all know needs to be done, but never really gets done.

01:30:40.780 --> 01:30:44.880
[Guest 2]: And we actually end up complicating more and more with this new GST fiasco.

01:30:44.880 --> 01:30:48.640
[Guest 2]: The other thing that I think is also very important to understand is if you want to

01:30:48.640 --> 01:30:53.360
[Guest 2]: avoid tax evasion, and if you want to expand the tax base, it's very important to keep

01:30:53.360 --> 01:30:55.080
[Guest 2]: the tax rates low.

01:30:55.080 --> 01:31:00.440
[Guest 2]: I think we just don't get that math at all, because our tax revenue is the multiplied

01:31:00.440 --> 01:31:03.160
[Guest 2]: product of tax base and tax rate.

01:31:03.160 --> 01:31:07.200
[Guest 2]: Now, if you want to increase the base, you have to lower the rate, otherwise, if you

01:31:07.200 --> 01:31:12.680
[Guest 2]: keep the tax system at a very high rate, the probability of tax evasion goes up that much

01:31:12.680 --> 01:31:13.680
[Guest 2]: more.

01:31:13.680 --> 01:31:17.840
[Guest 2]: And then in order to justify the high rate, you also give a lot of exemptions.

01:31:17.840 --> 01:31:21.480
[Guest 2]: And then the exemptions increase the leakages from the system even more.

01:31:21.480 --> 01:31:24.680
[Guest 2]: And then in the end, you're sitting with a really complicated system that you cannot

01:31:24.680 --> 01:31:28.200
[Guest 2]: monitor because you don't have enough employees in your tax administration.

01:31:28.200 --> 01:31:30.360
[Guest 2]: So it's a total mess at the end of the day.

01:31:30.360 --> 01:31:36.480
[Guest 2]: So two easy and finite things to do is one is ease tax administration by doing the logistical

01:31:36.480 --> 01:31:42.400
[Guest 2]: reforms of filing ease and all of that, and lower the taxes, be direct tax, indirect tax.

01:31:42.400 --> 01:31:45.080
[Guest 2]: Our corporate income tax is one of the highest in the world.

01:31:45.080 --> 01:31:49.720
[Guest 2]: It doesn't have to be so in a country when we want to encourage investment and make in

01:31:49.720 --> 01:31:51.040
[Guest 2]: India and all of that.

01:31:51.040 --> 01:31:54.840
[Guest 2]: So lower the tax rate and make the tax administration easy.

01:31:54.840 --> 01:31:56.800
[Guest 2]: You will expand the tax base.

01:31:56.800 --> 01:32:01.680
[Guest 2]: And with that expanded tax base, again, coming back to the point of anti-fiscal discipline,

01:32:01.680 --> 01:32:05.720
[Guest 2]: if you then have a tax base, which is expanded, then you remain within the means of the tax

01:32:05.720 --> 01:32:07.120
[Guest 2]: revenue and you spend.

01:32:07.120 --> 01:32:11.800
[Guest 2]: But all of these things are stuff that again, we have talked about, but for whatever reason

01:32:11.800 --> 01:32:14.520
[Guest 2]: and political economy, etc, there is a lot of inertia to do this.

01:32:14.520 --> 01:32:21.520
[Guest 3]: I mean, look at what Nirmala Sitharaman did in her first budget, introduced, basically

01:32:21.520 --> 01:32:27.080
[Guest 3]: increased the surcharges and now there are tax slabs at 39 percent and 42.74 percent.

01:32:27.080 --> 01:32:32.480
[Guest 3]: Now, the point is, OK, you know, you're looking at, you know, increasing the tax revenue and

01:32:32.480 --> 01:32:33.480
[Guest 3]: so on.

01:32:33.480 --> 01:32:37.400
[Guest 3]: But for these people at these levels, so people who earn two to five crore or five crore or

01:32:37.400 --> 01:32:42.760
[Guest 3]: more, and it's very easy to leave the country and go live somewhere else.

01:32:42.760 --> 01:32:46.560
[Guest 3]: I mean, they go to you can easily go to Dubai properties as expensive as it is in Mumbai.

01:32:46.560 --> 01:32:50.840
[Guest 2]: And for businesses to basically invest elsewhere, a foreign direct investment outside of India

01:32:50.840 --> 01:32:52.280
[Guest 2]: is actually increasing every year.

01:32:52.280 --> 01:32:55.640
[Amit Varma]: In fact, this is a point Vivek, you made in our budget episode, which earned you the nickname

01:32:55.640 --> 01:32:57.800
[Guest 3]: the Shah Rukh Khan of economics.

01:32:57.800 --> 01:33:00.600
[Guest 1]: You were the Govinda of podcasting.

01:33:00.600 --> 01:33:01.600
[Guest 1]: One more thing.

01:33:01.600 --> 01:33:03.480
[Guest 1]: I think none of this is a surprise.

01:33:03.480 --> 01:33:07.120
[Guest 1]: So a couple of things on this GST classification problem.

01:33:07.120 --> 01:33:11.400
[Guest 1]: First up, I do want to point out, it's extremely regressive and anti poor.

01:33:11.400 --> 01:33:15.720
[Guest 1]: You know, I mean, Palaji has been in the news because they've just laid off 10,000 employees

01:33:15.720 --> 01:33:17.160
[Guest 1]: and biscuit sales are down.

01:33:17.160 --> 01:33:21.400
[Guest 1]: Palaji's GST rate, I believe is 18% on biscuits, is that accurate?

01:33:21.400 --> 01:33:26.400
[Guest 1]: I mean, if Vivek doesn't know, but it's high, it's double digits and it's high.

01:33:26.400 --> 01:33:29.440
[Guest 1]: The GST on gold is 3%.

01:33:29.440 --> 01:33:34.040
[Guest 1]: And right and the GST on diamonds is 0.25.

01:33:34.040 --> 01:33:38.440
[Guest 1]: And if you go back and check the timing of reducing the GST on gold and diamond, it was

01:33:38.440 --> 01:33:42.160
[Guest 1]: done for some handicrafts, cottage industry reason.

01:33:42.160 --> 01:33:46.360
[Guest 1]: But it was just after demonetization and just before the Gujarat election, or just around

01:33:46.360 --> 01:33:47.360
[Guest 3]: that time.

01:33:47.360 --> 01:33:48.360
[Guest 3]: I'll interrupt you.

01:33:48.360 --> 01:33:49.360
[Guest 3]: GST on biscuits is 18%.

01:33:49.360 --> 01:33:50.360
[Guest 1]: 18%.

01:33:50.360 --> 01:33:51.360
[Guest 1]: Right.

01:33:51.360 --> 01:33:54.760
[Guest 1]: So Palaji, which is the poor man's food, they have a five rupee biscuit packet, they have

01:33:54.760 --> 01:33:59.560
[Guest 1]: a 12 rupee biscuit packet that is taxed at 18% GST.

01:33:59.560 --> 01:34:05.280
[Guest 1]: So this whole bullshit about, oh, the Mercedes guy, you know, is going to only end up paying

01:34:05.280 --> 01:34:07.800
[Guest 1]: 6% or 8%.

01:34:07.800 --> 01:34:13.280
[Guest 1]: The guy who's homeless, you know, begging outside a temple is paying 18% GST on Palaji.

01:34:13.280 --> 01:34:15.520
[Guest 3]: No, but there is a logic to it.

01:34:15.520 --> 01:34:17.840
[Guest 3]: So we don't want people to have maida and sugar.

01:34:17.840 --> 01:34:20.720
[Guest 3]: Maida is slow poison, sugar is poison.

01:34:20.720 --> 01:34:27.400
[Guest 2]: As I think, I mean, I know, but we want people to have a lot of gold.

01:34:27.400 --> 01:34:29.280
[Guest 3]: We want people to have the freedom to have poison.

01:34:29.280 --> 01:34:34.960
[Guest 3]: We should have bhoonja chana, which is, yeah, savings to buy gold.

01:34:34.960 --> 01:34:40.360
[Guest 1]: I know, I'm not so much of an economics nerd that I don't get the joke.

01:34:40.360 --> 01:34:45.280
[Guest 1]: But just as a side note, this kind of paternalism nudging people to better food choices through

01:34:45.280 --> 01:34:47.320
[Guest 3]: taxation is a really bad idea.

01:34:47.320 --> 01:34:48.320
[Guest 3]: They wouldn't do it.

01:34:48.320 --> 01:34:49.320
[Guest 2]: I mean, they're not doing that.

01:34:49.320 --> 01:34:50.320
[Guest 1]: I know.

01:34:50.320 --> 01:34:54.320
[Guest 2]: The whole idea of a good GST was to have a single rate for all goods and services.

01:34:54.320 --> 01:34:55.320
[Unknown]: No, no, I understand.

01:34:55.320 --> 01:34:56.760
[Guest 1]: But I'm saying we have gone so far away.

01:34:56.760 --> 01:34:57.760
[Guest 1]: I understand.

01:34:57.760 --> 01:34:58.760
[Guest 1]: But I'm not.

01:34:58.760 --> 01:34:59.760
[Guest 1]: I think this is not a knowledge problem.

01:34:59.760 --> 01:35:01.080
[Guest 1]: I think it's an incentive problem.

01:35:01.080 --> 01:35:02.080
[Guest 1]: Of course.

01:35:02.080 --> 01:35:05.840
[Guest 1]: If you have a proliferation of rates, you can control special interests.

01:35:05.840 --> 01:35:06.840
[Unknown]: Yeah.

01:35:06.840 --> 01:35:07.840
[Guest 2]: I mean, of course.

01:35:07.840 --> 01:35:11.520
[Guest 3]: Again, the political economy, the difference between what economists suggest and what politicians

01:35:11.520 --> 01:35:12.520
[Guest 3]: suggest.

01:35:12.520 --> 01:35:15.600
[Guest 3]: I'll give you an example here.

01:35:15.600 --> 01:35:21.560
[Guest 3]: In 2009, I think P. Chidambaram was the finance minister back then, we came up with the Direct

01:35:21.560 --> 01:35:22.560
[Guest 3]: Taxes Code.

01:35:22.560 --> 01:35:23.560
[Guest 3]: Okay.

01:35:23.560 --> 01:35:28.440
[Guest 3]: Now, it was a very small code, which sort of was supposed to replace the Income Tax

01:35:28.440 --> 01:35:29.760
[Guest 3]: Act.

01:35:29.760 --> 01:35:32.760
[Guest 3]: And along with the code, they had an 80-page explainer.

01:35:32.760 --> 01:35:33.760
[Guest 3]: Okay.

01:35:33.760 --> 01:35:37.080
[Guest 3]: Imagine the Income Tax Act of India being explained in just 80 pages.

01:35:37.080 --> 01:35:40.840
[Guest 3]: And I remember reading it over two to three hours and then writing a piece around it.

01:35:40.840 --> 01:35:45.800
[Guest 3]: So I read it in three hours also, obviously, it was scuttled, because if that had come

01:35:45.800 --> 01:35:52.440
[Guest 3]: through, you know, all the CAs would have gone out of job, and the IRS people would

01:35:52.440 --> 01:35:57.080
[Guest 3]: have gone out of job, I mean, they wouldn't have gone out of job, but then the rent seeking

01:35:57.080 --> 01:35:58.720
[Guest 3]: would have stopped.

01:35:58.720 --> 01:36:06.640
[Guest 3]: And so the moment, you know, P. Chidambaram was moved to Home Ministry, and our man, Pranab

01:36:06.640 --> 01:36:09.440
[Guest 3]: Mukherjee took over, I mean, it just got...

01:36:09.440 --> 01:36:15.160
[Guest 3]: Now we have a new Direct Taxes Code, which I mean, the news about it came up, which Vivek

01:36:15.160 --> 01:36:16.160
[Guest 1]: cannot read in three hours.

01:36:16.160 --> 01:36:17.160
[Amit Varma]: No, I haven't.

01:36:17.160 --> 01:36:22.400
[Amit Varma]: I had an episode with Pooja Mehra on what the Chidambaram to Pranab Mukherjee shift

01:36:22.400 --> 01:36:23.400
[Unknown]: did.

01:36:23.400 --> 01:36:25.160
[Amit Varma]: And that was a great episode.

01:36:25.160 --> 01:36:28.440
[Amit Varma]: And Pooja, unfortunately, is in Delhi, otherwise, we would have invited her to the studio for

01:36:28.440 --> 01:36:29.440
[Guest 1]: this.

01:36:29.440 --> 01:36:30.440
[Guest 1]: And it's a lovely book.

01:36:30.440 --> 01:36:31.440
[Guest 1]: Please read Pooja Mehra's book.

01:36:31.440 --> 01:36:32.760
[Amit Varma]: Please read Pooja Mehra's Lost Decade.

01:36:32.760 --> 01:36:37.600
[Amit Varma]: And I should also point out that both Vivek and Shruti have done episodes with me on

01:36:37.600 --> 01:36:38.600
[Guest 1]: GST.

01:36:38.600 --> 01:36:39.600
[Guest 1]: Very fine episodes.

01:36:39.600 --> 01:36:40.600
[Amit Varma]: Very fine episodes.

01:36:40.600 --> 01:36:41.600
[Amit Varma]: Magnificent.

01:36:41.600 --> 01:36:42.600
[Amit Varma]: And the last one of them was with Shruti.

01:36:42.600 --> 01:36:47.760
[Amit Varma]: And if I remember correctly, it was called the Bad and Complex Tax, which sums it up

01:36:47.760 --> 01:36:50.480
[Guest 3]: and kind of sums up what you're saying about your...

01:36:50.480 --> 01:36:51.480
[Guest 3]: Simplify it.

01:36:51.480 --> 01:36:52.480
[Guest 3]: That's your reading.

01:36:52.480 --> 01:36:53.480
[Guest 3]: PCT.

01:36:53.480 --> 01:36:54.480
[Guest 3]: I mean, I pay GST every month.

01:36:54.480 --> 01:36:55.480
[Amit Varma]: I'm in a bad state.

01:36:55.480 --> 01:36:56.480
[Amit Varma]: I'm in a bad state too.

01:36:56.480 --> 01:36:57.480
[Amit Varma]: I'm just keeping track of...

01:36:57.480 --> 01:36:58.480
[Amit Varma]: Dude, I give invoices, pay GST, but I don't get the money.

01:36:58.480 --> 01:36:59.480
[Amit Varma]: GST is coming out of my pocket.

01:36:59.480 --> 01:37:00.480
[Amit Varma]: So we are basically financing the government, right?

01:37:00.480 --> 01:37:12.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, because there is a... it's bad working capital management at the moment.

01:37:12.000 --> 01:37:16.240
[Amit Varma]: It's like the great Sharad Joshi ji said, negative subsidy.

01:37:16.240 --> 01:37:17.240
[Unknown]: And how many times...

01:37:17.240 --> 01:37:19.080
[Guest 1]: There's a great Sharad Joshi biography that has come out, I believe.

01:37:19.080 --> 01:37:20.080
[Guest 2]: I'm going to go look for it.

01:37:20.080 --> 01:37:24.120
[Guest 2]: How many times have you faced situations where the guy says that, madam, if you pay in cash,

01:37:24.120 --> 01:37:26.120
[Guest 2]: then there won't be any GST.

01:37:26.120 --> 01:37:27.560
[Unknown]: Oh, by the way, this is not just...

01:37:27.560 --> 01:37:30.920
[Guest 2]: Nobody is even caring about doing the billing and the receipts and everything.

01:37:30.920 --> 01:37:31.920
[Guest 3]: It's like it's easier for them.

01:37:31.920 --> 01:37:32.920
[Unknown]: No, no, no.

01:37:32.920 --> 01:37:37.160
[Unknown]: I have discovered entire supply chains that are working in cash.

01:37:37.160 --> 01:37:40.800
[Guest 1]: So my tailor in Delhi, you can do everything by the book.

01:37:40.800 --> 01:37:44.800
[Guest 1]: But you know, GST has that whole supply chain backward linkage issue, right?

01:37:44.800 --> 01:37:49.040
[Guest 1]: So she has a set of books for GST clients.

01:37:49.040 --> 01:37:51.280
[Guest 3]: She has a set of books for non-GST clients.

01:37:51.280 --> 01:37:52.280
[Guest 3]: This is a very old thing.

01:37:52.280 --> 01:37:53.280
[Guest 3]: It has always been in India.

01:37:53.280 --> 01:37:54.280
[Unknown]: You know, corporates have...

01:37:54.280 --> 01:37:56.600
[Guest 3]: I mean, forget your tailor.

01:37:56.600 --> 01:37:59.800
[Guest 2]: Corporates have always had books for income taxwala and their own book.

01:37:59.800 --> 01:38:03.200
[Guest 2]: So there is a reason why post-demonetization, cash utilization has come back to exactly

01:38:03.200 --> 01:38:04.200
[Unknown]: the free levels.

01:38:04.200 --> 01:38:05.200
[Unknown]: Absolutely.

01:38:05.200 --> 01:38:06.200
[Guest 2]: Because nobody cares about these things anymore.

01:38:06.200 --> 01:38:08.200
[Unknown]: Because you've figured out ways to do jugaar again.

01:38:08.200 --> 01:38:10.560
[Guest 1]: No, but it tells you something when my tailor is doing it.

01:38:10.560 --> 01:38:11.560
[Guest 1]: It doesn't...

01:38:11.560 --> 01:38:15.400
[Guest 1]: I mean, I'm not surprised that the corporates are sophisticated enough, but the GST is such

01:38:15.400 --> 01:38:16.400
[Guest 1]: a huge burden.

01:38:16.400 --> 01:38:17.400
[Guest 1]: Of course.

01:38:17.400 --> 01:38:18.800
[Unknown]: She's hurting them more.

01:38:18.800 --> 01:38:22.800
[Guest 1]: She's running a tailor shop no larger than this room in her own home.

01:38:22.800 --> 01:38:25.800
[Guest 3]: You still have tailors in India?

01:38:25.800 --> 01:38:29.480
[Amit Varma]: Yaar, tu matlab bahut hi elite ka elite hai.

01:38:29.480 --> 01:38:33.760
[Amit Varma]: Just now you will realize, Shruti, when we were discussing GST rates, he did not know

01:38:33.760 --> 01:38:39.160
[Amit Varma]: GST rate for biscuit, but he knew GST rate for diamond and gold.

01:38:39.160 --> 01:38:41.800
[Guest 3]: Vivek Kaur, you have been exposed.

01:38:41.800 --> 01:38:44.000
[Guest 3]: Yeah, you're supposed to know.

01:38:44.000 --> 01:38:46.560
[Guest 3]: But I knew the GST rate for Mercedes also.

01:38:46.560 --> 01:38:47.560
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

01:38:47.560 --> 01:38:49.720
[Amit Varma]: Diamond gold pe kyu rukh rahe ho yaar?

01:38:49.720 --> 01:38:51.120
[Amit Varma]: Uske upar jao toda.

01:38:51.120 --> 01:38:53.440
[Guest 3]: It depends on how many diamonds you buy.

01:38:53.440 --> 01:38:54.440
[Guest 3]: I don't believe.

01:38:54.440 --> 01:38:57.320
[Guest 1]: Podcasters and journalists ki shaan hi alag hai.

01:38:57.320 --> 01:38:58.320
[Amit Varma]: Shaan hi alag hai.

01:38:58.320 --> 01:39:00.320
[Amit Varma]: Let's abhi agle reform pe move karte hain.

01:39:00.320 --> 01:39:01.880
[Guest 2]: Rajeshwari ji ka turn hai.

01:39:01.880 --> 01:39:04.760
[Amit Varma]: Rajeshwari ji, bachayiye humein is banter se.

01:39:04.760 --> 01:39:09.760
[Guest 2]: I'm not even going to attempt to break into Hindi because then I'll be truly exposed.

01:39:09.760 --> 01:39:14.000
[Guest 2]: So the next reform that I'm going to talk about is going to take us quite far away from

01:39:14.000 --> 01:39:17.280
[Guest 2]: fiscal worries, etc.

01:39:17.280 --> 01:39:19.160
[Guest 2]: It's actually about immigration.

01:39:19.160 --> 01:39:27.600
[Guest 2]: And it's something that I'm very closely and very sincerely believe in, which is, so there's

01:39:27.600 --> 01:39:32.960
[Guest 2]: a very fantastic book that has come out recently by Tony Joseph called Early Indians.

01:39:32.960 --> 01:39:34.640
[Amit Varma]: I had an episode with him as well.

01:39:34.640 --> 01:39:35.640
[Guest 2]: Fantastic.

01:39:35.640 --> 01:39:37.560
[Guest 2]: I have not heard that and I will definitely.

01:39:37.560 --> 01:39:44.640
[Guest 2]: So it's a compelling read where Tony Joseph uses recent pathbreaking DNA research to essentially

01:39:44.640 --> 01:39:51.320
[Guest 2]: trace the history of Indians and essentially the truth that comes out of the book to summarize

01:39:51.320 --> 01:39:56.080
[Guest 2]: in a sentence is who we are and where we have come from.

01:39:56.080 --> 01:40:02.000
[Guest 2]: And the truth is that we are all immigrants and we have all come from somewhere else.

01:40:02.000 --> 01:40:06.120
[Guest 2]: And of course, he talks about the waves of migration, so on and so forth.

01:40:06.120 --> 01:40:10.760
[Guest 2]: So now, the reason I started with that is basically to say that there is nothing called

01:40:10.760 --> 01:40:11.760
[Guest 2]: a pure Indian.

01:40:11.760 --> 01:40:13.720
[Guest 2]: There's nothing called an indigenous Indian, right?

01:40:13.720 --> 01:40:16.280
[Guest 2]: We are all from somewhere else.

01:40:16.280 --> 01:40:21.840
[Guest 2]: And in that spirit and in a world where there is so much of intolerance now and border closing

01:40:21.840 --> 01:40:28.720
[Guest 2]: obsessions and whatnot, I think that we should we should be a country again in the dream

01:40:28.720 --> 01:40:35.400
[Guest 2]: world where we open up our gates and borders and doors, whatever you have, to whoever wants

01:40:35.400 --> 01:40:37.120
[Guest 2]: to come and live in India.

01:40:37.120 --> 01:40:41.480
[Guest 2]: Now, if that doesn't agree with your moral fiber, for whatever reason, then the next

01:40:41.480 --> 01:40:45.440
[Guest 2]: layer I would say is open up the borders to those who are desperate and helpless, which

01:40:45.440 --> 01:40:47.360
[Guest 2]: would be the refugees.

01:40:47.360 --> 01:40:51.000
[Guest 2]: If that too doesn't agree with the moral fiber, for again, whatever reason, the third layer

01:40:51.000 --> 01:40:57.720
[Guest 2]: that I would settle down in my dream world is open up your gates to those who are skilled.

01:40:57.720 --> 01:41:03.080
[Guest 2]: For example, whoever has an undergraduate degree from a decent university in the world,

01:41:03.080 --> 01:41:06.960
[Guest 2]: give them immediately a work visa and let them work in India and after 10 years, naturalize

01:41:06.960 --> 01:41:11.640
[Guest 2]: them and give them Indian citizenship or encourage students from all over the world to come and

01:41:11.640 --> 01:41:13.720
[Guest 2]: study in Indian colleges and universities.

01:41:13.720 --> 01:41:17.840
[Guest 2]: And don't stop at giving them a college degree, offer them jobs, offer them citizenship.

01:41:17.840 --> 01:41:22.480
[Guest 2]: I think India should aspire to be a country where people want the Indian citizenship.

01:41:22.480 --> 01:41:25.800
[Guest 2]: And that should be the level that we should dream about instead of saying that we are

01:41:25.800 --> 01:41:29.880
[Guest 2]: going to be this very insular country where we care about indigenous Indians.

01:41:29.880 --> 01:41:34.760
[Guest 2]: And I think we are going exactly the regressive way because immigrants are great because immigrants,

01:41:34.760 --> 01:41:38.760
[Guest 2]: they bring knowledge, they bring capabilities, they integrate us with their countries.

01:41:38.760 --> 01:41:40.640
[Guest 2]: They help knowledge sharing.

01:41:40.640 --> 01:41:45.120
[Guest 2]: They are, research shows, they're low on crime because they are scared of getting deported.

01:41:45.120 --> 01:41:48.240
[Guest 2]: So they basically work hard to stand on their own feet.

01:41:48.240 --> 01:41:52.320
[Guest 2]: They don't have a political clout, so they don't ask for your welfare benefits.

01:41:52.320 --> 01:41:56.240
[Guest 2]: And there are countries which have been built by immigrants, as we all know.

01:41:56.240 --> 01:42:02.640
[Guest 2]: I mean, my favorite example is Steve Jobs, who was the child, illegitimate child of a

01:42:02.640 --> 01:42:08.640
[Guest 2]: Syrian father who was a refugee, so to speak, in the U.S. and a Catholic mother of Swiss

01:42:08.640 --> 01:42:10.160
[Guest 2]: German descent.

01:42:10.160 --> 01:42:13.720
[Guest 2]: And that would be impossible today because Syrian refugee would obviously be turned away.

01:42:13.720 --> 01:42:18.880
[Guest 2]: The other example, of course, is Barack Obama, who is the child of a Kenyan father and a

01:42:18.880 --> 01:42:24.960
[Guest 2]: mother of, and let me remember this correctly, English, Swiss, German, Scottish, Irish and

01:42:24.960 --> 01:42:27.120
[Guest 2]: Welsh ancestry.

01:42:27.120 --> 01:42:32.680
[Guest 2]: And they got married at a time when Barack Obama's father was a student in Hawaii on

01:42:32.680 --> 01:42:35.240
[Guest 2]: scholarship, a foreign student on scholarship.

01:42:35.240 --> 01:42:37.440
[Guest 2]: So and there are, of course, many, many such examples, right?

01:42:37.440 --> 01:42:42.680
[Guest 2]: So I think India, in my dream world, we should aspire to be that country where we are open

01:42:42.680 --> 01:42:46.360
[Guest 2]: to immigrants and we are naturalizing them into citizenship.

01:42:46.360 --> 01:42:50.040
[Guest 2]: We will not get the good brains of U.S. and Europe, perhaps, but we will get the good

01:42:50.040 --> 01:42:53.600
[Guest 2]: brains of South Asian countries, of Middle Eastern countries, of African countries.

01:42:53.600 --> 01:42:57.800
[Guest 2]: And I think that is great, and that's what we should dream about.

01:42:57.800 --> 01:43:06.000
[Guest 3]: This reminds me of a Javed Akhtar song, Panchi Nadiya, Pawan Ke Jhoke, Koi Sarad Naon Hai

01:43:06.000 --> 01:43:07.000
[Unknown]: Hoke.

01:43:07.000 --> 01:43:08.000
[Amit Varma]: Refugee songs.

01:43:08.000 --> 01:43:10.880
[Amit Varma]: This is very, this is not pre-planned at all.

01:43:10.880 --> 01:43:11.880
[Unknown]: We did not know each other.

01:43:11.880 --> 01:43:16.720
[Amit Varma]: Sing, Vivek is just this encyclopediac brain on this.

01:43:16.720 --> 01:43:17.720
[Guest 1]: It's a lovely song.

01:43:17.720 --> 01:43:18.720
[Guest 1]: The movie is terrible.

01:43:18.720 --> 01:43:19.720
[Amit Varma]: I have to say this is a great reform.

01:43:19.720 --> 01:43:20.720
[Amit Varma]: I agree with you entirely.

01:43:20.720 --> 01:43:22.480
[Amit Varma]: I had an episode on immigration also.

01:43:22.480 --> 01:43:23.640
[Guest 3]: I've had so many episodes.

01:43:23.640 --> 01:43:27.040
[Guest 3]: But how do you explain then what will happen to India's demographic dividend?

01:43:27.040 --> 01:43:29.760
[Guest 3]: Our people are not getting jobs and foreigners are not getting jobs.

01:43:29.760 --> 01:43:33.240
[Guest 2]: That's obviously not the kind of thinking that I would subscribe to when I'm dreaming

01:43:33.240 --> 01:43:36.600
[Guest 2]: of immigration because that's why I had three layers, right?

01:43:36.600 --> 01:43:40.400
[Guest 2]: I said, okay, once you open up the gates to everybody, doesn't agree with the moral fiber,

01:43:40.400 --> 01:43:42.940
[Guest 2]: open up gates to refugees, doesn't agree to moral fiber.

01:43:42.940 --> 01:43:46.480
[Guest 2]: If you're only allowing skilled people, I think the numbers will be too minuscule to

01:43:46.480 --> 01:43:49.600
[Guest 2]: make a difference to a large demographic dividend, if anything.

01:43:49.600 --> 01:43:52.960
[Guest 2]: And if you're really worried about it, then the Indian state should think about or the

01:43:52.960 --> 01:43:57.720
[Guest 2]: private sector, the markets that you are not going to worsen the demographic dividend problem

01:43:57.720 --> 01:44:00.320
[Guest 2]: by letting people coming in who are probably more skilled.

01:44:00.320 --> 01:44:03.480
[Guest 2]: The whole idea is why should we be restricted to our local skill pool?

01:44:03.480 --> 01:44:06.480
[Guest 2]: We should be able to access the skill pool everywhere in the world.

01:44:06.480 --> 01:44:10.800
[Guest 2]: And starting with my initial premise, there is nothing called Indians to begin with.

01:44:10.800 --> 01:44:16.160
[Guest 2]: We should first have a change of mindset instead of having that kind of an insular mentality.

01:44:16.160 --> 01:44:20.840
[Guest 1]: I would add to what you're saying, not just for the immigration purposes, but also add

01:44:20.840 --> 01:44:24.160
[Guest 1]: tourism to it, because I think it's pertinent, right?

01:44:24.160 --> 01:44:27.640
[Guest 1]: I mean, there is a certain kind of immigration, which just goes to another country and just

01:44:27.640 --> 01:44:28.720
[Guest 1]: moves there.

01:44:28.720 --> 01:44:33.560
[Guest 1]: But I think people are more likely to mingle and, you know, think about living in another

01:44:33.560 --> 01:44:37.120
[Guest 1]: place or working in another place or sharing their skills.

01:44:37.120 --> 01:44:41.960
[Guest 1]: And you know, sort of this kind of cultural exchange, intellectual exchange, if they can

01:44:41.960 --> 01:44:45.920
[Guest 1]: visit more easily, they've simplified the process of getting an Indian visa.

01:44:45.920 --> 01:44:47.880
[Guest 1]: But it's still a hassle, right?

01:44:47.880 --> 01:44:54.560
[Guest 1]: I mean, we can just do, you know, unilateral, no visa required to come to India.

01:44:54.560 --> 01:44:55.560
[Guest 2]: Absolutely.

01:44:55.560 --> 01:45:00.280
[Guest 2]: I mean, the tourist visa, but in the work visa, I was just reading up some of the rules.

01:45:00.280 --> 01:45:04.580
[Guest 2]: I mean, the stipulation of the work visa is that the person applying for a visa needs

01:45:04.580 --> 01:45:08.400
[Guest 2]: to have an income of 25,000 US dollars a year.

01:45:08.400 --> 01:45:10.240
[Guest 2]: And only then can you be given a work visa.

01:45:10.240 --> 01:45:12.160
[Guest 2]: That's almost about 20 lakhs a year.

01:45:12.160 --> 01:45:14.280
[Guest 2]: Why do you have to have these stipulations to give a job?

01:45:14.280 --> 01:45:16.960
[Guest 2]: If somebody wants to be a secretary or whatever it is, right?

01:45:16.960 --> 01:45:19.480
[Guest 2]: Any job that the person wants, give him or her that job.

01:45:19.480 --> 01:45:21.480
[Guest 2]: Why do you have this weird kind of a restriction?

01:45:21.480 --> 01:45:23.040
[Guest 3]: And that too for five years, by the way.

01:45:23.040 --> 01:45:31.680
[Guest 3]: So talking about tourism, a couple of years back, I went to Bali with my immediate family.

01:45:31.680 --> 01:45:34.400
[Guest 3]: And so I remember this.

01:45:34.400 --> 01:45:40.200
[Guest 3]: So when we were leaving Bombay, I sort of gave my passport to the Bureau of Immigration

01:45:40.200 --> 01:45:42.720
[Guest 3]: and the guy said, where is the visa?

01:45:42.720 --> 01:45:45.640
[Guest 3]: So I had to tell him that visa doesn't apply in Bali.

01:45:45.640 --> 01:45:47.640
[Guest 3]: So then he said, no, but Veera, is visa on arrival?

01:45:47.640 --> 01:45:48.640
[Guest 3]: I said, no, visa doesn't apply.

01:45:48.640 --> 01:45:53.120
[Guest 3]: So he was very surprised that there is this place in Doha, you know, very close to where

01:45:53.120 --> 01:45:55.720
[Guest 3]: we are, which doesn't require a visa.

01:45:55.720 --> 01:46:02.160
[Guest 3]: And the best part is you land, you know, in Bali and you just walk out, I mean, they take

01:46:02.160 --> 01:46:04.920
[Guest 3]: a picture and you walk out of the airport.

01:46:04.920 --> 01:46:09.680
[Guest 3]: And there are more requirements, I mean, there were more requirements for me to fill up when

01:46:09.680 --> 01:46:11.600
[Guest 3]: I came back to India.

01:46:11.600 --> 01:46:15.920
[Guest 3]: And the other thing I really can't understand is that, you know, when someone is leaving

01:46:15.920 --> 01:46:21.280
[Guest 3]: the country, you don't have to have a Bureau of Immigration there and, you know, create

01:46:21.280 --> 01:46:22.280
[Guest 3]: a...

01:46:22.280 --> 01:46:27.120
[Guest 3]: I can understand that, you know, when someone's coming back, when someone's coming into the

01:46:27.120 --> 01:46:30.200
[Guest 3]: country, there has to be, you know, I mean, a check.

01:46:30.200 --> 01:46:33.800
[Guest 3]: But when you're leaving the country, I mean, not my headache, right?

01:46:33.800 --> 01:46:35.800
[Guest 1]: You know, my problem is not that they check it.

01:46:35.800 --> 01:46:36.800
[Guest 1]: It's okay.

01:46:36.800 --> 01:46:37.800
[Guest 1]: I mean, the stamp takes a minute.

01:46:37.800 --> 01:46:41.880
[Guest 2]: The question is how cumbersome the process is and what is the reason for doing it?

01:46:41.880 --> 01:46:46.640
[Guest 2]: And exactly the same for having foreign students coming in or foreign nationals coming in and

01:46:46.640 --> 01:46:49.160
[Guest 2]: being here and getting a job and getting nationalized into India.

01:46:49.160 --> 01:46:53.480
[Guest 2]: Why can't we dream of that world that it's possible there are people in South Asian countries

01:46:53.480 --> 01:46:57.040
[Guest 2]: who would really give anything to come here and work and get a degree.

01:46:57.040 --> 01:46:59.880
[Guest 2]: And that's perfectly fine for us because we actually benefit from it.

01:46:59.880 --> 01:47:03.680
[Guest 2]: So I'll give you a small number, which will show you how lopsided the thing is.

01:47:03.680 --> 01:47:09.320
[Guest 2]: The total number of foreign students who are studying in other countries in 2017 was 5

01:47:09.320 --> 01:47:10.320
[Guest 2]: million.

01:47:10.320 --> 01:47:15.280
[Guest 2]: In India, there are only about 48-49,000 foreign students, which is less than 1% of the number.

01:47:15.280 --> 01:47:19.840
[Guest 2]: As opposed to that, Indian students studying abroad are about 3 lakh.

01:47:19.840 --> 01:47:22.760
[Guest 2]: So it's massive because that's about close to 6%.

01:47:22.760 --> 01:47:26.800
[Guest 1]: And that tells you something about our education system also.

01:47:26.800 --> 01:47:31.540
[Guest 2]: We are very, very fine with our students going to other countries and, you know, making a

01:47:31.540 --> 01:47:32.540
[Guest 2]: name for themselves.

01:47:32.540 --> 01:47:35.660
[Guest 2]: I mean, there is an Indian in the US who's standing for some local election, we'll just

01:47:35.660 --> 01:47:38.640
[Guest 2]: beat our chest and say, Oh, look, there's an Indian connection who's standing for some

01:47:38.640 --> 01:47:40.400
[Guest 2]: US election, etc.

01:47:40.400 --> 01:47:44.800
[Guest 2]: But when it comes to them coming here, we have all these long pages of restrictions

01:47:44.800 --> 01:47:46.400
[Guest 2]: and no, you cannot do this, you cannot do that.

01:47:46.400 --> 01:47:47.400
[Guest 2]: But why?

01:47:47.400 --> 01:47:50.960
[Guest 2]: I mean, why can't we just open up and say, fine, come here, get a degree, get a job and

01:47:50.960 --> 01:47:53.020
[Guest 2]: become Indian, get an Indian citizenship.

01:47:53.020 --> 01:47:56.200
[Guest 2]: So I absolutely don't understand why we haven't done it.

01:47:56.200 --> 01:47:57.520
[Guest 3]: And I think that's something that we should definitely do.

01:47:57.520 --> 01:48:01.520
[Guest 3]: I think I'll have to rephrase what I said in the sense that, you know, when you're leaving

01:48:01.520 --> 01:48:05.000
[Guest 3]: the country in this day and age with Vijay Mallya and Nirav Modi, yes, I mean, I guess

01:48:05.000 --> 01:48:08.200
[Guest 3]: we have to be careful.

01:48:08.200 --> 01:48:09.200
[Guest 1]: Let's move on now.

01:48:09.200 --> 01:48:13.240
[Guest 1]: And Pranay Roy apparently also is on that list, because he was stopped at the airport

01:48:13.240 --> 01:48:14.240
[Guest 1]: the other day.

01:48:14.240 --> 01:48:15.240
[Amit Varma]: There you go.

01:48:15.240 --> 01:48:18.320
[Guest 3]: No, but these guys are not on the list, which is why they left.

01:48:18.320 --> 01:48:19.320
[Guest 1]: No, they were on the list.

01:48:19.320 --> 01:48:21.920
[Guest 1]: We knew when they were leaving, so we could look the other way.

01:48:21.920 --> 01:48:23.840
[Amit Varma]: Let's move on now to reform number eight.

01:48:23.840 --> 01:48:25.240
[Amit Varma]: And it's my turn again.

01:48:25.240 --> 01:48:26.240
[Amit Varma]: And this is a pet reform.

01:48:26.240 --> 01:48:30.160
[Amit Varma]: And it's actually a reform I feel really, really strongly about.

01:48:30.160 --> 01:48:33.520
[Amit Varma]: And the reform very simply is abolish family planning.

01:48:33.520 --> 01:48:40.360
[Amit Varma]: I think population control is one of the absolute worst ideas of modern India.

01:48:40.360 --> 01:48:43.760
[Amit Varma]: And this is at two levels.

01:48:43.760 --> 01:48:47.640
[Amit Varma]: It's at what I would say a consequential level and a deontological level.

01:48:47.640 --> 01:48:48.640
[Amit Varma]: Let me explain both.

01:48:48.640 --> 01:48:55.360
[Amit Varma]: One, there is this kind of zero sum thinking where, started, of course, famously by Malthus

01:48:55.360 --> 01:49:01.400
[Amit Varma]: and now called Malthusian, where the sense is that there are only so many natural resources,

01:49:01.400 --> 01:49:04.440
[Amit Varma]: we are going to run out of them if there are too many people.

01:49:04.440 --> 01:49:07.480
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, we have to do population control.

01:49:07.480 --> 01:49:12.000
[Amit Varma]: And what this completely ignores, and this has been proven completely false over the

01:49:12.000 --> 01:49:14.040
[Amit Varma]: centuries, but the myth still persists.

01:49:14.040 --> 01:49:18.880
[Amit Varma]: And what this completely ignores is that human beings are, in the words of the economist

01:49:18.880 --> 01:49:21.960
[Amit Varma]: Julian Simon, the ultimate resource.

01:49:21.960 --> 01:49:27.880
[Amit Varma]: And what typically happens is that the more the population density anywhere, the greater

01:49:27.880 --> 01:49:29.880
[Amit Varma]: the prosperity that you're likely to see.

01:49:29.880 --> 01:49:33.880
[Amit Varma]: You see this at the level of countries where you have countries like Bahrain and Monaco,

01:49:33.880 --> 01:49:37.780
[Amit Varma]: which have far greater population density than say Bangladesh or India.

01:49:37.780 --> 01:49:43.360
[Amit Varma]: You see this within any country, where the most prosperous parts of a country are those

01:49:43.360 --> 01:49:47.960
[Amit Varma]: parts with the greatest population density, which is why cities are the richest parts

01:49:47.960 --> 01:49:52.680
[Amit Varma]: of any country and the history of humankind is a history of urbanization.

01:49:52.680 --> 01:49:58.400
[Amit Varma]: People move from less populated areas to more populated areas because you get the chance

01:49:58.400 --> 01:50:05.320
[Amit Varma]: to be part of larger economic networks with all the benefits of specialization and division

01:50:05.320 --> 01:50:12.080
[Amit Varma]: of labor that entails and also because people are, you know, to quote Simon again, the ultimate

01:50:12.080 --> 01:50:13.080
[Amit Varma]: resource.

01:50:13.080 --> 01:50:22.440
[Amit Varma]: So with our ingenuity, we get over any possible shortfall of natural resources that happens.

01:50:22.440 --> 01:50:27.800
[Amit Varma]: And this also kind of plays to the point that Rajeshwari made about immigration, where people

01:50:27.800 --> 01:50:32.320
[Amit Varma]: might well ask that why should you let people in on a work visa when, as we discussed earlier

01:50:32.320 --> 01:50:35.120
[Amit Varma]: in this episode, there is such a massive jobs crisis.

01:50:35.120 --> 01:50:39.480
[Amit Varma]: And my sense is no, the thing is that the more people there are, the better we will

01:50:39.480 --> 01:50:40.480
[Amit Varma]: do.

01:50:40.480 --> 01:50:44.400
[Amit Varma]: One of the problems that we currently have, which seems to be because of too many people

01:50:44.400 --> 01:50:47.360
[Amit Varma]: are problems of bad governance.

01:50:47.360 --> 01:50:52.040
[Amit Varma]: Many of the reforms that we've suggested play exactly to that bad governance, bad incentives,

01:50:52.040 --> 01:50:53.440
[Amit Varma]: so on and so forth.

01:50:53.440 --> 01:50:59.760
[Amit Varma]: If people were a problem, people would not be moving from rural areas to cities.

01:50:59.760 --> 01:51:04.360
[Amit Varma]: And we would not be constantly logically, rationally urbanizing.

01:51:04.360 --> 01:51:08.480
[Amit Varma]: In fact, if you're listening this and you live in a city, you've actually, you know,

01:51:08.480 --> 01:51:12.160
[Amit Varma]: in a sense voted with your feet or by being where you are.

01:51:12.160 --> 01:51:16.840
[Amit Varma]: My second more important point, and this makes me really angry, the moral point, the deontological

01:51:16.840 --> 01:51:22.240
[Amit Varma]: point is that our bodies do not belong to the state.

01:51:22.240 --> 01:51:26.320
[Amit Varma]: We are all individuals, the job of the state should be to protect our bodies, not to tell

01:51:26.320 --> 01:51:28.560
[Amit Varma]: us how many children we may or may not have.

01:51:28.560 --> 01:51:32.680
[Amit Varma]: I, of course, have chosen, we have chosen not to have any, but that's a different matter.

01:51:32.680 --> 01:51:37.560
[Amit Varma]: That choice is something that should be made by all individuals.

01:51:37.560 --> 01:51:39.240
[Amit Varma]: And to me, it is shock.

01:51:39.240 --> 01:51:45.440
[Amit Varma]: And I'm not just, you know, I'm not just outraged by the kind of coercive family planning and

01:51:45.440 --> 01:51:50.000
[Amit Varma]: the Nazbandis carried out by that monster Sanjay Gandhi during the emergency and his

01:51:50.000 --> 01:51:53.760
[Amit Varma]: equally monstrous mother, the kind of policies they put in place.

01:51:53.760 --> 01:51:56.160
[Amit Varma]: Family planning still exists in India today.

01:51:56.160 --> 01:52:02.840
[Amit Varma]: The Ministry of Health still incentivizes local level workers to, you know, still today

01:52:02.840 --> 01:52:06.200
[Amit Varma]: to carry out Nazbandis and to carry out sterilizations.

01:52:06.200 --> 01:52:12.640
[Amit Varma]: And the state is giving incentives to coerce people or to, you know, for people often to

01:52:12.640 --> 01:52:17.680
[Amit Varma]: themselves going and it's always, again, the women who are at the receiving end of this.

01:52:17.680 --> 01:52:22.040
[Amit Varma]: Very rarely will you find that the man is actually going to a clinic and saying, chalo

01:52:22.040 --> 01:52:23.040
[Amit Varma]: Nazbandi karwa do.

01:52:23.040 --> 01:52:25.240
[Amit Varma]: It's the women with whom it's a problem.

01:52:25.240 --> 01:52:29.120
[Amit Varma]: So these are the two problems I have, consequential and moral.

01:52:29.120 --> 01:52:30.120
[Amit Varma]: I think Vivek raised this.

01:52:30.120 --> 01:52:31.120
[Guest 1]: I have a frivolous point.

01:52:31.120 --> 01:52:38.960
[Guest 1]: I think this comes from a more fundamental misunderstanding of the world we live in.

01:52:38.960 --> 01:52:42.880
[Guest 1]: You know, economists would always tell you that resources are scarce, but resources are

01:52:42.880 --> 01:52:43.880
[Guest 1]: scarce.

01:52:43.880 --> 01:52:44.880
[Guest 1]: They're not fixed.

01:52:44.880 --> 01:52:45.880
[Guest 1]: Right.

01:52:45.880 --> 01:52:49.120
[Guest 1]: And the resources aren't fixed because of human ingenuity.

01:52:49.120 --> 01:52:50.120
[Guest 1]: Right.

01:52:50.120 --> 01:52:52.120
[Guest 1]: Now, look at a city like Bombay.

01:52:52.120 --> 01:52:56.440
[Guest 1]: You have a fixed piece of land in the sense that, you know, there's only so much land.

01:52:56.440 --> 01:52:59.680
[Guest 1]: It's a peninsula and there's water surrounding it.

01:52:59.680 --> 01:53:06.560
[Guest 1]: Right, because of human ingenuity on things like concrete, right, or elevators, elevators,

01:53:06.560 --> 01:53:10.080
[Guest 1]: according to me, are the best mass transit system, right?

01:53:10.080 --> 01:53:14.240
[Guest 1]: Because you can go up so many floors in a matter of seconds.

01:53:14.240 --> 01:53:18.200
[Guest 1]: And so that didn't come because that resource existed.

01:53:18.200 --> 01:53:21.120
[Guest 1]: Human beings had to make that resource, right?

01:53:21.120 --> 01:53:26.840
[Guest 1]: And it existed only in a world where the size of the market was large enough to allow that

01:53:26.840 --> 01:53:29.400
[Guest 1]: kind of division of labor and specialization.

01:53:29.400 --> 01:53:35.160
[Guest 1]: So what we need in the world is more people, more prosperous people, more productive people.

01:53:35.160 --> 01:53:36.160
[Guest 1]: Right.

01:53:36.160 --> 01:53:38.920
[Guest 1]: This idea that Bombay has fixed amount of land.

01:53:38.920 --> 01:53:40.760
[Guest 1]: I hear this all the time in Bombay.

01:53:40.760 --> 01:53:42.240
[Guest 1]: We have a fixed amount of land.

01:53:42.240 --> 01:53:43.600
[Guest 1]: There's only so much road.

01:53:43.600 --> 01:53:44.600
[Guest 1]: Yeah.

01:53:44.600 --> 01:53:47.080
[Guest 1]: But our transit system is not the road alone.

01:53:47.080 --> 01:53:48.720
[Guest 2]: Our transit system is also the phone.

01:53:48.720 --> 01:53:51.640
[Guest 2]: And actually, contrary to perception, India has a lot of land.

01:53:51.640 --> 01:53:53.320
[Guest 1]: Land is not a problem.

01:53:53.320 --> 01:53:55.640
[Guest 1]: No, but in Bombay, you'll see, right?

01:53:55.640 --> 01:53:57.080
[Amit Varma]: Like there's nowhere to expand.

01:53:57.080 --> 01:53:58.080
[Amit Varma]: Digression, digression.

01:53:58.080 --> 01:54:01.680
[Guest 1]: But it's not about the land alone.

01:54:01.680 --> 01:54:04.280
[Guest 1]: I mean, there are only seven musical notes.

01:54:04.280 --> 01:54:07.200
[Guest 1]: And yet we manage to produce more and more tunes.

01:54:07.200 --> 01:54:11.360
[Guest 1]: So the idea is there is human beings are the resource.

01:54:11.360 --> 01:54:12.360
[Guest 1]: Why?

01:54:12.360 --> 01:54:14.480
[Guest 1]: Because their skill and productivity is the resource.

01:54:14.480 --> 01:54:19.440
[Guest 1]: So the resources are finite as long as human beings and the ingenuity is finite, which

01:54:19.440 --> 01:54:20.920
[Guest 1]: thankfully it is not.

01:54:20.920 --> 01:54:21.920
[Unknown]: Right.

01:54:21.920 --> 01:54:28.400
[Guest 1]: So it comes from a planning control mindset that resources are fixed, right?

01:54:28.400 --> 01:54:33.200
[Guest 1]: Because there is no incentive for those people to innovate on how you use those resources.

01:54:33.200 --> 01:54:34.360
[Guest 1]: So this is a really big problem.

01:54:34.360 --> 01:54:39.200
[Guest 1]: So if you look at like Paul Romer and all the new, you know, endogenous growth theory

01:54:39.200 --> 01:54:40.200
[Guest 1]: and so on and so forth.

01:54:40.200 --> 01:54:43.720
[Guest 1]: Earlier, there was this idea that growth is a function of some lever you pull, right?

01:54:43.720 --> 01:54:45.720
[Guest 1]: Some exogenous shock will happen.

01:54:45.720 --> 01:54:49.600
[Guest 1]: You'll get this spurt of growth and that'll, you know, there'll be some spillover effect

01:54:49.600 --> 01:54:50.640
[Guest 1]: and that's it.

01:54:50.640 --> 01:54:55.680
[Guest 1]: But what you talked about cities, cities are endogenous growth engines, right?

01:54:55.680 --> 01:55:01.680
[Guest 1]: There is growth because of something inherent that is happening when a lot of people mingle

01:55:01.680 --> 01:55:07.280
[Guest 1]: with each other in a small physical space or a small intellectual space.

01:55:07.280 --> 01:55:11.560
[Guest 1]: So and as you pointed out, most of us choose to live in dense places because that's where

01:55:11.560 --> 01:55:13.140
[Guest 1]: the opportunities are.

01:55:13.140 --> 01:55:15.400
[Guest 1]: So this is, you know, part of the problem.

01:55:15.400 --> 01:55:19.500
[Guest 1]: The other part of the problem is we are very poor on service delivery.

01:55:19.500 --> 01:55:24.840
[Guest 1]: So the metaphor for the Indian citizen when it comes to life is standing in line, right?

01:55:24.840 --> 01:55:26.960
[Guest 1]: That is really the life of the common man.

01:55:26.960 --> 01:55:31.320
[Guest 1]: So when you're standing in line, you blame everyone who's standing in front of you.

01:55:31.320 --> 01:55:32.580
[Guest 1]: That's really the problem.

01:55:32.580 --> 01:55:36.920
[Guest 1]: So this mindset comes for the state from one place, it manifests in the citizen from a

01:55:36.920 --> 01:55:41.680
[Guest 1]: completely different place because we have just failed to provide the basic services

01:55:41.680 --> 01:55:43.160
[Guest 1]: that you need, right?

01:55:43.160 --> 01:55:47.040
[Guest 1]: The elevator was not provided by the state and the buses the state doesn't provide.

01:55:47.040 --> 01:55:48.040
[Amit Varma]: So that's the problem.

01:55:48.040 --> 01:55:53.080
[Amit Varma]: And to quickly add to that before we sort of go on is what also strikes me about population

01:55:53.080 --> 01:55:58.160
[Amit Varma]: is that anyone who complains about the population being a problem is basically saying other

01:55:58.160 --> 01:55:59.160
[Amit Varma]: people are the problem.

01:55:59.160 --> 01:56:00.160
[Unknown]: Yeah.

01:56:00.160 --> 01:56:01.880
[Amit Varma]: You know, they are also part of the population.

01:56:01.880 --> 01:56:06.600
[Amit Varma]: And if you ask any one individual, are you a net cost to society or a net benefit?

01:56:06.600 --> 01:56:08.280
[Amit Varma]: Are you giving more than you're taking out?

01:56:08.280 --> 01:56:11.060
[Amit Varma]: I think everybody would say that no, I should be the one.

01:56:11.060 --> 01:56:15.760
[Amit Varma]: But somehow, other people are the problem and they think other people are the problem

01:56:15.760 --> 01:56:23.040
[Guest 1]: because of this constraint on public service delivery by the resources for which bad governance

01:56:23.040 --> 01:56:24.040
[Guest 2]: is a problem.

01:56:24.040 --> 01:56:25.040
[Guest 2]: Exactly.

01:56:25.040 --> 01:56:26.040
[Guest 2]: Bad governance is the problem.

01:56:26.040 --> 01:56:29.240
[Guest 2]: And of course, I mean, the way I see it is it's it's an escapism by the government, right?

01:56:29.240 --> 01:56:33.000
[Guest 2]: So the government is saying, oh, we have failed to do our job of providing public goods and

01:56:33.000 --> 01:56:34.000
[Unknown]: services.

01:56:34.000 --> 01:56:35.480
[Guest 2]: And therefore, I'm going to just push the burden on you.

01:56:35.480 --> 01:56:37.880
[Guest 2]: It's your responsibility to solve the problem by not having kids.

01:56:37.880 --> 01:56:42.360
[Guest 2]: Now, one thing that I want to point out here is one country that tried this for a very

01:56:42.360 --> 01:56:47.440
[Guest 2]: long period of time was, of course, China and the negative consequences of that, the

01:56:47.440 --> 01:56:52.280
[Guest 2]: side effect that happened was actually and I've seen that happen in the US with my friends

01:56:52.280 --> 01:56:53.280
[Guest 2]: is the Chinese.

01:56:53.280 --> 01:56:56.800
[Guest 2]: They obviously they moved in large numbers to the US.

01:56:56.800 --> 01:56:59.960
[Guest 2]: And once in the US, they actually started having kids there.

01:56:59.960 --> 01:57:04.820
[Guest 2]: So I actually have friends who have so their parents had one kid in China and they have

01:57:04.820 --> 01:57:07.860
[Guest 2]: actually moved to the US to have another kid.

01:57:07.860 --> 01:57:10.080
[Guest 2]: And then they have taken the entire family back in the US.

01:57:10.080 --> 01:57:12.880
[Guest 2]: And there is this brain drain that's happening from China because the Chinese government

01:57:12.880 --> 01:57:14.240
[Guest 2]: has imposed this control.

01:57:14.240 --> 01:57:18.440
[Guest 2]: So every time we bring a draconian measure like this, we should be very aware of the

01:57:18.440 --> 01:57:22.360
[Guest 2]: consequence that it's going to happen because people are not going to be subservient and

01:57:22.360 --> 01:57:25.760
[Guest 2]: say, oh, we are going to listen to it, people will find ways around it.

01:57:25.760 --> 01:57:28.880
[Guest 2]: And the ways around it are not going to be good for the economy in the society in the

01:57:28.880 --> 01:57:29.880
[Guest 1]: long run.

01:57:29.880 --> 01:57:35.080
[Guest 1]: I want to add one more thing to this, Rukmini has just had a piece on how population control

01:57:35.080 --> 01:57:39.400
[Unknown]: is tightly linked to female foeticide, right?

01:57:39.400 --> 01:57:43.760
[Guest 1]: So this is just, you know, since you're talking about these unintended and perverse consequences,

01:57:43.760 --> 01:57:47.200
[Guest 1]: I don't agree with population control for any reason.

01:57:47.200 --> 01:57:50.760
[Guest 1]: But one of the terrible consequences of that is gender selection prenatally.

01:57:50.760 --> 01:57:57.580
[Guest 2]: I mean, in terms of dense population, I mean, one example that I can think of is Hong Kong.

01:57:57.580 --> 01:58:00.440
[Guest 2]: It's one of it's the highest population density in the world.

01:58:00.440 --> 01:58:03.760
[Guest 2]: And if you go to Hong Kong, do you feel that there are no public good services because

01:58:03.760 --> 01:58:07.240
[Guest 2]: there are many people absolutely not go to Tokyo, there are people standing in lines

01:58:07.240 --> 01:58:10.520
[Guest 2]: to get into the metro in Tokyo, but then are we going to say there's no public goods and

01:58:10.520 --> 01:58:11.520
[Guest 2]: services?

01:58:11.520 --> 01:58:12.520
[Guest 2]: Absolutely not.

01:58:12.520 --> 01:58:16.040
[Guest 2]: So it's a sham that we create that because we are a densely populated country, therefore,

01:58:16.040 --> 01:58:17.800
[Amit Varma]: we are poor, and therefore, we don't have public goods and services.

01:58:17.800 --> 01:58:18.800
[Amit Varma]: That's a great point.

01:58:18.800 --> 01:58:21.120
[Guest 1]: It's a state blaming the society for its own failures.

01:58:21.120 --> 01:58:22.120
[Guest 1]: Absolutely.

01:58:22.120 --> 01:58:23.120
[Amit Varma]: For existing.

01:58:23.120 --> 01:58:27.720
[Guest 3]: So the first point I wanted to make was about land.

01:58:27.720 --> 01:58:33.440
[Guest 3]: So, you know, in Mumbai, the problem is obviously the low FSI and low FSI is where all the state

01:58:33.440 --> 01:58:34.440
[Guest 3]: government politicians

01:58:34.440 --> 01:58:52.360
[Guest 3]: I mean, I don't know if many people would know that the government of India also manufactures

01:58:52.360 --> 01:58:53.360
[Guest 3]: condoms, right?

01:58:53.360 --> 01:58:54.360
[Amit Varma]: I mean, why?

01:58:54.360 --> 01:58:55.360
[Amit Varma]: And sex toys.

01:58:55.360 --> 01:58:56.360
[Amit Varma]: So, yeah, okay.

01:58:56.360 --> 01:58:57.360
[Amit Varma]: No, it literally does.

01:58:57.360 --> 01:59:02.640
[Amit Varma]: Obviously, you know, Pavan Srinath and I were just once sort of researching into this back

01:59:02.640 --> 01:59:03.640
[Guest 1]: in the days of Pragat.

01:59:03.640 --> 01:59:08.120
[Guest 1]: I don't know if I'm more aghast that they do it or you have this information.

01:59:08.120 --> 01:59:11.640
[Guest 3]: I have this information because I care about good governance.

01:59:11.640 --> 01:59:12.640
[Guest 3]: No.

01:59:12.640 --> 01:59:16.600
[Guest 3]: So the funny point is, you know, people know that the government manufactures Nirodh, but

01:59:16.600 --> 01:59:20.760
[Guest 3]: they don't know that the government also manufactures Mood condoms.

01:59:20.760 --> 01:59:25.280
[Guest 3]: So which is, so every time you're using, you know, Mood condoms, you're basically using

01:59:25.280 --> 01:59:30.780
[Guest 3]: a product manufactured by a company which belongs to the government of India.

01:59:30.780 --> 01:59:33.920
[Amit Varma]: This is like the same guy owning a sweet shop and a gym side by side.

01:59:33.920 --> 01:59:39.560
[Guest 2]: When I listen to these things, I get the feeling that we are literally, literally dreaming

01:59:39.560 --> 01:59:43.440
[Guest 2]: here because when we are in a country like this, where the government is doing everything

