[Guest 3]: So.

02:02:06.440 --> 02:02:07.440
[Amit Varma]: Interesting.

02:02:07.440 --> 02:02:10.440
[Guest 3]: What was the name of the movie?

02:02:10.440 --> 02:02:11.440
[Guest 3]: Matru Bhoomi.

02:02:11.440 --> 02:02:12.440
[Guest 3]: Very, very disturbing.

02:02:12.440 --> 02:02:13.440
[Guest 3]: Start Piyush Mishra.

02:02:13.440 --> 02:02:14.440
[Amit Varma]: That's how I remember it.

02:02:14.440 --> 02:02:17.240
[Amit Varma]: Let's now move on to our ninth reform.

02:02:17.240 --> 02:02:21.280
[Guest 1]: And back to miss Shruti Rajagopalan.

02:02:21.280 --> 02:02:26.000
[Guest 1]: I would say, you know, I, I don't know if this is, I inadvertently ended up picking

02:02:26.000 --> 02:02:30.560
[Guest 1]: up reforms that sort of benefit or affect the largest number possible.

02:02:30.560 --> 02:02:31.560
[Guest 1]: Right.

02:02:31.560 --> 02:02:35.120
[Guest 1]: So, so that's where I was going with the, with the dreaming and the big thing.

02:02:35.120 --> 02:02:38.320
[Guest 1]: And I think the big one we need to solve is law and order.

02:02:38.320 --> 02:02:39.320
[Guest 1]: Right.

02:02:39.320 --> 02:02:41.280
[Guest 1]: And law and order has multiple parts to it.

02:02:41.280 --> 02:02:45.200
[Guest 1]: You know, we need a fixed prison system, we need to fix courts and things like that.

02:02:45.200 --> 02:02:51.160
[Guest 1]: But I think at the very least, even before we improve quality and do police reform, judicial

02:02:51.160 --> 02:02:56.080
[Guest 1]: reform, I think one way to stimulate the economy with all this government spending is just

02:02:56.080 --> 02:02:58.640
[Guest 1]: triple the police force.

02:02:58.640 --> 02:03:02.320
[Guest 1]: Just triple the number of courts, triple the number of judges, right?

02:03:02.320 --> 02:03:06.200
[Guest 1]: Triple our entire law enforcement structure.

02:03:06.200 --> 02:03:11.240
[Guest 1]: Now I'm going to get trolled heavily for this because anytime I suggest adding to government,

02:03:11.240 --> 02:03:19.160
[Guest 1]: someone calls me and asks me to throw my non-existent libertarian card in the Ganges, which is dirty.

02:03:19.160 --> 02:03:22.760
[Amit Varma]: No, but I think libertarians like you and I kind of agree on one thing that what we

02:03:22.760 --> 02:03:28.480
[Amit Varma]: need is a small and strong government that does its limited job well, and not a large

02:03:28.480 --> 02:03:30.720
[Amit Varma]: and weak government as we have now.

02:03:30.720 --> 02:03:32.320
[Amit Varma]: And law and order falls within that.

02:03:32.320 --> 02:03:33.320
[Guest 1]: Exactly.

02:03:33.320 --> 02:03:38.200
[Guest 1]: So one is, no, but there are, you know, speaking of the unintended consequences, so what's

02:03:38.200 --> 02:03:45.400
[Guest 1]: ended up happening in India is we keep passing laws as a substitute for enforcement, right?

02:03:45.400 --> 02:03:48.520
[Guest 1]: So the number of rapes are on the rise, right?

02:03:48.520 --> 02:03:50.320
[Guest 1]: We don't know what to do about it.

02:03:50.320 --> 02:03:52.600
[Guest 1]: There is some moral and public outrage.

02:03:52.600 --> 02:03:58.560
[Guest 1]: So we pass a law that will, you know, change the juvenile rape to a normal rape law, or

02:03:58.560 --> 02:04:02.480
[Guest 1]: we will change, you know, regular penalty to death penalty and so on and so forth.

02:04:02.480 --> 02:04:03.920
[Guest 1]: But that's only one part, right?

02:04:03.920 --> 02:04:07.360
[Guest 1]: Now making it death penalty doesn't mean it's being enforced more.

02:04:07.360 --> 02:04:11.800
[Guest 1]: So the women are being raped as much or as little as they were before you pass this law,

02:04:11.800 --> 02:04:17.240
[Guest 1]: because no one, forget rape, you don't get called into question or even get a slap on

02:04:17.240 --> 02:04:21.440
[Guest 1]: the wrist for anything, groping, molesting, leering.

02:04:21.440 --> 02:04:25.800
[Guest 1]: Every woman I know has experienced someone, you know, flashing her and groping her and

02:04:25.800 --> 02:04:26.800
[Guest 1]: so on.

02:04:26.800 --> 02:04:28.240
[Guest 1]: And this is not just about women.

02:04:28.240 --> 02:04:29.880
[Guest 1]: It's about everyone, right?

02:04:29.880 --> 02:04:35.560
[Guest 1]: So when you have very poor law enforcement, one of the consequences of that is there is

02:04:35.560 --> 02:04:38.480
[Guest 1]: selective enforcement, right?

02:04:38.480 --> 02:04:42.960
[Guest 1]: And the police must decide what is the most important case at hand.

02:04:42.960 --> 02:04:49.020
[Guest 1]: Now when you can choose, you obviously, there is some politics involved in what are we choosing

02:04:49.020 --> 02:04:51.740
[Guest 1]: to enforce in society, right?

02:04:51.740 --> 02:04:56.840
[Guest 1]: So if you notice, it is always the disenfranchised who get harassed the most.

02:04:56.840 --> 02:04:59.720
[Guest 1]: So there used to be a section 377.

02:04:59.720 --> 02:05:03.440
[Guest 1]: It was never enforced, but it was used as, you know, the Matunga.

02:05:03.440 --> 02:05:06.400
[Amit Varma]: I wrote a column called the Matunga racket.

02:05:06.400 --> 02:05:12.000
[Guest 1]: And this is basically, they're just harassing young same sex couples by threatening to out

02:05:12.000 --> 02:05:16.680
[Guest 1]: them or take them to their parents or take their photographs and you know, so on so forth.

02:05:16.680 --> 02:05:20.120
[Guest 1]: The same thing happens when it comes to political issues, right?

02:05:20.120 --> 02:05:23.680
[Guest 1]: You selectively enforce what you're going to do.

02:05:23.680 --> 02:05:30.720
[Guest 1]: So the selective enforcement allows the government to use the police as a tool to punish any

02:05:30.720 --> 02:05:31.720
[Guest 1]: opponents.

02:05:31.720 --> 02:05:36.680
[Guest 1]: That's one very poor unintended consequence, or maybe an intended consequence of having

02:05:36.680 --> 02:05:38.280
[Guest 1]: weak law enforcement.

02:05:38.280 --> 02:05:39.960
[Guest 1]: That's what you see in India.

02:05:39.960 --> 02:05:46.240
[Guest 1]: And now with this whole nationalist movement on the rise, people keep complaining that

02:05:46.240 --> 02:05:51.240
[Guest 1]: you know, why are these people who are lynching going free and not getting, well, it's basically

02:05:51.240 --> 02:05:55.000
[Guest 1]: because our entire law enforcement system is completely broken.

02:05:55.000 --> 02:06:00.840
[Guest 1]: We have no chain of custody when it comes to evidence that requires people, it requires,

02:06:00.840 --> 02:06:04.760
[Guest 1]: it literally requires more hands on deck and manpower, right?

02:06:04.760 --> 02:06:07.200
[Guest 1]: Requires labs, it requires infrastructure.

02:06:07.200 --> 02:06:11.400
[Guest 1]: So one part of it is, of course, as a society, we're choosing to look the other way.

02:06:11.400 --> 02:06:17.320
[Guest 1]: But even if you have good people in a system that's broken, and is like just barely functioning,

02:06:17.320 --> 02:06:20.360
[Guest 1]: you're going to get consequences like Bailu Khan, right?

02:06:20.360 --> 02:06:24.880
[Guest 1]: So I think the big one we need to solve is law and order.

02:06:24.880 --> 02:06:29.400
[Guest 1]: And I think the first step towards solving that is just more hands on deck.

02:06:29.400 --> 02:06:34.720
[Guest 1]: I know some of the laws they will enforce are terrible, but we still just need more

02:06:34.720 --> 02:06:35.720
[Guest 1]: law enforcement.

02:06:35.720 --> 02:06:41.160
[Guest 1]: We need more constables, more traffic police, you know, just the, we really need to increase

02:06:41.160 --> 02:06:42.160
[Guest 2]: that number right now.

02:06:42.160 --> 02:06:45.360
[Guest 2]: So one question that I have there, Shruti, and you'll obviously know much more on this

02:06:45.360 --> 02:06:49.400
[Guest 2]: than I do, which is that, isn't it the case and that there's research that shows that

02:06:49.400 --> 02:06:53.800
[Guest 2]: just by increasing the number of courts and judges is really not going to solve the problem

02:06:53.800 --> 02:06:55.280
[Guest 2]: of the judiciary?

02:06:55.280 --> 02:06:59.120
[Guest 2]: Because it's not that we have a problem of a broken judiciary, because we don't have

02:06:59.120 --> 02:07:00.120
[Guest 2]: enough judges and courts.

02:07:00.120 --> 02:07:01.120
[Guest 1]: No, we do.

02:07:01.120 --> 02:07:02.120
[Guest 1]: The problem lies somewhere else.

02:07:02.120 --> 02:07:03.120
[Guest 1]: No, that is.

02:07:03.120 --> 02:07:05.120
[Guest 1]: But that's a big part of the problem, right?

02:07:05.120 --> 02:07:10.240
[Guest 1]: Pendency rates are incredibly high and judicial workloads are very high for two reasons.

02:07:10.240 --> 02:07:13.200
[Guest 1]: One, we don't have enough judges and courts.

02:07:13.200 --> 02:07:17.120
[Guest 1]: And two, the vacancies are staggering right now.

02:07:17.120 --> 02:07:18.120
[Amit Varma]: You know,

02:07:18.120 --> 02:07:19.120
[Amit Varma]: But can I add to a question?

02:07:19.120 --> 02:07:22.640
[Amit Varma]: I mean, just to add to a question, there seem to be two problems here.

02:07:22.640 --> 02:07:24.720
[Amit Varma]: One is state capacity, not enough cops.

02:07:24.720 --> 02:07:28.520
[Amit Varma]: And the other is wrong incentives for the state capacity that does exist, which is why

02:07:28.520 --> 02:07:32.720
[Amit Varma]: so many policemen are into rent seeking, for example, they will stand at signals and wait

02:07:32.720 --> 02:07:33.720
[Amit Varma]: to catch somebody.

02:07:33.720 --> 02:07:38.240
[Amit Varma]: Now, you can increase the state capacity, but the bad incentives are still in place.

02:07:38.240 --> 02:07:39.240
[Guest 1]: Yes.

02:07:39.240 --> 02:07:43.720
[Guest 1]: So I don't claim that just increasing the law enforcement will solve the entire criminal

02:07:43.720 --> 02:07:45.080
[Guest 1]: justice system.

02:07:45.080 --> 02:07:50.720
[Guest 1]: But I do think it helps to have more police on the streets or in the metro or at the train

02:07:50.720 --> 02:07:55.920
[Guest 1]: station to prevent basic things like right now, the system we've devolved into in India

02:07:55.920 --> 02:07:59.160
[Guest 1]: is no one's even reporting a mugging.

02:07:59.160 --> 02:08:03.960
[Guest 1]: The only time you report a theft is because you need an FIR to get a new driver's license,

02:08:03.960 --> 02:08:04.960
[Guest 1]: right?

02:08:04.960 --> 02:08:08.920
[Guest 1]: Or to, you know, give it to the credit card company to get out of fraud or something like

02:08:08.920 --> 02:08:09.920
[Guest 1]: that.

02:08:09.920 --> 02:08:15.880
[Guest 1]: So one of the consequences of just not having hands on deck is extreme underreporting.

02:08:15.880 --> 02:08:19.720
[Guest 1]: Because you have no one to report to and no one's willing to write the report.

02:08:19.720 --> 02:08:22.040
[Guest 1]: Or there's just no one present, right?

02:08:22.040 --> 02:08:24.560
[Guest 1]: Which means all your small offenses.

02:08:24.560 --> 02:08:29.560
[Guest 1]: And when I say small, I mean, minor in terms of both punishment and how society views them.

02:08:29.560 --> 02:08:31.000
[Guest 1]: They just go underreported.

02:08:31.000 --> 02:08:35.600
[Guest 1]: So it looks like society doesn't have these problems, but the deadweight loss is somewhere

02:08:35.600 --> 02:08:36.600
[Guest 1]: else.

02:08:36.600 --> 02:08:41.360
[Guest 1]: You know, people don't carry as much money as they would like to carry, right?

02:08:41.360 --> 02:08:44.680
[Guest 1]: People don't carry gold when they travel across cities to go to a wedding or something like

02:08:44.680 --> 02:08:46.680
[Guest 1]: that, because everyone's nervous, right?

02:08:46.680 --> 02:08:49.680
[Guest 1]: You don't go out late at night, you don't go to watch a movie, you don't take a job

02:08:49.680 --> 02:08:52.060
[Guest 1]: that's going to require late hours.

02:08:52.060 --> 02:08:54.520
[Guest 1]: You don't go to a university that's too far, right?

02:08:54.520 --> 02:08:57.680
[Guest 1]: So this is how it compounds.

02:08:57.680 --> 02:09:01.560
[Guest 1]: So will just having more police solve all problems?

02:09:01.560 --> 02:09:02.560
[Guest 1]: No.

02:09:02.560 --> 02:09:07.980
[Guest 1]: Will having more judges will go a much longer way in solving problems than more police.

02:09:07.980 --> 02:09:13.160
[Guest 1]: With police, there is also a fear that unless we fix the pernicious regulation, this could

02:09:13.160 --> 02:09:18.260
[Guest 1]: also manifest into an exercise where police has more control.

02:09:18.260 --> 02:09:25.360
[Guest 1]: But I think at this point, given how lawless our society is, I think this tradeoff, I think

02:09:25.360 --> 02:09:26.360
[Amit Varma]: would be reasonable.

02:09:26.360 --> 02:09:29.480
[Amit Varma]: I guess what you're saying is more state capacity is necessary, but not sufficient.

02:09:29.480 --> 02:09:31.120
[Guest 1]: Yeah, it's absolutely necessary.

02:09:31.120 --> 02:09:34.160
[Guest 1]: And it could have some other unintended issues also.

02:09:34.160 --> 02:09:40.000
[Guest 1]: But I really think we need to go towards this because we are just living, you know, some

02:09:40.000 --> 02:09:45.580
[Guest 1]: parts it's just anarchy the bad way, like, you know, the, it's just gundaraj going on

02:09:45.580 --> 02:09:47.760
[Guest 3]: in lots of towns and villages in India.

02:09:47.760 --> 02:09:53.440
[Guest 3]: So, you know, one of the things I realized, so there is, I have a chapter on this in my

02:09:53.440 --> 02:09:55.280
[Guest 3]: India's big government book.

02:09:55.280 --> 02:10:03.800
[Guest 3]: So if you look at the pending cases, so one point is that what kind of cases are pending,

02:10:03.800 --> 02:10:04.800
[Guest 3]: okay.

02:10:04.800 --> 02:10:09.920
[Guest 3]: And very, very interestingly, a lot of cases which are pending have to do with vehicle

02:10:09.920 --> 02:10:10.920
[Guest 3]: chalans.

02:10:10.920 --> 02:10:11.920
[Guest 3]: Okay.

02:10:11.920 --> 02:10:15.820
[Guest 3]: Now that is not something that needs to go on and on and on.

02:10:15.820 --> 02:10:20.960
[Guest 3]: So all it needs is essentially a dedicated court, and you put in a few young guys, it's

02:10:20.960 --> 02:10:25.400
[Guest 3]: not like a complicated reading of the law that is required there, put in some recruit

02:10:25.400 --> 02:10:28.800
[Guest 3]: a few more young judges, put them there.

02:10:28.800 --> 02:10:34.080
[Guest 3]: And then, you know, you can tackle this problem at a very fast pace, you can do it by post.

02:10:34.080 --> 02:10:37.880
[Guest 3]: Also, the second thing that is, you know, this is something that Shailesh Gandhi had

02:10:37.880 --> 02:10:42.000
[Guest 3]: written a very interesting column on in the Times of India a few years back.

02:10:42.000 --> 02:10:46.080
[Guest 3]: And what he said was that it's not like the courts are not doing any work, they're disposing

02:10:46.080 --> 02:10:50.800
[Guest 3]: close to 2 crore cases a year, which is like a huge number.

02:10:50.800 --> 02:10:55.040
[Guest 3]: But what is happening is that the number of cases that sort of new cases that come on

02:10:55.040 --> 02:10:56.260
[Guest 3]: are more than that.

02:10:56.260 --> 02:11:01.740
[Guest 3]: So essentially, you know, if you sort of let's say, you know, I mean, I remember this offhand,

02:11:01.740 --> 02:11:04.220
[Guest 3]: so I may not be very sure of the numbers.

02:11:04.220 --> 02:11:10.280
[Guest 3]: So like India has, I think, the number of judges that the high court judges, the number

02:11:10.280 --> 02:11:13.400
[Guest 3]: of positions is around 1040 or something like that.

02:11:13.400 --> 02:11:18.020
[Guest 3]: And the last time I checked, we had some 600 or something like that who were appointed

02:11:18.020 --> 02:11:19.160
[Guest 3]: to those posts.

02:11:19.160 --> 02:11:26.920
[Guest 3]: So the point is, even if we don't create extra posts, and we just appoint the number of,

02:11:26.920 --> 02:11:33.920
[Guest 3]: you know, the posts that are already there, that in itself will take care of a large part

02:11:33.920 --> 02:11:35.760
[Guest 3]: of the problem.

02:11:35.760 --> 02:11:41.840
[Guest 3]: And one frivolous point, basically, the police thing, you know, when you want to, the fact

02:11:41.840 --> 02:11:44.560
[Guest 3]: that more police may not solve the problem.

02:11:44.560 --> 02:11:49.560
[Guest 3]: So there's this movie called China Gate many, many years back, which had, you know, the

02:11:49.560 --> 02:11:54.440
[Guest 3]: villain was played by this guy called Mukesh Tiwari, it was his first movie.

02:11:54.440 --> 02:11:58.640
[Guest 3]: And there's a line in the movie which said that ki hum se ladne ki taqat toh le aoge,

02:11:58.640 --> 02:12:01.360
[Guest 3]: par hamara kameena pan kahan se laoge.

02:12:01.360 --> 02:12:07.560
[Amit Varma]: So you know, so you can, which completely goes against everything we say about incentives,

02:12:07.560 --> 02:12:12.800
[Amit Varma]: because level of kameena pan doesn't matter if incentives are right.

02:12:12.800 --> 02:12:15.280
[Guest 3]: So the new, so I'll tell you, it's really bad, by the way.

02:12:15.280 --> 02:12:21.400
[Guest 3]: So basically, what happened was that, you know, and I mean, if you, you know, in Mumbai

02:12:21.400 --> 02:12:25.600
[Guest 3]: now they've started to send traffic fines via SMS.

02:12:25.600 --> 02:12:28.120
[Guest 3]: So you basically log on to an app and pay off.

02:12:28.120 --> 02:12:32.320
[Guest 3]: Now, what is happening is that, so you know, initially, when this happened, everyone was

02:12:32.320 --> 02:12:36.360
[Guest 3]: like, okay, now these hawaldars won't be able to charge anything at all.

02:12:36.360 --> 02:12:40.400
[Guest 3]: But what has happened is that the bribes have, in fact, instead of going down, have gone

02:12:40.400 --> 02:12:41.400
[Guest 3]: up.

02:12:41.400 --> 02:12:42.400
[Guest 3]: Now, so basically

02:12:42.400 --> 02:12:44.400
[Amit Varma]: Because a hawaldar has less opportunity.

02:12:44.400 --> 02:12:50.400
[Guest 3]: No, what is happening is, so when you get a fine, most people don't know that they've

02:12:50.400 --> 02:12:51.400
[Guest 3]: got a fine.

02:12:51.400 --> 02:12:52.400
[Guest 3]: Okay.

02:12:52.400 --> 02:12:56.040
[Guest 3]: So let's say, during a random check, the hawaldar has his phone, he just has to sort,

02:12:56.040 --> 02:13:00.280
[Guest 3]: he has some sort of an app, which he points towards your number plate, and he immediately

02:13:00.280 --> 02:13:02.580
[Guest 3]: gets the fine outstanding.

02:13:02.580 --> 02:13:08.200
[Guest 3]: So let's say you've driven through the sea link a few times, and instead of driving at

02:13:08.200 --> 02:13:13.600
[Guest 3]: less than 80 kilometers, you've driven at 95, and you have a fine outstanding of 4000

02:13:13.600 --> 02:13:14.600
[Guest 3]: bucks.

02:13:14.600 --> 02:13:18.320
[Guest 3]: So the first thing you'll do is that, you know, we need to confiscate your vehicle and

02:13:18.320 --> 02:13:19.320
[Guest 3]: shut it down.

02:13:19.320 --> 02:13:23.880
[Guest 3]: And then you'll, he'll start at 500 bucks, and you know, you finally negotiate 200, 250,

02:13:23.880 --> 02:13:25.240
[Guest 3]: and you go off.

02:13:25.240 --> 02:13:28.440
[Guest 3]: And earlier, these hawaldars, you could have paid them 50 bucks and

02:13:28.440 --> 02:13:29.440
[Amit Varma]: You don't even drive a car.

02:13:29.440 --> 02:13:30.440
[Amit Varma]: How do you know this?

02:13:30.440 --> 02:13:31.440
[Amit Varma]: I drive a car.

02:13:31.440 --> 02:13:33.720
[Guest 3]: Because I talk to all these cab, you know, cab guys that I

02:13:33.720 --> 02:13:35.280
[Amit Varma]: The journalist who talks to the cabbie.

02:13:35.280 --> 02:13:39.320
[Guest 3]: The best thing is, you should, you should now drive through the JJ flyover, okay?

02:13:39.320 --> 02:13:43.920
[Guest 3]: So the JJ flyover speed limit is now 30 kilometers an hour.

02:13:43.920 --> 02:13:48.240
[Guest 3]: So when you go there, and especially during the day when the traffic is not very heavy,

02:13:48.240 --> 02:13:50.880
[Guest 3]: you actually feel that everything is in slow motion.

02:13:50.880 --> 02:13:56.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, so once I was in fact on Worli sea link with our mutual friend Kumar, late at night,

02:13:56.600 --> 02:13:58.160
[Amit Varma]: dropping him back home.

02:13:58.160 --> 02:14:00.840
[Amit Varma]: And there was a car going at the speed limit, right?

02:14:00.840 --> 02:14:04.400
[Amit Varma]: And we thought ki yeh kaun pagal hai, kya kar raha hai, speed limit pe chal raha hai.

02:14:04.400 --> 02:14:09.400
[Amit Varma]: So what I did was, as I passed him, I slowed down to go at his pace so we could look inside.

02:14:09.400 --> 02:14:14.400
[Amit Varma]: And the driver was drinking a cup of coffee, he has a cup of coffee in his hand.

02:14:14.400 --> 02:14:20.560
[Guest 3]: So these days, if you are on the sea link, and you see any car going above 80, you would

02:14:20.560 --> 02:14:25.600
[Guest 3]: know that it is a non-Maharashtra or a non-Mumbai car, a number at least.

02:14:25.600 --> 02:14:27.480
[Guest 3]: So because they don't know.

02:14:27.480 --> 02:14:31.040
[Guest 3]: I go at whatever speed I want, I should check the app, I think.

02:14:31.040 --> 02:14:33.160
[Guest 3]: You should, tumhara hoga hai.

02:14:33.160 --> 02:14:37.920
[Guest 3]: So one driver told me about his friend that, you know, his friend had a fine of some 22,000

02:14:37.920 --> 02:14:38.920
[Guest 3]: rupees.

02:14:38.920 --> 02:14:41.440
[Guest 1]: And so because people don't know, so I mean, this is the funny thing.

02:14:41.440 --> 02:14:43.760
[Guest 1]: Have you guys ever been in a car with Amit?

02:14:43.760 --> 02:14:44.840
[Guest 1]: Yeah, why?

02:14:44.840 --> 02:14:47.960
[Guest 1]: He thinks traffic signals are a suggestion.

02:14:47.960 --> 02:14:52.080
[Guest 1]: Well, it's, let us just say, he takes his libertarianism to this extreme.

02:14:52.080 --> 02:14:57.480
[Amit Varma]: Let me just say that Haidt spoke of emergent order and in a country with no rule of law,

02:14:57.480 --> 02:14:58.480
[Amit Varma]: sometimes you just follow the emergent order.

02:14:58.480 --> 02:14:59.480
[Unknown]: I have never been so terrified for my life.

02:14:59.480 --> 02:15:05.200
[Guest 3]: I'll give you some research in support of your point.

02:15:05.200 --> 02:15:09.560
[Guest 3]: So I think in some town in Holland, one of the Scandinavian countries, I mean, I'm not

02:15:09.560 --> 02:15:15.040
[Guest 3]: sure whether it was Holland, they decided that they'll do away with traffic lights.

02:15:15.040 --> 02:15:16.680
[Guest 3]: And they did away with traffic lights.

02:15:16.680 --> 02:15:19.520
[Guest 3]: And the accident rates, in fact, came down.

02:15:19.520 --> 02:15:23.440
[Guest 3]: Because now, you know, everyone was driving even more carefully to ensure that they don't

02:15:23.440 --> 02:15:24.440
[Guest 3]: that's interesting.

02:15:24.440 --> 02:15:26.600
[Amit Varma]: But I have to say, I mean, I'm not that extreme.

02:15:26.600 --> 02:15:31.120
[Guest 3]: I do believe in traffic lights and for all my listeners is a great all your you know,

02:15:31.120 --> 02:15:33.240
[Guest 3]: the fact that you're libertarian.

02:15:33.240 --> 02:15:37.160
[Amit Varma]: So maybe for all my listeners is a great book called Traffic by Tom Vanderbilt.

02:15:37.160 --> 02:15:38.160
[Amit Varma]: Check that out.

02:15:38.160 --> 02:15:43.320
[Amit Varma]: Lots of interesting insights such as the majority of accidents tend to happen when you're close

02:15:43.320 --> 02:15:44.720
[Amit Varma]: to home, which is very interesting.

02:15:44.720 --> 02:15:45.720
[Amit Varma]: I didn't know that.

02:15:45.720 --> 02:15:49.160
[Amit Varma]: So you go on a long journey, but the accident probably won't happen throughout the journey.

02:15:49.160 --> 02:15:53.320
[Amit Varma]: But just when you're about to get home, possibly because you let your guard down, let's move

02:15:53.320 --> 02:15:54.320
[Guest 3]: on.

02:15:54.320 --> 02:15:57.840
[Amit Varma]: So when you don't know where you're going, so we do know where we are going.

02:15:57.840 --> 02:16:01.760
[Amit Varma]: We are now moving on to reform number 11.

02:16:01.760 --> 02:16:05.400
[Guest 1]: Okay, which is 1010 which is 1010 not 11.

02:16:05.400 --> 02:16:09.840
[Amit Varma]: I mean, the counting doesn't matter.

02:16:09.840 --> 02:16:10.840
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:16:10.840 --> 02:16:17.280
[Amit Varma]: Like you famously said, forget fiscal federalism, we can't count.

02:16:17.280 --> 02:16:19.200
[Amit Varma]: That's like the quote of the episode, right?

02:16:19.200 --> 02:16:20.200
[Guest 1]: It's nice.

02:16:20.200 --> 02:16:21.200
[Guest 1]: Absolutely.

02:16:21.200 --> 02:16:22.720
[Guest 3]: I'm sure Vivek will come up with something better.

02:16:22.720 --> 02:16:26.400
[Guest 3]: No, I will come up with something better, but it will only be borrowed.

02:16:26.400 --> 02:16:29.080
[Guest 3]: It won't be original.

02:16:29.080 --> 02:16:31.600
[Guest 3]: And kindly give reason.

02:16:31.600 --> 02:16:37.480
[Guest 3]: So no, I mean, the final, the third thing I wanted to talk about is basically India's

02:16:37.480 --> 02:16:41.920
[Guest 3]: big government, on which I have, I wrote a 800 page tome.

02:16:41.920 --> 02:16:44.200
[Guest 1]: It's a very fine book.

02:16:44.200 --> 02:16:49.360
[Guest 3]: One of my friends called it very recently, you know, we were talking that, you know,

02:16:49.360 --> 02:16:53.440
[Guest 3]: I'm writing this new book and all that and he said, Kripya, is bar hati ka bacha nahi

02:16:53.440 --> 02:16:54.440
[Amit Varma]: likhiyega.

02:16:54.440 --> 02:16:57.200
[Amit Varma]: It's less of a book and more of a murder weapon.

02:16:57.200 --> 02:17:02.480
[Amit Varma]: I mean, if you eventually write crime fiction as friends like me persuade you to do so,

02:17:02.480 --> 02:17:06.120
[Amit Varma]: your own book can feature as a murder weapon in the book.

02:17:06.120 --> 02:17:08.880
[Guest 1]: The print in that book is really small.

02:17:08.880 --> 02:17:09.880
[Guest 1]: I have to point out.

02:17:09.880 --> 02:17:10.880
[Amit Varma]: It's small.

02:17:10.880 --> 02:17:11.880
[Amit Varma]: But let us not intimidate readers.

02:17:11.880 --> 02:17:15.600
[Guest 1]: It's just a large book, but it's very well written.

02:17:15.600 --> 02:17:16.600
[Unknown]: It's a page turner.

02:17:16.600 --> 02:17:17.600
[Guest 3]: I strongly recommend.

02:17:17.600 --> 02:17:22.600
[Guest 3]: It has some great, hilarious examples, which is why I'm the only one who's read it.

02:17:22.600 --> 02:17:31.720
[Guest 3]: What I'm trying to say is that the key theme in the book is that India has a big government,

02:17:31.720 --> 02:17:37.680
[Guest 3]: but not in terms of the number of people it employs, but in terms of what it hopes to

02:17:37.680 --> 02:17:38.680
[Guest 3]: achieve.

02:17:38.680 --> 02:17:42.760
[Guest 3]: I mean, or, you know, the technical term of, you know, for which is state capacity, as

02:17:42.760 --> 02:17:43.760
[Guest 3]: we say.

02:17:43.760 --> 02:17:48.360
[Guest 3]: So I think, you know, we need to sort of I mean, because we're talking about dream reforms

02:17:48.360 --> 02:17:49.360
[Guest 3]: here.

02:17:49.360 --> 02:17:53.640
[Guest 3]: So my dream is that the Indian government will get out of, you know, most of the things

02:17:53.640 --> 02:17:59.400
[Guest 3]: that it does and concentrate on five, six things, you know, defense, external affairs,

02:17:59.400 --> 02:18:07.400
[Guest 3]: agriculture, probably education, and so on and so forth, and health and not try to run

02:18:07.400 --> 02:18:12.320
[Guest 3]: Air India or Hindustan Photo Films for that matter.

02:18:12.320 --> 02:18:20.280
[Guest 3]: So manufacture sex toys, manufacture condoms, or, in fact, we even manufacture six-seaters.

02:18:20.280 --> 02:18:21.280
[Guest 3]: So there are seven-seaters.

02:18:21.280 --> 02:18:26.360
[Guest 3]: We have a company, we as taxpayers own a company called Hindustan Scooters Limited, which once

02:18:26.360 --> 02:18:30.600
[Guest 3]: upon a time used to produce the Vijay Super, and given that they don't produce the Vijay

02:18:30.600 --> 02:18:36.360
[Guest 3]: Super anymore, but what they produce is a seven-seater called Vikram.

02:18:36.360 --> 02:18:39.360
[Guest 3]: If you've, you know, ever traveled through this, you know, streets.

02:18:39.360 --> 02:18:42.360
[Guest 2]: See, the government is contradicting itself.

02:18:42.360 --> 02:18:46.600
[Guest 3]: On one hand, you're encouraging family planning, on the other hand, you're manufacturing seven-seaters.

02:18:46.600 --> 02:18:52.360
[Guest 3]: So yeah, so the government should sort of get out of all these things.

02:18:52.360 --> 02:18:56.800
[Guest 3]: I mean, like, you know, even before I came here, I was reading, you know, the news, in

02:18:56.800 --> 02:19:02.360
[Guest 3]: the newspaper today, there was this news about how Air India has asked, you know, the government

02:19:02.360 --> 02:19:04.360
[Guest 3]: again for money, you know, some 2,000 odd crores.

02:19:04.360 --> 02:19:08.360
[Guest 3]: Now, I mean, it's not, I mean, why should a government be running an airline?

02:19:08.360 --> 02:19:13.360
[Guest 3]: I mean, nowhere in the world does, at least not in the developed world, maybe in the developing

02:19:13.360 --> 02:19:14.720
[Guest 3]: world, they still do.

02:19:14.720 --> 02:19:16.640
[Guest 3]: So the government should not be running an airline.

02:19:16.640 --> 02:19:19.120
[Guest 3]: The government should not be making condoms.

02:19:19.120 --> 02:19:22.400
[Guest 3]: The government should not be making seven-seaters.

02:19:22.400 --> 02:19:27.680
[Guest 3]: The government should be, I mean, as far as banking is concerned, I think that, you know,

02:19:27.680 --> 02:19:31.880
[Guest 3]: if they want to be in banking, they should probably run five, six big banks, and then

02:19:31.880 --> 02:19:34.360
[Guest 3]: just sell off the, or just shut it down.

02:19:34.360 --> 02:19:38.480
[Guest 3]: I mean, you know, if a bank like Indian Overseas Bank shuts down, nothing is going to happen

02:19:38.480 --> 02:19:40.520
[Guest 3]: to the state of the Indian economy.

02:19:40.520 --> 02:19:45.760
[Guest 3]: I mean, or if you look at a bank like Bank of Maharashtra, I mean, it could possibly

02:19:45.760 --> 02:19:49.680
[Guest 3]: concentrate on the state of Maharashtra, where it has, you know, extensive presence.

02:19:49.680 --> 02:19:54.560
[Guest 3]: There's no point of, you know, Bank of Maharashtra opening a branch in Assam.

02:19:54.560 --> 02:19:57.360
[Guest 3]: It just doesn't make any sense.

02:19:57.360 --> 02:19:59.920
[Guest 3]: Or look at the Jammu and Kashmir Bank.

02:19:59.920 --> 02:20:06.260
[Guest 3]: By far the best example, Jammu and Kashmir Bank is not a, it's not a nationalized bank.

02:20:06.260 --> 02:20:11.480
[Guest 3]: It has branches in the state of Jammu and Kashmir, has access to, you know, a lot of

02:20:11.480 --> 02:20:14.560
[Guest 3]: deposits, and then, you know, it lends that money.

02:20:14.560 --> 02:20:18.960
[Guest 3]: So you need that kind of model, like Dena Bank, once upon a time, used to be pretty

02:20:18.960 --> 02:20:21.680
[Guest 3]: good at trade finance.

02:20:21.680 --> 02:20:25.600
[Guest 3]: So it could have specialized and continued to be in that space instead of being, you

02:20:25.600 --> 02:20:30.640
[Guest 3]: know, merged away with Bank of Baroda, so as to hide its bad loans rate, very, very

02:20:30.640 --> 02:20:32.920
[Guest 3]: high bad loans rate of 22%.

02:20:32.920 --> 02:20:39.520
[Guest 3]: So all this merger-sharjah is basically, again, you know, it's essentially trying to hide

02:20:39.520 --> 02:20:44.040
[Guest 3]: the bad loans of the bad banks, and it's not going to help in any way.

02:20:44.040 --> 02:20:48.560
[Guest 3]: Like when is State Bank of India, I mean, by far the best example, before the merger

02:20:48.560 --> 02:20:56.920
[Guest 3]: with its five associate banks and Bharatiya Mahila Bank, had a bad loans rate of something

02:20:56.920 --> 02:20:59.920
[Guest 3]: around 7.2% or something.

02:20:59.920 --> 02:21:06.040
[Guest 3]: And after the merger, the rate increased to 10%, because all these banks came up with

02:21:06.040 --> 02:21:07.120
[Guest 3]: their bad loans.

02:21:07.120 --> 02:21:12.400
[Guest 3]: So State Bank essentially cleaned up its book, and then had to start cleaning it all over

02:21:12.400 --> 02:21:13.400
[Amit Varma]: again.

02:21:13.400 --> 02:21:14.400
[Amit Varma]: You know, it's still in the red.

02:21:14.400 --> 02:21:18.400
[Amit Varma]: Since you were mentioning bad loans, a bad joke, which is that if there is a bank called

02:21:18.400 --> 02:21:22.720
[Guest 3]: Dena Bank, should there not be a collection agency called Vapas Lena Collection Agency

02:21:22.720 --> 02:21:23.720
[Guest 3]: anyway?

02:21:23.720 --> 02:21:25.400
[Amit Varma]: Lena Bank.

02:21:25.400 --> 02:21:26.400
[Guest 3]: Moving on.

02:21:26.400 --> 02:21:27.400
[Guest 3]: Yeah.

02:21:27.400 --> 02:21:29.960
[Guest 3]: So I mean, I think, again, I mean, this is this is a dream thing.

02:21:29.960 --> 02:21:35.840
[Guest 3]: So the government should restrict its ambitions and, you know, get and but I said this will

02:21:35.840 --> 02:21:41.720
[Guest 3]: not be possible because, you know, every PSU reports to a government ministry and which

02:21:41.720 --> 02:21:44.520
[Guest 3]: is what gives them the importance that they have.

02:21:44.520 --> 02:21:48.080
[Guest 3]: I mean, so something like, if you take away Air India, you don't require the Ministry

02:21:48.080 --> 02:21:49.080
[Guest 3]: of Civil Aviation.

02:21:49.080 --> 02:21:52.720
[Amit Varma]: No, in fact, that's what I was about to say that I think your instincts are all in the

02:21:52.720 --> 02:21:53.720
[Amit Varma]: right direction.

02:21:53.720 --> 02:21:54.720
[Amit Varma]: But they do not go far enough.

02:21:54.720 --> 02:21:58.480
[Amit Varma]: Like, you named more ministries than I would have as being justified.

02:21:58.480 --> 02:22:01.120
[Amit Varma]: And you said ki chhe saath bank toh rehne chahiye.

02:22:01.120 --> 02:22:05.680
[Guest 3]: No, in the sense, no, what I'm trying to say is that see, my, you know, over the years,

02:22:05.680 --> 02:22:12.520
[Guest 3]: what I've realized is that there is, there is there is economics, which is right, which

02:22:12.520 --> 02:22:13.520
[Guest 3]: is the right thing to do.

02:22:13.520 --> 02:22:18.400
[Guest 3]: And then there are then there is economics, which is saleable, feasible, yeah, but we're

02:22:18.400 --> 02:22:19.400
[Guest 3]: dreaming now, you know, talking.

02:22:19.400 --> 02:22:23.320
[Guest 3]: So no, so I'm saying the good thing to do is to get out of everything.

02:22:23.320 --> 02:22:27.760
[Guest 3]: But then if that's not possible, let's say you want to meet your social targets, and

02:22:27.760 --> 02:22:30.240
[Guest 3]: you want people to open Jan Dhan accounts.

02:22:30.240 --> 02:22:34.360
[Guest 3]: And by the way, talking about Jan Dhan accounts, there are some 36 crore Jan Dhan accounts

02:22:34.360 --> 02:22:37.160
[Guest 3]: now, and India has 25 crore households.

02:22:37.160 --> 02:22:41.120
[Guest 3]: So we have opened enough Jan Dhan accounts.

02:22:41.120 --> 02:22:45.120
[Guest 3]: So you know, on an average, it's more than one per family, which is good enough.

02:22:45.120 --> 02:22:49.040
[Guest 2]: So I have a point, which is sort of again, echoing what Amit said is, you know, since

02:22:49.040 --> 02:22:52.760
[Guest 2]: we're in the dream world, if you if you allow the government to be in one field, the government

02:22:52.760 --> 02:22:56.760
[Guest 2]: will not balance itself and say, we'll just open five banks and not open 25.

02:22:56.760 --> 02:23:00.400
[Guest 2]: The government will basically want to go all out and grab all the power in that field and

02:23:00.400 --> 02:23:02.720
[Guest 2]: say, okay, we are basically the Mahibab in this field.

02:23:02.720 --> 02:23:06.440
[Guest 2]: So I think in that sense, it's a little bit of a black and white that if you really want

02:23:06.440 --> 02:23:10.520
[Guest 2]: to shrink the size of the government, the government should be restricted to the five

02:23:10.520 --> 02:23:15.800
[Guest 2]: or four basic functions of, of defense and law and order and etc, etc, and not be in

02:23:15.800 --> 02:23:20.760
[Guest 2]: at all in banking, in hotels, opening tiffin canteens in Tamil Nadu, or whatever it is

02:23:20.760 --> 02:23:24.640
[Guest 2]: they're doing nothing at all just define four basic functions that the government should

02:23:24.640 --> 02:23:25.640
[Guest 2]: do.

02:23:25.640 --> 02:23:29.180
[Guest 2]: And that also addresses all the other our previous points about fiscal responsibility

02:23:29.180 --> 02:23:32.560
[Guest 2]: and doing education opening up to the private sector and all of this.

02:23:32.560 --> 02:23:36.440
[Guest 2]: So I think the overarching thing is, I think we should agree that if you want to shrink

02:23:36.440 --> 02:23:40.000
[Guest 2]: the size of the government, let's be serious and really shrink it to just four functions

02:23:40.000 --> 02:23:41.000
[Guest 3]: and nothing else.

02:23:41.000 --> 02:23:46.160
[Guest 3]: And the good part is, you know, there's another part to it that a lot of these PSUs are sitting

02:23:46.160 --> 02:23:48.220
[Guest 3]: on a whole lot of land.

02:23:48.220 --> 02:23:52.400
[Guest 3]: And a lot of this land is bang in the middle of because when these PSUs were established,

02:23:52.400 --> 02:23:57.600
[Guest 3]: they were established outside the cities, but now, you know, the cities have grown around.

02:23:57.600 --> 02:24:03.320
[Guest 3]: What is just government land, most of it right?

02:24:03.320 --> 02:24:08.360
[Guest 3]: I grew up in this city called Ranchi and Ranchi has a lot of PSUs, but the biggest of them

02:24:08.360 --> 02:24:13.160
[Guest 3]: all is the Heavy Engineering Corporation, which is located in this place called Dhruva

02:24:13.160 --> 02:24:16.600
[Guest 3]: on the outskirts, or at least used to be on the outskirts, not anymore.

02:24:16.600 --> 02:24:21.640
[Guest 3]: Now, the amount of land that company has is mind boggling, because there is a factory,

02:24:21.640 --> 02:24:25.360
[Guest 3]: you know, which they manufacture things at one end, and then there's just, you know,

02:24:25.360 --> 02:24:30.960
[Guest 3]: land everywhere, whereas the city of Ranchi has no land because the Tribal Act is in place.

02:24:30.960 --> 02:24:35.280
[Guest 3]: So you have, you know, atrocious real estate prices.

02:24:35.280 --> 02:24:40.120
[Guest 3]: But one part of the city has land, which is virtually free lying there, nothing's being

02:24:40.120 --> 02:24:41.120
[Guest 3]: done.

02:24:41.120 --> 02:24:42.600
[Guest 3]: And that's, that's been the case for years now.

02:24:42.600 --> 02:24:43.600
[Guest 2]: So,

02:24:43.600 --> 02:24:48.560
[Guest 2]: But you know, one example of that land point is the difficulties of liquidating this land,

02:24:48.560 --> 02:24:52.840
[Guest 2]: so to speak, or then using it for private purposes, even if you let's say sell Air India.

02:24:52.840 --> 02:24:57.160
[Guest 2]: So in Air India, specifically, I know this, that when the contracts were written to have

02:24:57.160 --> 02:25:00.760
[Guest 2]: Air India big buildings, like we have in South Bombay, we have in Calcutta, we have in every

02:25:00.760 --> 02:25:05.880
[Guest 2]: city, in fact, the contract actually specified that, okay, this land, whatever is being given

02:25:05.880 --> 02:25:10.360
[Guest 2]: to Air India for constructing this Air India specific building, and it belongs to the government

02:25:10.360 --> 02:25:11.360
[Guest 2]: of India.

