02:30:45.640 --> 02:30:52.720
[Guest 2]: So my next and last reform is actually very, very narrow in scope and very specific.

02:30:52.720 --> 02:30:57.560
[Guest 2]: But in a way it is tied to my first point about fiscal discipline.

02:30:57.560 --> 02:31:00.200
[Guest 2]: And this is about, this is related to banking.

02:31:00.200 --> 02:31:03.160
[Guest 2]: So I'm moving to the financial sector.

02:31:03.160 --> 02:31:08.120
[Guest 2]: So now in India, what happens is banks and other financial institutions like insurance

02:31:08.120 --> 02:31:12.760
[Guest 2]: funds and pension funds have to hold large amounts of government securities through what

02:31:12.760 --> 02:31:14.880
[Guest 2]: we call statutory liquidity ratio.

02:31:14.880 --> 02:31:16.720
[Guest 2]: That's the technical term.

02:31:16.720 --> 02:31:22.440
[Guest 2]: And essentially this boils down to financial repression, because this is the captive market

02:31:22.440 --> 02:31:24.420
[Guest 2]: that the government has access to.

02:31:24.420 --> 02:31:28.400
[Guest 2]: And the government bonds are basically something that have to be bought by the banks and the

02:31:28.400 --> 02:31:29.560
[Guest 2]: insurance companies.

02:31:29.560 --> 02:31:33.880
[Guest 2]: And through that, the government keeps on maintaining a fiscal deficit and whatever

02:31:33.880 --> 02:31:34.880
[Guest 2]: it is.

02:31:34.880 --> 02:31:35.880
[Guest 2]: It makes it much easier.

02:31:35.880 --> 02:31:41.440
[Guest 2]: And the sort of the lie that the policymakers also tell us, including the Reserve Bank of

02:31:41.440 --> 02:31:44.240
[Guest 2]: India, is that this is not financial repression.

02:31:44.240 --> 02:31:46.040
[Guest 2]: This is prudential regulation.

02:31:46.040 --> 02:31:48.800
[Guest 2]: This is required for the safety of the banks.

02:31:48.800 --> 02:31:54.560
[Guest 2]: And the banks need to hold on to safe assets, because that's just how the prudential regulation

02:31:54.560 --> 02:31:55.560
[Guest 2]: works.

02:31:55.560 --> 02:32:01.280
[Guest 2]: Now, what my reform is about is, I want to bust that myth, because this is not a safety

02:32:01.280 --> 02:32:06.440
[Guest 2]: asset, because the Indian government bonds are not the safe assets.

02:32:06.440 --> 02:32:10.800
[Guest 2]: Because if you look at Indian government credit rating internationally, it is borderline investment

02:32:10.800 --> 02:32:13.560
[Guest 2]: grade and one step away from speculative grade.

02:32:13.560 --> 02:32:18.420
[Guest 2]: So if we really want our banks to be safe and our financial institutions to be safe,

02:32:18.420 --> 02:32:24.880
[Guest 2]: it is policy adventurism to tell them to hold government securities, Indian government securities.

02:32:24.880 --> 02:32:31.160
[Guest 2]: And instead, if you really want them to hold liquid assets, they should be holding minimum

02:32:31.160 --> 02:32:36.160
[Guest 2]: double A rated or more triple A rated assets of foreign governments, like international

02:32:36.160 --> 02:32:40.800
[Guest 2]: assets, which have much higher rating, much higher credit rating and are actually safe

02:32:40.800 --> 02:32:44.380
[Guest 2]: and liquid, because Indian government securities are not even liquid.

02:32:44.380 --> 02:32:47.440
[Guest 2]: And there are also the additional risk that every time the interest rate goes up, the

02:32:47.440 --> 02:32:49.000
[Guest 2]: banks are actually incurring losses.

02:32:49.000 --> 02:32:51.480
[Guest 2]: So it cuts them multiple ways.

02:32:51.480 --> 02:32:55.960
[Guest 2]: So instead of that, you reduce, and of course, if you are tying the hands of the government

02:32:55.960 --> 02:32:59.520
[Guest 2]: in the fiscal discipline, which was my first point, you don't need to do this financial

02:32:59.520 --> 02:33:05.400
[Guest 2]: repression of SLR, you cut down the SLR significantly, and for the safety purpose, the bank should

02:33:05.400 --> 02:33:10.000
[Guest 2]: actually be holding foreign government assets, which are triple A rated.

02:33:10.000 --> 02:33:14.740
[Guest 2]: And the reason I thought about this is also in the last 10 years, what has been happening

02:33:14.740 --> 02:33:19.720
[Guest 2]: in Europe has been an eye opener, because of the sovereign debt crisis, the banking

02:33:19.720 --> 02:33:23.960
[Guest 2]: sector in European countries has been really struggling, because the banks of Italy and

02:33:23.960 --> 02:33:27.680
[Guest 2]: Greece were actually holding their own domestic government bonds.

02:33:27.680 --> 02:33:31.600
[Guest 2]: And when the governments defaulted, when the governments went on the brink of a default,

02:33:31.600 --> 02:33:34.000
[Guest 2]: these banks basically took a massive hit.

02:33:34.000 --> 02:33:36.720
[Guest 2]: And this in economics is what we call home buyers.

02:33:36.720 --> 02:33:41.520
[Guest 2]: And home buyers can really be very costly, because you are not diversifying your portfolio,

02:33:41.520 --> 02:33:43.400
[Guest 2]: you're putting all your eggs in one basket.

02:33:43.400 --> 02:33:47.040
[Guest 2]: And in India, as I said, it goes one step further, because it's financial repression,

02:33:47.040 --> 02:33:50.560
[Guest 2]: because to that extent, banks are also not able to lend to the rest of the economy.

02:33:50.560 --> 02:33:55.520
[Guest 2]: So you kill many birds with this one stone, if you say that, okay, banks will hold liquid

02:33:55.520 --> 02:34:00.760
[Guest 2]: assets of foreign governments, which are triple A rated, and you reduce that SLR so that banks

02:34:00.760 --> 02:34:04.080
[Guest 2]: have that much more money to lend out to the rest of the economy.

02:34:04.080 --> 02:34:07.920
[Guest 2]: And you also take away that captive bond market from the government, which the government

02:34:07.920 --> 02:34:10.960
[Guest 2]: very nicely and comfortably falls back on.

02:34:10.960 --> 02:34:13.440
[Guest 2]: So that would be my third and last reform.

02:34:13.440 --> 02:34:19.480
[Guest 3]: So I'd like to add a couple of points to what Rajeshwari said, I mean, I agree with her

02:34:19.480 --> 02:34:20.480
[Guest 3]: completely.

02:34:20.480 --> 02:34:25.680
[Guest 3]: And so the first thing here is that, you know, it's not like the RBI hasn't done anything

02:34:25.680 --> 02:34:26.680
[Guest 3]: about it.

02:34:26.680 --> 02:34:32.240
[Guest 3]: The SLR has been reduced from, you know, from what I remember from almost 38% to now it's

02:34:32.240 --> 02:34:34.200
[Guest 3]: at 18.75.

02:34:34.200 --> 02:34:40.800
[Guest 3]: But the bank's investment in government securities has not come down in a similar way.

02:34:40.800 --> 02:34:47.880
[Guest 3]: So if you I mean, the last that I checked, a couple of months back, almost 27-28% of

02:34:47.880 --> 02:34:53.240
[Guest 3]: the total liabilities that the banks have, were invested in government bonds, even though

02:34:53.240 --> 02:34:58.960
[Guest 3]: you know, the number should have been around 19, 19 and a half percent.

02:34:58.960 --> 02:35:03.040
[Guest 3]: So banks also like to do some lazy banking, wherein, you know, you just put in some money

02:35:03.040 --> 02:35:06.160
[Guest 3]: there and our arms interest are high.

02:35:06.160 --> 02:35:08.220
[Guest 3]: So that's, that's one point.

02:35:08.220 --> 02:35:15.160
[Guest 3]: The second point is, you know, as far as the government is concerned, I mean, it obviously

02:35:15.160 --> 02:35:18.840
[Guest 3]: is a very, very easy way for it to raise money.

02:35:18.840 --> 02:35:23.400
[Guest 3]: And given that it is compulsory for banks to buy these bonds, the yield that the government

02:35:23.400 --> 02:35:29.240
[Guest 3]: ends up paying on these bonds is extremely low, because, you know, if you start to factor

02:35:29.240 --> 02:35:34.720
[Guest 3]: in, you know, typically how, you know, thumb rule to price a bond is, you know, you take

02:35:34.720 --> 02:35:41.240
[Guest 3]: inflation and you take some risk premium, and you add it and you come at a basic rate.

02:35:41.240 --> 02:35:47.200
[Guest 3]: So if you do that, I mean, then the bond yields would not be as low as they are, okay.

02:35:47.200 --> 02:35:52.880
[Guest 3]: So obviously, you know, the bond yields would go up, interest rates would go up.

02:35:52.880 --> 02:35:55.600
[Guest 3]: So there is a flip side to it as well.

02:35:55.600 --> 02:36:00.240
[Guest 3]: But what will happen over a period of time is that because there is, you know, the access

02:36:00.240 --> 02:36:06.200
[Guest 3]: to this easy money goes away, the chances of the government being more fiscally prudent

02:36:06.200 --> 02:36:09.760
[Guest 3]: and fiscally disciplined will go up as well.

02:36:09.760 --> 02:36:15.000
[Guest 2]: And also, Vivek, there is a conflict of interest inherent, which is happening in open eyes

02:36:15.000 --> 02:36:19.640
[Guest 2]: and nobody points out is that the Reserve Bank of India is responsible for controlling

02:36:19.640 --> 02:36:23.920
[Unknown]: inflation, which is setting the interest rate, and also borrowing money from the government,

02:36:23.920 --> 02:36:27.400
[Guest 2]: because the Reserve Bank of India is the public debt manager on behalf of the government.

02:36:27.400 --> 02:36:30.600
[Guest 3]: So obviously, they try to take and they're also the regulator for the banks.

02:36:30.600 --> 02:36:31.600
[Guest 3]: That's the third point.

02:36:31.600 --> 02:36:33.200
[Guest 2]: So they're also regulating the banks.

02:36:33.200 --> 02:36:37.360
[Guest 2]: But once you take this away, then the conflict of interest goes away, then you no longer

02:36:37.360 --> 02:36:41.200
[Guest 2]: need to manage the bonds of the government on behalf of the banks that you're regulating.

02:36:41.200 --> 02:36:43.720
[Guest 2]: And you can go back to doing your inflation controlling thing, which you're supposed

02:36:43.720 --> 02:36:44.720
[Guest 3]: to do.

02:36:44.720 --> 02:36:50.640
[Guest 3]: So, you know, talking about the public debt thing, I think the government did try to come

02:36:50.640 --> 02:36:52.160
[Guest 2]: up with a separate public debt office.

02:36:52.160 --> 02:36:55.680
[Guest 2]: But it got completely squashed by the Reserve Bank of India, because of course, the Reserve

02:36:55.680 --> 02:36:58.080
[Guest 3]: Bank of India doesn't want to let go of its territory.

02:36:58.080 --> 02:37:03.280
[Guest 3]: You work for an institution which owns Reserve Bank of India, sorry, which is owned by Reserve

02:37:03.280 --> 02:37:04.280
[Guest 2]: Bank of India.

02:37:04.280 --> 02:37:06.280
[Guest 3]: These views are entirely my own.

02:37:06.280 --> 02:37:07.280
[Guest 3]: Be personal.

02:37:07.280 --> 02:37:08.280
[Guest 3]: Please make that disclaimer.

02:37:08.280 --> 02:37:09.280
[Guest 1]: That's my disclaimer.

02:37:09.280 --> 02:37:12.120
[Guest 1]: Which is what I wanted to tell you.

02:37:12.120 --> 02:37:15.440
[Guest 1]: But this, you know, this is more general than just the RBI, right?

02:37:15.440 --> 02:37:19.640
