02:37:21.680 --> 02:37:27.320
[Guest 1]: It used to be the lender to housing finance companies and also their regulator, right?

02:37:27.320 --> 02:37:30.640
[Guest 1]: And that's a dual function is a huge conflict of interest.

02:37:30.640 --> 02:37:32.040
[Guest 1]: And the same thing with the RBI.

02:37:32.040 --> 02:37:37.400
[Guest 1]: So India does this quite frequently, it comes from this attitude of like socialist control,

02:37:37.400 --> 02:37:40.680
[Guest 1]: that I'm going to be your parent, and I'm going to give you the carrot when you want

02:37:40.680 --> 02:37:43.840
[Guest 1]: and give you the stick when you want, as if I'm a perfect benevolent,

02:37:43.840 --> 02:37:47.080
[Guest 3]: I'd say more than socialist control.

02:37:47.080 --> 02:37:52.560
[Guest 2]: These are also, you know, institutions of the Raj which have held on.

02:37:52.560 --> 02:37:56.920
[Guest 2]: And also the other, the broader point that I'm trying to make is, you know, we fall into

02:37:56.920 --> 02:38:00.760
[Guest 2]: this trap of thinking that Indian government securities are safe assets.

02:38:00.760 --> 02:38:03.920
[Guest 2]: You know, I mean, theoretically, your own government assets are safe.

02:38:03.920 --> 02:38:06.440
[Guest 2]: But in practice, Indian government assets are not safe.

02:38:06.440 --> 02:38:10.180
[Guest 2]: And that's something that we really need to understand, that if you want our banks and

02:38:10.180 --> 02:38:14.040
[Guest 2]: financial institutions to be safe, you should not be holding GCECs.

02:38:14.040 --> 02:38:18.760
[Guest 2]: You should be holding US government bonds, or UK government bonds, or diversified.

02:38:18.760 --> 02:38:21.320
[Guest 2]: You don't put all your eggs in one basket.

02:38:21.320 --> 02:38:24.720
[Guest 2]: And of course, the point is currency risk, then you hedge your currency risk.

02:38:24.720 --> 02:38:29.200
[Guest 2]: Because it's now we really have to open our mindset to the thing that financial markets

02:38:29.200 --> 02:38:33.120
[Guest 2]: have to be really liberalized, not liberalized in the sense that Indians mean it.

02:38:33.120 --> 02:38:36.600
[Guest 2]: But basically have your currency hedging options and banks will hedge the currency risk, give

02:38:36.600 --> 02:38:41.440
[Guest 2]: them the option of diversifying their portfolio into multiple assets, instead of taking them

02:38:41.440 --> 02:38:44.960
[Guest 2]: into this colonial kind of a past where you only hold government securities.

02:38:44.960 --> 02:38:50.160
[Guest 1]: I had a question for both of you on the SLR, right, which is, you know, didn't go down.

02:38:50.160 --> 02:38:54.160
[Guest 1]: I mean, even though the SLR went down, there was a lot of lazy banking.

02:38:54.160 --> 02:38:58.800
[Guest 1]: Do you think it's because of uncertainty, that there's so much uncertainty in the markets

02:38:58.800 --> 02:39:01.600
[Guest 1]: and the economy is clearly going towards a downturn?

02:39:01.600 --> 02:39:05.960
[Guest 2]: No, this is this is an old trend.

02:39:05.960 --> 02:39:10.400
[Guest 2]: It's almost like a culture, you know, the banking culture today is that you hold a lot

02:39:10.400 --> 02:39:12.640
[Guest 2]: of government securities because you want to be safe.

02:39:12.640 --> 02:39:16.480
[Guest 2]: It's the safety thing is a safety thing that has been sold to us for years.

02:39:16.480 --> 02:39:22.440
[Guest 3]: What happens is, so let's say if yields go up, and, you know, they have to sort of mark

02:39:22.440 --> 02:39:24.400
[Guest 3]: down bond prices and face losses.

02:39:24.400 --> 02:39:28.360
[Guest 3]: So then you know, RBI will come in and then they'll tell them okay, in this quarter, we'll

02:39:28.360 --> 02:39:30.160
[Guest 3]: give you that leeway and all that rubbish happens.

02:39:30.160 --> 02:39:33.400
[Guest 2]: There's a lot of nexus between the government, the RBI and the banks, right?

02:39:33.400 --> 02:39:35.720
[Guest 2]: It works very comfortably for the banks.

02:39:35.720 --> 02:39:39.840
[Guest 2]: And also because they have not opened up their own vision to this possibility that you can

02:39:39.840 --> 02:39:44.080
[Guest 2]: diversify your portfolio holding foreign assets, because what foreign asset is a very dirty

02:39:44.080 --> 02:39:45.080
[Guest 2]: word again, right?

02:39:45.080 --> 02:39:48.800
[Guest 3]: No, but see, I mean, you know, I mean, I appreciate what she's saying, but ultimately, you know,

02:39:48.800 --> 02:39:50.320
[Guest 3]: all governments are Ponzi schemes.

02:39:50.320 --> 02:39:55.440
[Guest 3]: So as long as you keep running a fiscal deficit, another quote of the episode, it's so funny,

02:39:55.440 --> 02:39:59.280
[Guest 1]: if you keep running a fiscal deficit and keep going into debt, we really shouldn't have

02:39:59.280 --> 02:40:03.240
[Guest 1]: a population control policy because we need children to be, which is what I said, the

02:40:03.240 --> 02:40:04.240
[Unknown]: government is contradicting itself.

02:40:04.240 --> 02:40:10.440
[Guest 1]: No, because the music will stop when the children stop.

02:40:10.440 --> 02:40:14.360
[Guest 2]: This point is related to my first reform that if you're going to tie the hands of the government,

02:40:14.360 --> 02:40:17.280
[Guest 2]: another way of doing it is take away their captive markets, which through which they're

02:40:17.280 --> 02:40:20.400
[Guest 2]: very easily financing the deficit, which is hurting the economy.

02:40:20.400 --> 02:40:25.400
[Guest 2]: Because imagine banks are holding, let's say 20-25% of GCEX, 40% goes into priority sector

02:40:25.400 --> 02:40:30.120
[Guest 2]: lending, how much is really available to get into the small, medium enterprises and industries,

02:40:30.120 --> 02:40:31.120
[Guest 2]: nothing.

02:40:31.120 --> 02:40:35.040
[Guest 2]: So how do you do this job crisis solving when there is no money coming for investment?

02:40:35.040 --> 02:40:41.800
[Guest 3]: Which is also why the, you know, the priority sector, you know, also keeps getting redefined.

02:40:41.800 --> 02:40:42.800
[Guest 1]: Exactly.

02:40:42.800 --> 02:40:43.800
[Unknown]: Exactly.

02:40:43.800 --> 02:40:46.760
[Guest 1]: I have never understood this priority sector business.

02:40:46.760 --> 02:40:48.760
[Guest 3]: It's again a nationalization, socialization.

02:40:48.760 --> 02:40:51.120
[Guest 3]: It started in 1969.

02:40:51.120 --> 02:40:56.640
[Guest 3]: And first what they did was, the RBI for four, five years, I think in 73 or 74, they used

02:40:56.640 --> 02:40:59.040
[Guest 3]: to just give broad directions.

02:40:59.040 --> 02:41:02.800
[Guest 3]: Then they set up a number which said 33% has to go.

02:41:02.800 --> 02:41:07.640
[Guest 3]: And then over a period of time, they included like housing loans are now, you know, up to

02:41:07.640 --> 02:41:09.760
[Guest 3]: a certain size, not all.

02:41:09.760 --> 02:41:15.640
[Guest 3]: And that size, I think is 45 lakhs, which is a huge number, get included in priority

02:41:15.640 --> 02:41:16.640
[Guest 3]: sector lending.

02:41:16.640 --> 02:41:18.640
[Guest 2]: Now, housing loan, if it's priority sector lending, then

02:41:18.640 --> 02:41:23.400
[Guest 2]: Because you know, the dichotomy is we dream of becoming a $5 trillion economy, but we

02:41:23.400 --> 02:41:27.240
[Guest 2]: in every which way we behave that we are a really poor country, so which needs to be

02:41:27.240 --> 02:41:29.040
[Guest 2]: handheld and shown the way.

02:41:29.040 --> 02:41:32.280
[Guest 1]: Another thing, I don't understand the goal of being a $5 trillion economy.

02:41:32.280 --> 02:41:33.280
[Unknown]: I think that's a separate podcast altogether.

02:41:33.280 --> 02:41:36.000
[Amit Varma]: No, so what happens to Optic's fancy number?

02:41:36.000 --> 02:41:38.040
[Amit Varma]: It's not even a good fancy number, because it means

02:41:38.040 --> 02:41:39.680
[Amit Varma]: 5 trillion is a damn good number.

02:41:39.680 --> 02:41:40.680
[Guest 1]: I like it.

02:41:40.680 --> 02:41:42.680
[Guest 2]: Well, in real terms, no one knows what that means.

02:41:42.680 --> 02:41:43.680
[Guest 2]: Exactly, but it's better than 5.2 trillion.

02:41:43.680 --> 02:41:47.120
[Guest 2]: But I don't even understand what's the fuss about it, the rate at which we are fudging

02:41:47.120 --> 02:41:48.120
[Guest 2]: numbers.

02:41:48.120 --> 02:41:49.120
[Guest 2]: We can show next month that we've become a $5 trillion economy.

02:41:49.120 --> 02:41:50.120
[Unknown]: It's just a question of perception.

02:41:50.120 --> 02:41:51.120
[Unknown]: Or you could print a lot of money.

02:41:51.120 --> 02:41:52.120
[Unknown]: Or just say that we have become a $5 trillion economy, who's checking?

02:41:52.120 --> 02:41:53.120
[Unknown]: Yeah.

02:41:53.120 --> 02:41:57.440
[Unknown]: So, GDP per capita is the best it's going to have.

02:41:57.440 --> 02:41:58.440
[Unknown]: Reality versus narrative.

02:41:58.440 --> 02:42:01.560
[Unknown]: I had a great episode on GDP with Rajeshwari by the way.

02:42:01.560 --> 02:42:02.560
[Guest 3]: I did hear that.

02:42:02.560 --> 02:42:03.560
[Amit Varma]: Absolutely.

02:42:03.560 --> 02:42:04.560
[Guest 2]: Everyone should listen to it.

02:42:04.560 --> 02:42:05.560
[Guest 3]: So, that was my third

02:42:05.560 --> 02:42:06.560
[Guest 3]: You wrote about that GDP deflator thing, right?

02:42:06.560 --> 02:42:07.560
[Guest 3]: If I remember correctly.

02:42:07.560 --> 02:42:08.560
[Guest 2]: Yes, yes, yes, yes.

02:42:08.560 --> 02:42:12.560
[Guest 2]: This is the first time I thought someone's actually explained ki kya ho raha hai.

02:42:12.560 --> 02:42:18.880
[Guest 2]: Since 2015, I wrote an article where I said the actual GDP growth is not 7.1%, it's 5%.

02:42:18.880 --> 02:42:21.160
[Guest 2]: And that had become viral at that point of time.

02:42:21.160 --> 02:42:24.880
[Guest 2]: But then, of course, now, Arvind Subramaniam has gone to the next level.

02:42:24.880 --> 02:42:29.920
[Guest 1]: You know, things are so bad that the stuff economists are saying is going viral.

02:42:29.920 --> 02:42:31.400
[Guest 1]: That's how badly they are fudging numbers.

02:42:31.400 --> 02:42:32.400
[Unknown]: Normally, no one would read someone.

02:42:32.400 --> 02:42:33.400
[Unknown]: And also, GDP is not something that would be in newspapers.

02:42:33.400 --> 02:42:34.400
[Unknown]: It is the most unsexy

02:42:34.400 --> 02:42:43.520
[Amit Varma]: Very reliable sources have told me Arvind Subramaniam does not know the G of GDP, but

02:42:43.520 --> 02:42:45.120
[Guest 3]: we will not ask anyone to go on the record.

02:42:45.120 --> 02:42:48.160
[Guest 3]: The best thing is, you know, we're talking about things going viral.

02:42:48.160 --> 02:42:53.360
[Guest 3]: You know, the first forward I got after Chidambaram was arrested was, what is the first question

02:42:53.360 --> 02:42:55.720
[Guest 3]: that CBI asked Chidambaram?

02:42:55.720 --> 02:42:57.760
[Guest 3]: So the question was, what do we do about the economy?

02:42:57.760 --> 02:42:58.760
[Guest 3]: I mean, that tells you.

02:42:58.760 --> 02:43:05.000
[Amit Varma]: Well, listening to your conversation, the question also struck me that could Agent 007

02:43:05.000 --> 02:43:07.000
[Amit Varma]: be described as a government bond?

02:43:07.000 --> 02:43:15.160
[Amit Varma]: Never mind, let's move on to the final dream reform.

02:43:15.160 --> 02:43:18.280
[Amit Varma]: So we can all actually end together before she leaves, and we can take a group photograph

02:43:18.280 --> 02:43:24.120
[Guest 3]: because this is already the longest ever episode, so it's a historic moment.

02:43:24.120 --> 02:43:33.160
[Guest 3]: We have recorded an episode longer than the episode I recorded with Manu Pillay.

02:43:33.160 --> 02:43:34.880
[Amit Varma]: I have not beaten Manu Pillay.

02:43:34.880 --> 02:43:37.240
[Unknown]: He is a very wonderful historian.

02:43:37.240 --> 02:43:41.160
[Guest 3]: Yes, I disapprove of this kind of language.

02:43:41.160 --> 02:43:47.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, so my reform is basically a dual reform, and all of you would kind of agree with it.

02:43:47.000 --> 02:43:50.240
[Amit Varma]: And this again comes back to cities and urbanization.

02:43:50.240 --> 02:43:53.720
[Amit Varma]: Reform 3A, do away with rent control.

02:43:53.720 --> 02:43:55.720
[Amit Varma]: Reform 3B, reform FSI.

02:43:55.720 --> 02:44:00.000
[Amit Varma]: Now, to just quickly explain both of these, rent control, on which I had an episode with

02:44:00.000 --> 02:44:07.400
[Amit Varma]: Shruti's co-writer and good friend Alex Tabarrok, is this ludicrous law, which has crippled

02:44:07.400 --> 02:44:11.320
[Amit Varma]: a lot of Mumbai, which is basically that at one point, government decided that rents are

02:44:11.320 --> 02:44:13.480
[Amit Varma]: getting too high, let us fix the rents.

02:44:13.480 --> 02:44:16.720
[Amit Varma]: So rents were fixed, which is why you go through Marine Drive and parts of South Bombay, you'll

02:44:16.720 --> 02:44:21.960
[Amit Varma]: find people are paying 300 rupees a month, 200 rupees a month for these large lavish

02:44:21.960 --> 02:44:22.960
[Amit Varma]: houses.

02:44:22.960 --> 02:44:23.960
[Amit Varma]: Now, what does this do?

02:44:23.960 --> 02:44:29.080
[Amit Varma]: What this does is that it reduces the incentives for the owners to look after their house.

02:44:29.080 --> 02:44:30.920
[Amit Varma]: In one sense, it's not their house anymore.

02:44:30.920 --> 02:44:34.040
[Amit Varma]: Their property has essentially been taken away from them.

02:44:34.040 --> 02:44:37.480
[Amit Varma]: The same way governments, for example, to go back to my old rant, take away our bodies

02:44:37.480 --> 02:44:42.960
[Amit Varma]: with something like family planning, assert their right over it.

02:44:42.960 --> 02:44:50.400
[Amit Varma]: And what this has meant is that, number one, that there are large stretches of cities,

02:44:50.400 --> 02:44:54.800
[Amit Varma]: you know, South Bombay just comes to mind very easily, where you have old dilapidated

02:44:54.800 --> 02:44:57.760
[Amit Varma]: buildings where no one has the incentive to look after them.

02:44:57.760 --> 02:45:00.640
[Amit Varma]: Number two, this reduces the housing supply.

02:45:00.640 --> 02:45:05.120
[Amit Varma]: And what it means is that because the housing supply is so restricted, and not what it should

02:45:05.120 --> 02:45:10.960
[Amit Varma]: be, that the rents and real estate prices are far more than they otherwise would be

02:45:10.960 --> 02:45:13.000
[Amit Varma]: simple supply and demand.

02:45:13.000 --> 02:45:19.080
[Amit Varma]: The second one is increasing FSI, FSI stands for floor space index, but what it basically

02:45:19.080 --> 02:45:23.360
[Amit Varma]: means is that there is a limit to how tall you can build your building.

02:45:23.360 --> 02:45:26.940
[Amit Varma]: Now, Bombay has an FSI of about one as far as I recall.

02:45:26.940 --> 02:45:31.000
[Amit Varma]: And there are countries in the world which have like, I think New York has 15, parts

02:45:31.000 --> 02:45:33.400
[Amit Varma]: of Hong Kong have 25-30.

02:45:33.400 --> 02:45:36.120
[Amit Varma]: And again, I did an episode on this with Alex Tabarrok.

02:45:36.120 --> 02:45:42.200
[Amit Varma]: And Alex coined a beautiful phrase, which was in fact the title of that episode, which

02:45:42.200 --> 02:45:43.680
[Amit Varma]: is reclaim the sky.

02:45:43.680 --> 02:45:47.080
[Amit Varma]: He said that what we have done in Mumbai is we have tried to reclaim the sea and there

02:45:47.080 --> 02:45:48.360
[Amit Varma]: is a limit to that.

02:45:48.360 --> 02:45:50.640
[Amit Varma]: But we can reclaim the sky and there is no limit to that.

02:45:50.640 --> 02:45:55.880
[Amit Varma]: His argument is that FSI should be far, far more, let people build upwards.

02:45:55.880 --> 02:46:01.320
[Amit Varma]: And the typical objections which are made against increasing FSI is that our infrastructure

02:46:01.320 --> 02:46:05.760
[Amit Varma]: is already crumbling, public services already crumbling, they won't keep pace.

02:46:05.760 --> 02:46:11.040
[Amit Varma]: But the same objection has been used before FSI has been raised in other cities across

02:46:11.040 --> 02:46:13.440
[Amit Varma]: the world at different stages of development.

02:46:13.440 --> 02:46:18.980
[Amit Varma]: And what inevitably happens is that supply catches up with demand, and the infrastructure

02:46:18.980 --> 02:46:22.800
[Amit Varma]: and public services do well enough.

02:46:22.800 --> 02:46:27.800
[Amit Varma]: What this will really do is if you increase FSI, is because people will be building upwards

02:46:27.800 --> 02:46:33.040
[Amit Varma]: and building more, land prices will come down, rentals will come down, more people will be

02:46:33.040 --> 02:46:35.920
[Amit Varma]: able to move into the city at a lesser cost.

02:46:35.920 --> 02:46:41.760
[Amit Varma]: Again, all the benefits of population density, larger economic networks, and, you know, to

02:46:41.760 --> 02:46:47.920
[Amit Varma]: an extent less slums, and it's just, you know, it's a no brainer why we don't do it.

02:46:47.920 --> 02:46:50.240
[Guest 1]: And elevators can substitute for cars.

02:46:50.240 --> 02:46:53.600
[Amit Varma]: And elevators can, which is such a radical thought when you think about it.

02:46:53.600 --> 02:46:56.600
[Guest 1]: Well, Tim Harford has written about this also.

02:46:56.600 --> 02:47:01.000
[Guest 1]: And he, you know, in his book on 50 great innovations, do you know, do you remember

02:47:01.000 --> 02:47:02.000
[Guest 1]: the title of the book?

02:47:02.000 --> 02:47:05.000
[Guest 1]: 50 great something of the 50 great innovations.

02:47:05.000 --> 02:47:07.320
[Guest 1]: Yeah, just look, just look for Tim Harford's book.

02:47:07.320 --> 02:47:11.600
[Guest 1]: I think there's a chapter on the elevator road, it's mentioned somewhere there.

02:47:11.600 --> 02:47:15.460
[Guest 1]: Elevators are a mass transit system when you reclaim the skies, and they reduce congestion

02:47:15.460 --> 02:47:17.000
[Guest 1]: on the roads.

02:47:17.000 --> 02:47:21.400
[Guest 1]: And they are environmentally friendly, because you can carpool, if elevators are actually

02:47:21.400 --> 02:47:23.240
[Guest 1]: a substitute for a car.

02:47:23.240 --> 02:47:26.160
[Guest 1]: And they are substitutes for metro and so many more things.

02:47:26.160 --> 02:47:29.320
[Guest 1]: And so it's also a very green idea.

02:47:29.320 --> 02:47:30.320
[Guest 3]: Yeah.

02:47:30.320 --> 02:47:36.040
[Guest 3]: So basically, again, frivolous point, but now, you know, if there was no FSI, and there

02:47:36.040 --> 02:47:40.800
[Guest 3]: was no rent control in the city of Bombay, Bombay as it used to be, we wouldn't have

02:47:40.800 --> 02:47:43.840
[Guest 3]: got two very beautiful songs from Gulzar.

02:47:43.840 --> 02:47:53.800
[Guest 3]: So, you know, ek akela shahar mein abu dana dhundta hai, do diwane shahar mein abu dana

02:47:53.800 --> 02:47:54.800
[Amit Varma]: dhundta hai.

02:47:54.800 --> 02:47:58.880
[Amit Varma]: First time I heard it, I heard it as sabudana and I'm like, okay, even I like that, you

02:47:58.880 --> 02:47:59.880
[Guest 3]: know, sabudana khichdi.

02:47:59.880 --> 02:48:02.880
[Guest 3]: It's a terrible name, you can do better than that.

02:48:02.880 --> 02:48:03.880
[Guest 3]: No, I really thought so.

02:48:03.880 --> 02:48:04.880
[Unknown]: You like sabudana khichdi?

02:48:04.880 --> 02:48:06.680
[Unknown]: I am a huge fan of sabudana khichdi.

02:48:06.680 --> 02:48:09.400
[Unknown]: It's not bird feed or whatever you call poha.

02:48:09.400 --> 02:48:11.080
[Unknown]: Look, I don't eat all vegetables.

02:48:11.080 --> 02:48:15.200
[Unknown]: But I think that's a great connection that Vivek has made, let's please appreciate it.

02:48:15.200 --> 02:48:20.040
[Guest 3]: Sorry, I got distracted, the moment you said frivolous, I thought I should add to it.

02:48:20.040 --> 02:48:24.920
[Guest 3]: No, so what I basically said that, you know, if it wasn't for FSI and rent control, then

02:48:24.920 --> 02:48:26.600
[Guest 2]: we wouldn't have got two great Gulzar songs.

02:48:26.600 --> 02:48:30.840
[Guest 2]: And even that entire romanticism about coming to Bombay, looking for a place to stay, that

02:48:30.840 --> 02:48:31.840
[Guest 1]: would completely go.

02:48:31.840 --> 02:48:32.840
[Guest 2]: But what I should point out

02:48:32.840 --> 02:48:35.200
[Guest 1]: I think we would have gotten two other great Gulzar songs.

02:48:35.200 --> 02:48:36.760
[Guest 1]: Which would be?

02:48:36.760 --> 02:48:37.760
[Guest 1]: I don't know.

02:48:37.760 --> 02:48:41.400
[Amit Varma]: Something about reclaiming the skies, maybe.

02:48:41.400 --> 02:48:42.400
[Amit Varma]: Opportunity, cost and all that.

02:48:42.400 --> 02:48:47.440
[Amit Varma]: But I have to point out that in the magazine I used to edit, Pragati, we had a section

02:48:47.440 --> 02:48:48.440
[Amit Varma]: called Houseful Economics.

02:48:48.440 --> 02:48:53.820
[Amit Varma]: And I used exactly those songs to make exactly this point on FSI and rent control.

02:48:53.820 --> 02:48:55.880
[Amit Varma]: So great minds think alike.

02:48:55.880 --> 02:48:58.920
[Amit Varma]: And we are done with our 12 reforms.

02:48:58.920 --> 02:48:59.920
[Amit Varma]: That was quick.

02:48:59.920 --> 02:49:00.920
[Amit Varma]: Great happiness has come.

02:49:00.920 --> 02:49:02.240
[Amit Varma]: Shruti is already checking her Twitter.

02:49:02.240 --> 02:49:03.640
[Guest 1]: Are you checking your Twitter, Shruti?

02:49:03.640 --> 02:49:05.160
[Guest 1]: I'm not checking my Twitter.

02:49:05.160 --> 02:49:08.720
[Guest 1]: I'm just telling people that I am no longer a prisoner here.

02:49:08.720 --> 02:49:11.800
[Amit Varma]: It is so good to have you here in person.

02:49:11.800 --> 02:49:13.960
[Guest 3]: And guys, thanks a lot for

